<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Kidnapping 2ndLd-Writethru a0966 07-21 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Kidnapping, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0966,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Free Kidnapped Former Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with AP telephone interview with
Gomez Hurtado, details. PICKS up 5th graf pvs bgng, Gomez Hurtado,
son of .... ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas freed former
presidential candidate Alvaro Gomez Hurtado on Wednesday night 53
days after kidnapping him. He said he was unharmed.
   Gomez Hurtado arrived in a taxi at his home in northern Bogota
at 8:15 p.m. (9:15 p.m. EDT), Radio Caracol reported. Hundreds of
people gathered at the house to greet him.
   ``The episode of my kidnapping has been a confirmation that we
are living in difficult times and that it is necessary to look for
reconciliation among Colombians,'' Gomez Hurtado told The
Associated Press in a telephone interview shortly after his release.
   Gomez Hurtado, 69, a former ambassador to the United States, was
kidnapped May 29 by four men armed with submachine guns. His
bodyguard was killed.
   The leftist guerrilla group April 19 Movement, or M-19, claimed
responsibility. Early in the abduction, Gomez Hurtado was reported
to have been fatally wounded.
   However, Gomez Hurtado denied that he had been wounded when he
was abducted. He said the only physical problem he encountered
during his captivity was a stomach ailment.
   ``I was treated well, and when I needed any medicine, it was
given to me without delay,'' he said.
   Shown on television shortly after his release, he appeared to be
in good health.
   He said he was released on the edge of the city, where he had
hailed a taxi.
   Gomez Hurtado, son of former President Laureano Gomez, was a
presidential candidate for the Conservative Party in the 1986
elections, running against President Virgilio Barco Vargas of the
Liberal Party, who won.
   He also is publisher of the daily El Siglo and has said in many
editorials that he wants to see Colombia free of leftist guerrillas.
   Leftist guerrillas, right-wing death squads and powerful drug
traffickers have been active in Colombia, kidnapping and killing
public officials in the last five years.
   Gomez Hurtado was kidnapped as he left a Bogota church across
the street from the British Embassy. Four men fired submachine
guns, wounding the bodyguard 14 times, and pushed Gomez Hurtado
into a vehicle that sped away.
   In a communique released July 14 in Panama City, the M-19 said
it would release Gomez Hurtado. The communique, read by Papal
Nuncio Jose Sebastian Laboa, came after five hours of negotiations
in the Vatican Embassy in the Panamanian capital.
   It said the decision had been made ``in the spirit of finding
routes that lead to a more equitable society, to the preservation
of human rights and reconciliation among Colombians.''
</TEXT>
