<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PanAmHeist     07-21 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pan Am Heist,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Men Flee JFK Airport With $1 Million in Cash and Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men posing as guards of an armored car
company made off with $50,000 in cash and about $950,000 in checks
from a Pan Am airlines counter at Kennedy International Airport
Wednesday, authorities said.
   The trio, dressed in blue uniforms, entered the Pan Am building
at 1:35 p.m. and walked up to a cashier who handles ticket sales
and other transactions, said Allen Morrison, a spokesman for the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey.
   He said the men presented what appeared to be legitimate
identification cards from Armored Transport in Brooklyn.
   ``They signed for a pickup and received two bags. In the bags
were $50,000 in cash and non-negotiable checks, for a total value
of just over $1 million,'' said Morrison.
   The trio then fled the terminal, and the Port Authority police
and the FBI were investigating, he said.
   Pamela Hanlon, a spokeswoman for the airline, declined to
comment on the incident, referring all questions to the Port
Authority.
   The full name of the armored company is Vets International
Armored Transport. A supervisor answering the telephone there
Wednesday night said its owner, Joseph Cleary, would comment on the
case Thursday.
</TEXT>
