<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NightStalker     07-21 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Night Stalker,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long-Delayed Trial of Accused Serial Killer Set to Begin _ Sort Of</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Trial expected to begin with jury selection midafternoon. No
top planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Night Stalker trial has taken nearly
three years to get underway, but it may take until next spring
before a jury is selected in the case of the grisly crime rampage
that terrorized the region.
   Defense attorneys for Richard Ramirez, the 28-year-old drifter
charged with 13 murders and 30 related felonies, estimate that jury
selection will last eight months.
   The entire trial is expected to take two years. The judge, who
scheduled jury selection to start late today, has said it will be
hard to find jurors able to serve in such a marathon proceeding.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan, who has presided over the
case since November of 1986, moved to get the trial under way, if
only symbolically.
   ``We are going to swear in a panel of about 70 folks and examine
them regarding hardship and any attitudes they have developed,''
said Tynan.
   ``I will ask people if they can afford to stick around for two
years for this case,'' Tynan said. ``If they say they can't survive
financially that will be good cause for them to be excused.''
   Ramirez, originally from El Paso, Tex., was captured by East Los
Angeles citizens following a siege of harrowing killings. He is
said to be eager to put his case before a jury.
   ``He's been ready to go to trial all along,'' said attorney
Daniel Hernandez who, with his co-counsel, has filed a blizzard of
pretrial motions which delayed the trial until now.
   The prosecutor, Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin, has
protested delays since the case began.
   ``I am ecstatic about finally going to trial in this case,'' he
said Wednesday. ``And I hope we can move the trial along a little
more efficiently than we've attended to the pretrial affairs.''
   Ramirez' notoriety will be a key subject of inquiry.
   The pale, shaggy-haired Ramirez was the subject of a police
dragnet before citizens ran him down and captured him.
   His sometimes bizarre courtroom behavior fueled speculation that
he was a devil worshiper. At an early hearing, he shouted, ``Hail
Satan!'' and flashed a pentagram drawn on his palm. The symbol,
associated with devil worship, was found at some crime scenes and
on victims in the Night Stalker case.
   Prospective jurors who have heard of Ramirez and know of his
outbursts will be asked whether they believe he is guilty and
whether they can be unbiased.
   They will also likely be asked to remember the steamy summer of
of 1985 when residents of Southern California bolted their doors
and kept their windows closed in fear of the Night Stalker.
   The random killer typically entered homes through unlocked
doors, raped women, killed both men and women and stole jewelry and
other valuables.
   At a preliminary hearing for Ramirez in 1986, anguished
witnesses including several women who had been raped, told of
horrific confrontations with the Night Stalker who invaded their
homes, killed their husbands and demanded they ``Swear to Satan.''
   Some murders were ghoulish including one in which the victim's
eyes were gouged out.
   The Ramirez case has cost Los Angeles County $1.28 million in
court and investigatory fees. That doesn't include $15,000 a month
for the defendant's private jail cell.
</TEXT>
