<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Medfly     07-21 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medfly,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Proclaims Emergency After Two Medflies Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Deukmejian proclaimed a state of
emergency for Los Angeles County on Thursday after the discovery of
two female Mediterranean fruit flies in traps.
   County agricultural officials sprayed the ground in parts of the
San Fernando Valley with a protein-based bait and set an additional
1,300 traps, said Bill Edwards, chief deputy in the county
Department of Agriculture and Weights and Measures.
   If the traps catch more flies, the state Department of Food and
Agriculture may begin aerial spraying as allowed under the
governor's proclamation, and county officials may release sterile
flies to reduce the Medfly population, said Edwards.
   The Medfly, one of the most destructive crop-destroying insects,
is considered a severe threat to California's multibillion-dollar
agricultural industry. The Medfly preys on more than 250 varieties
of produce, survives in different climates and reproduces rapidly,
officials say.
   In 1981, California spent about $100 million to eradicate a
statewide Medfly infestation that destroyed $100 million in crops.
   Last year, officials trapped 42 Medflies within a
110-square-mile part of east Los Angeles and spent $2 million to
fight the infestation, which required the importation of 700
million sterile flies and two aerial sprayings.
</TEXT>
