<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Train     07-21 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Train,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Speed Train To Link London, Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new high-speed rail link to shuttle passengers
from central London to outlying Heathrow airport at 100 mph has
been approved by the Department of Transport.
   The $325 million Heathrow Express will whisk 10 million
passengers a year from London's Paddington station to the airport
in 17 minutes, Transport Secretary Paul Channon said Wednesday.
   A comparable trip on the London Underground _ the city's subway
_ takes about an hour. Journeys by car and bus can take even longer.
   Work on the electrically powered service could start in 1990 and
finish by 1993. The private British Airport Authority will finance
80 percent of the project, with British Rail supplying the rest.
   A slower direct rail service already links Gatwick airport,
south of London, with Victoria train station, one of the city's
major rail hubs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
