<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TMISleeping     07-21 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TMI Sleeping,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Workers Disciplined At TMI After Sleeping Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five more management-level employees at
the Three Mile Island Unit 2 nuclear plant have been disciplined as
the result of an inquiry into frequent sleeping by a control room
supervisor, company officials said Wednesday.
   The actions by GPU Nuclear Corp., including dismissal of one
employee, stem from conclusions in an independent report issued to
the company on June 30, the officials said. The report said
managers at the plant did not aggressively investigate allegations
that a control room shift supervisor was sleeping on duty, thus
indirectly allowing the situation to continue.
   The report said management's failure to fully look into the
allegations, as well as accepting denials by the supervisor and
discounting statements by others, led to ``inaccurate and distorted
information'' being passed through TMI management and to the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   ``They (managers) didn't get a full picture of what occurred.
The situation festered,'' said GPU spokesman Doug Bedell.
   An earlier report found the sleeping had occurred as early as
1983 and continued through June 1987. The shift supervisor was
fired Nov. 27, after the release of the first report.
   The Unit 2 reactor, site of the nation's worst commercial
nuclear accident, has been shut down since 1979. The shift
supervisor, however, is responsible for overseeing staff,
fire-protection systems and radiation monitors at the plant.
   Of the four management-level workers disciplined but retained,
Bedell said two were reassigned to lower-level positions that did
not involve supervision of licensed reactor operators at TMI-2 and
that formal reprimands were filed against two others.
   Bedell said, ``We have lessons to learn as far as supervisory
techniques. This was not handled well.''
   He said managers had perceived the problem as stemming from
``friction'' between the crew and the shift supervisor.
   ``They accepted the view of the shift supervisor instead of what
they were hearing from the crews,'' he said.
</TEXT>
