<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Clinton, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0950,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clinton Hails Dukakis as Man With Shining Vision for America</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs on Clinton speech bombing; picks up 9th
graf pvs, ``At a ... ; edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton saluted Michael
Dukakis as a man of vision and character Wednesday night in a
presidential nominating speech that Democratic delegates cheered
loudest when it finally drew to an end.
   Clinton ignored a flashing red light on the podium signalling
that he had exceeded his allotted 15 minutes, and at one point
House Speaker Jim Wright, the convention chairman, edged close to
remind him to finish up.
   Clinton was no match for the oratory of Jesse Jackson's
nominators, and the Dukakis delegates were eager to get on with the
roll call of the states that finally delivered the nomination to
the Massachusetts governor.
   Clinton said Dukakis ``has the character, the record and the
vision America needs at this moment in our journey. ... He'll help
us seize the future and make it ours.''
   Clinton got his loudest cheer when he said, ``In closing ... ''
One network, NBC, cut away from the speech.
   Leaving the podium, he told reporters that he had practiced the
talk repeatedly and it had never lasted more than 15 minutes. It
ran twice as long because of the cheers and chants of the enthused
Dukakis delegates, he said.
   ``They just desperately wanted to cheer for Dukakis,'' he said.
``They wanted to make noise.''
   In the speech, Clinton said Dukakis' ``character is steadfast
and consistent. He wakes up in the same world every day, a trait of
no small importance in a president.''
   ``He hasn't just played with issues, he's wrestled them to the
ground. He has made the hard decisions: to balance budgets, create
jobs, fight crime and drug abuse, move people from welfare to work,
expand day care and health care, increase housing and improve
education,'' said Clinton, who shared Dukakis' experience of being
voted out of the governor's office only to stage a comeback.
   ``When he needs to be, Michael Dukakis is tough as nails,'' he
said.
   At a time when America is facing new economic challenges abroad
and ``an epidemic of social problems'' at home, Clinton said,
Dukakis ``believes America's best days lie ahead. He reminds us
that we've faced even greater challenges in the past. He is an
apostle of hope.''
   Decrying homelessness, illiteracy and infant morality, Clinton
said, ``I want Michael Dukakis to be president because he knows we
don't have a single person to waste.''
   ``His whole life is a tribute to the enduring strength of the
American dream. He knows that unless that dream is real for all our
children, it is not secure for any of them. And he'll help us seize
the future and make it ours,'' said Clinton.
   ``He's old-fashioned all right: he's the kind of man who plays
it straight, keeps his word and pays his bills.''
   Clinton, 41, met Dukakis in 1981, when ``he was teaching at the
Kennedy School and I was the youngest ex-governor in American
history.''
   ``Both of us were ... given a rare second chance by our people.
That does wonders for your sensitivity to others,'' he said.
   ``He has also been a soldier, a lawyer, a teacher, a legislator.
He has excelled in all these roles because of his fine mind and his
keen interest in other people,'' said Clinton.
   ``Michael Dukakis is a man with a vision, a shining vision for
America _ a country with good jobs at good wages; a country where
all Americans can send their children to good public schools and
... college; a country where working parents have access to good
child care and health care for their kids; one where people can get
decent long-term care without going to the poorhouse; a country
with a clean environment and, yes, a clean government devoted once
again to the rule of law,'' said Clinton.
   Clinton said that after Jesse Jackson spoke Tuesday night,
``many of you waved signs with his slogan: `Keep Hope Alive.' In
his own way, Mike Dukakis will never let us forget that
admonition.''
</TEXT>
