<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--IowaMixup     07-21 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Iowa Mixup,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation Gets The Wrong Vote From Iowa At First</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation initially got the wrong vote from the
Iowa delegation Wednesday night as Democrats nominated Michael
Dukakis as their 1988 presidential candidate.
   Jerry Crawford stepped to the microphone to announce that, in a
show of unity, he and state Sen. Thomas Mann of Des Moines would
jointly announce the Hawkeye State's vote total.
   When Crawford said the word ``unity'' after announcing 49 votes
for Dukakis, convention secretary Dorothy Bush and her assistant
promptly announced that Iowa had cast all 61 of its votes for
Dukakis.
   Reached by telephone on the convention floor, Crawford said his
intention was to have Mann announce that Jesse Jackson had received
12 votes.
   Throughout the convention, leaders of the Iowa delegation have
credited Mann with stressing party unity above loyalty to a single
candidate.
   The Iowa delegates phoned the podium immediately after the error
was made, and the delegation was asked to announce its vote a
second time.
   This time, the Crawford-Mann unity announcement was made without
a hitch.
</TEXT>
