<HEAD>California's Votes Put Dukakis Over The Top</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS final graf to FIX that nine votes, sted eight, cast for
other candidates and to FIX fraction on Dukakis vote</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's 235 votes gave Michael Dukakis the
margin he needed to win the Democratic presidential nomination on
Wednesday.
   A dozen states, including Dukakis' home state of Massachusetts,
passed during the roll call in a prearranged plan to have
California put Dukakis over the 2,082 votes needed to secure the
nomination.
   In 1984, New Jersey provided Walter Mondale with the margin
needed to win the nomination.
   In all, Dukakis received 2,876.25 votes, while Jesse Jackson
received 1,218.5. Nine votes were cast for other candidates.
