<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HazardousWaste     07-21 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hazardous Waste,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Not Protecting Public Against Hazardous Wastes, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency's
12-year-old campaign against hazardous waste is not protecting
public health and the environment, a congressional report says.
   The broad-ranging critique by the General Accounting Office says
EPA has made only limited progress in administering and enforcing
the 1976 law covering the handling, storage and disposal of
health-threatening wastes.
   The report by the GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, cites
a variety of problems, including failure to meet congressionally
set deadlines, inadequate resources, shifting enforcement
approaches and lack of information.
   ``EPA's progress in regulating hazardous wastes that it has
identified has been limited and not sufficiently comprehensive to
protect the public and the environment,'' GAO concluded.
   The report said EPA is regulating about 450 materials known to
be hazardous, with only five having been added to the list since
1980.
   Still to be controlled are ``potentially large volumes of
hazardous wastes,'' but EPA has not determined what industries need
to be reviewed or how long it will take to assess the suspect
materials, according to GAO.
   ``We believe EPA's limited progress has resulted from the
absence of an overall waste identification goal and a related
implementation approach that together would focus and assign
priorities in the program,'' the study said.
   The 1976 law, the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA),
was enacted in response to unregulated toxic dumps such as Love
Canal near Niagara Falls, N.Y., but GAO said the law is not
preventing new Love Canals.
   The study quotes EPA as saying that as many as half the 5,000
storage and disposal sites regulated under RCRA may be leaking
hazardous materials and could require expensive cleanups.
   ``EPA has made very little progress in achieving actual cleanups
or in setting goals for actual cleanups because of other RCRA
program priorities and the complexity involved in identifying the
extent of contamination and the level of cleanup required,'' GAO
said.
   The study said it could take until the year 2025 to clean up the
regulated RCRA sites through an effort rivaling ``Superfund,'' the
cleanup program that the EPA says could spend $22.7 billion at some
2,500 abandoned dump sites.
   ``The longer EPA waits to actually implement corrective action
at RCRA facilities, the greater the risk will become that the
contamination at the leaking facilities will worsen and that a
number of these facilities will have to be cleaned up under
Superfund,'' GAO said.
   The report said there has been ``widespread and persistent''
non-compliance with RCRA regulations by both private sector and
federal facilities, with only about half the regulated
land-disposal sites meeting standards over the past three years.
   GAO said that while the principal reasons for non-compliance are
the technical complexity of the regulations and the costs of
following them, ``ineffective enforcement on the part of EPA and
states'' has been part of the problem.
   Compliance inspections have been increasing, the report said,
but when GAO investigators went out on 26 of them, they observed
inspectors missing almost as many violations as they cited.
   In its 1984 reworking of RCRA, EPA was given 76 specific
deadlines for taking RCRA actions by a Congress that was unhappy
with the agency's progress in controlling hazardous wastes.
   As of last April, 66 of the deadlines had come due, with EPA
missing 38 of them, said GAO.
   GAO quoted EPA as saying the report ``adequately describes'' the
situation and that officials are working to improve the
administration of the hazardous waste law on a variety of fronts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
