<DOCNO> AP880721-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan-Judges     07-21 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Judges,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Mapping Plan To Push Through Judicial Nominees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With six months left for President
Reagan to get conservative nominees confirmed to federal
judgeships, administration officials are mapping strategy to
overcome what they say is foot-dragging by the
Democratic-controlled Senate.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the matter of
judicial nominations was high on the list of topics to be discussed
today by White House aides at a planning session called by the
president's chief of staff, Kenneth Duberstein.
   ``We're talking about judgeships and getting our nominees
confirmed,'' Fitzwater told reporters Wednesday.
   The president's term will end next Jan. 20. Already, according
to many legal scholars, he has named enough judges to life terms on
federal district and circuit courts to put his conservative stamp
on the judiciary for many years.
   Justice Department spokesman Patrick Korten, however, said the
administration is concerned about inaction in the Senate on pending
nominations. Korten said there are 26 judicial nominations awaiting
Senate action _ 20 of them for district judgeships and six for
positions on the circuit courts of appeal.
   ``The absence of even one circuit judge on a circuit that only
has 12 can put a crimp in their ability to handle the workload,''
Korten said in a telephone interview from Washington.
   ``There hasn't been any action on (Capitol) Hill for many
months,'' Korten said. ``They have been dragging their feet.''
   By delaying action on nominations in the closing months of the
administration, the Democrats who control the Senate could give
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis a chance to make
the appointments in the event of his election.
   Jane Verman Bourgeois, spokeswoman for the Judiciary Committee,
failed to respond to repeated telephone calls seeking comment on
the meeting and Korten's statements.
   All federal judicial nominations are subject to confirmation by
the Senate after first being screened by the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
   Deputy White House Press Secretary B.J. Cooper said he did not
know what strategy Duberstein and the White House aides would be
discussing to push for action on the backlog of nominations.
   Fitzwater said the judicial nominee situation was one of several
items to be discussed at today's meeting.
   ``It's to go over themes, agenda, schedule, budget _ those kinds
of internal matters,'' he said. ``We'll have a review of all the
legislation that's now on the hill and what the administration's
position is.''
   ``We'll talk about any speeches or trips by the president and
what kind of themes we want, or we recommend that be discussed in
those appearances,'' the spokesman said.
   He said Duberstein had talked extensively with the president
about his plans for the election campaign and the final months of
his administration before Reagan came west to vacation at his
mountaintop ranch north of Santa Barbara.
   Fitzwater said the president has talked about a schedule of two
campaign appearances a week after September. He also said two
political fund-raising appearances are planned in Los Angeles
during another California vacation that the president plans for
next month.
   When asked whether the president had watched any of the
Democratic National Convention on television at the ranch,
Fitzwater said, ``I know he was going to watch parts of it. My
guess is he did, but I don't really know.''
   On Wednesday, Reagan signed an $18 billion energy and water
development appropriations bill that he said reached his desk
earlier than any other appropriations bill since he became
president. He urged Congres to swiftly complete work on the
remaining 12 appropriations bills for fiscal 1989.
</TEXT>
