<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BiaggiCampaign     07-21 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi Campaign,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legal Fees Drain Biaggi's Campaign Coffers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mario Biaggi's re-election campaign has
gone into debt as the New York Democrat, convicted of taking an
illegal gratuity and under indictment on additional charges,
continues to use campaign dollars to pay his legal fees.
   According to Biaggi's latest report to the Federal Election
Commission, the 10-term congressman paid his lawyers $130,000 from
the campaign treasury between April 1 and June 30, 1988. In all,
Biaggi has spent about $496,000 from his campaign coffers on
lawyers since 1986, when his legal troubles began.
   The campaign began the quarter with $37,160 on hand and
collected $16,500 in donations from four political action
committees representing labor unions. But because of expenditures,
including the legal fees, the campaign wound up the quarter with a
$17,872 cash deficit and a $70,000 debt, representing personal
loans Biaggi made to his campaign during the quarter.
   Biaggi also has a separate defense fund, but his spokesman, Bob
Blancato, has declined to make public its cash flow. Blancato has
estimated that Biaggi's defense ultimately could cost about $1
million.
   The congressman has been on trial for the last four months in
the Wedtech scandal, in which he and six others are accused of
turning the Bronx, N.Y., military contractor into a racketeering
enterprise. The jury heard closing arguments in the trial Wednesday.
   In another federal trial, Biaggi was convicted last year of
accepting an illegal gratuity in the form of a paid Florida
vacation. He was sentenced to 2{ years in prison and a $500,000
fine but is free pending appeal.
   Biaggi's two Democratic opponents _ Bronx Assemblyman Eliot
Engel and Vincent Marchiselli _ have filed challenges to his
nominating petitions and Biaggi in return has challenged their
petitions to gain access to the September primary ballot.
   The grounds ``are just general right now,'' but each man has six
days from the challenge date to specify what he believes is wrong
with the others' petitions, state Board of Elections spokesman
Steven LaFever said.
</TEXT>
