<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialMoney     07-21 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Money,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Still Leading Dukakis In Campaign Spending</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush continues to lead
Democrat Michael Dukakis in spending on the presidential campaign
trail, but Dukakis outspent his GOP rival during June, financial
reports show.
   Dukakis reported to the Federal Election Commission that his
campaign spent $1,939,385 last month, compared to $1,197,784 spent
by Bush.
   Overall, the Republican vice president has spent $22,107,183 to
Dukakis' $20,714,342. Each candidate is allowed to spend
$23,050,000 during the primary campaign, which ends with the
nomination.
   That meant Dukakis had another $2,285,658 to spend between July
1 and his nomination last night. Bush, pushing far closer to the
spending cap, had $942,817 to spend between July 1 and his
scheduled nomination in mid-August.
   Edie Holiday, chief counsel and financial director for the Bush
campaign, said the campaign will not hit the ceiling before Bush is
nominated.
   ``We're very comfortable with where we are right now,'' she said.
   Each candidate will get $46.1 million from the Treasury for the
general election, with Dukakis, because of the earlier nomination,
having to make his money go a longer distance.
   In reports covering advanced spending for the general election,
Dukakis was leading Bush in outlays, $309,604 to $269,050.
   The FEC said it had not received a June spending report from
Democrat Jesse Jackson on Wednesday, when the reports were required
to be mailed or delivered to the agency.
</TEXT>
