<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Jesse Jackson still in his hotel suite,
California Assembly Speaker Willie Brown took on the ritual role of
asking the Democratic Party to unify behind its presidential
nominee Wednesday night.
   Brown, the national chairman of Jesse Jackson's presidential
campaign, told the cheering crowd that he had just talked to
Jackson and that Jackson had asked him to make the nomination of
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis unanimous.
   Brown did not miss a chance, however, to point out that Jackson
``won more votes than any other runner-up in history.''
   Brown said he had received a telephone call from Jackson asking
him to move acclamation just five minutes before he took the
action, and that Jackson was laughing and joking in the phone call.
   ``He simply said please make it by acclamation, at my request,
and do it with the same appropriate sensitivity as we've attempted
to conduct ourselves with during the campaign,'' Brown said.
   The convention agreed to the motion with only barely heard
dissenting votes.
