<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Jackson-Nomination 4thLd-Writethru a0441 07-21
0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Jackson-Nomination, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0441,600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS final Dukakis figure in graf 4.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union leader William Winpisinger praised Jesse
Jackson as one ``who has ignited the passionate fires of justice in
our souls,'' as he placed the civil rights leader's name in
nomination Wednesday for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   ``Not since Hubert H. Humphrey has a presidential candidate
elevated the aspirations of workers and championed their quest for
worker rights to such heights in the mainstream political
dialogue,'' said the head of the International Association of
Machinists.
   Even as Jackson's name went into nomination, it was clear that
his cause was lost, that Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was the
party's choice for the presidential nomination.
   Jackson won 1,218.5 votes, far more than his 1984 showing, but
still well short of Dukakis' 2,876.25 nominating majority.
   After the last state had responded to the roll call, Jackson's
campaign chairman, California Assembly Speaker Willie Brown,
stepped forward to move that the Dukakis nomination be made
unanimous. The motion carried, with only a few objections.
   In her seconding speech for Jackson, California Assemblywoman
Maxine Waters said ``This one man will one day, one way, this one
man will be the president of the United States of America. As his
name goes in nomination, so does yours. We will all never be the
same.''
   Jackson's nomination was also seconded by New York State Senator
Olga Mendez.
   ``He has a vision of America ... his vision emcompasses all of
us,'' said the Hispanic politician. ``Jackson understands our
reality. He includes us in the common effort to eliminate poverty.''
   Bright red ``Jesse Jesse'' signs were hoisted in the air for a
five-minute demonstration when Winpisinger proclaimed, ``I am
inordinately proud and uniquely privileged to offer in nomination
for president of the United States, the name of Jesse Louis
Jackson. ''
   ``Jesse, Jesse, Jesse'' the crowd chanted before changing the
refrain to ``Keep Hope Alive'' _ Jackson's slogan for his political
efforts to come.
   Winpisinger hailed Jackson as the ``personification of feeling
and reason uited'' and for ``telling it like it is.''
   ``It is a singular experience and honor to stand before you
tonight to place in nomination the name of the one person in this
vast nation who has roused the moral conscience of the populace and
our party,'' he said, ``who has shown us the way to thaw the ice of
indifference, smug self-satisfaction and meanness that too long has
masked the heartbeat of America; who has ignited the passionate
fires of justice in our souls as no other contemporary has; the man
who has dared sound our call to greatness.''
   ``He has forced new issues, and new ways of thinking about old
issues into public view and the political dialogue.''
   ``Yes, this is a man of history _ a mover and shaker in the
power struggles of freedom and tyranny _ of democracy and
autocracy,'' Winpisinger said. ``This man knows what justice on the
job means. He has long recognized that without equal economic
opportunity and economic rights, there can be no real political
democracy, no real freedom.''
   The union leader detailed Jackson's long struggle on behalf of
working Americans, a record that was a key to his effort to win the
votes of blue collar workers during the primary season.
   ``He has seized history by the mane,'' he said. ``He has been
there with the workers on the picket lines, when they've been shut
out in the cold. He was there in Wisconsin at Cudahy with the
packing house workers. And he was there with the International
Association of Machinists and aerospace workers at Rome Cable in
the bitter cold of an early upstate New York winter.''
</TEXT>
