<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefenseProbe     07-21 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Unsealing Defense Probe Documents Would `Harm Process'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge who refused to order the
release of documents related to the probe of alleged fraud on
Pentagon defense contracts said public disclosure of the
information would ``harm the process'' of the investigation.
   U.S. District Judge Claude A. Hilton on Wednesday rejected a
motion by the Washington Times to unseal the affidavits that
triggered judicial authorization of dozens of searches by federal
agents around the country on June 14.
   The government's investigation centers around allegations that
defense contractors and private defense consultants, many of them
former Pentagon employees, bribed Defense Department employees for
inside information considered crucial to winning
multimillion-dollar contracts.
   Representing the newspaper, Jerome Barron told Hilton that ``the
massive publicity already sought by the government in the middle of
June has put all defense contractors under a cloud.''
   He said the best way to clear the air is to reveal what
information the government has. Barron also argued that release of
information could permit ``corrective action to be undertaken.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Aronica prevailed in his argument
that release of the material could tip off prospective defendants
and ``lead to destruction of property'' not yet obtained by
investigators.
   ``There have been no charges filed, no indictments. ... The
government is in the middle of a grand jury,'' he told Hilton.
   Hilton agreed, saying, ``It seems to me that release of this
information now would harm the process.''
   While conceding the case has great public interest, Aronica said
``there's a greater public interest and that is that this
investigation move forward with diligence and dispatch.''
   Barron said he didn't know if Hilton's ruling would be appealed.
</TEXT>
