<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     07-21 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Can Take `Ugly Stuff' From Democrats</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: First event is an 11 a.m. EDT news conference in Charlotte.
Top planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, back on the
campaign trail after a four-day fishing vacation, says he can take
all the ``ugly stuff'' Democrats dish out at their convention,
claiming it may backfire on them in the fall.
   ``If you just go nasty, go ugly, that isn't an effective way to
do business,'' the vice president said, while pleading he had only
secondhand knowledge of attacks on him by a succession of speakers
at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   Bush said he'd neither watched nor listened to any part of the
Democratic convention while on the fishing trip in Wyoming.
However, aides said Bush watched the convention briefly Wednesday
night and saw Michael Dukakis' name placed in nomination.
   ``This name-calling isn't going to get anyone anything. Maybe it
will backfire on them,'' he told reporters when he appeared at a
Ukrainian cultural center in this Detroit suburb, where he
delivered a speech commemorating ``Captive Nations Week.''
   ``I've got broad shoulders,'' the certain GOP presidential
nominee said. ``They've got to get in line to say ugly stuff. ...
The concentration of trying to tear me down, it might show a little
desperation.''
   Told that Democratic conventioneers were asking, ``Where was
George?'' a reference mostly to the vice president's efforts to
disassociate himself from some of the Reagan administration's major
problems, Bush responded: ``Four days in the wilderness is the
answer.''
   ``I don't want to be cute with you, but I've been out of contact
for four nights and three days,'' he told reporters.
   ``We stayed in the same tent. ... We caught a lot of fish, we
went to bed early and had a minimal discussion of politics,'' he
said of his days in the Wyoming wilderness with his chief political
mentor, Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III.
   Bush said he has decided on a process for selecting a running
mate, but intends to make the choice ``without a lot of high
visibility and show business.''
   And, while saying ``we're not in the list business yet,'' Bush
said that his former GOP rival, Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, ``would be
on any list, just because he's so widely respected.''
   Bush was to attend GOP fund-raisers today in Charlotte, N.C.,
and in Greenville, S.C.
   Bush defended his decision to campaign during the final days of
the Democratic convention _ a break with a tradition in which
candidates cease campaigning during the other party's convention.
   Noting that he had also been criticized for dropping out of
sight for four days on his fishing trip, Bush said he did not think
his activities would upstage the Democrats.
   ``I'm not going to rain on their parade,'' he said.
   The vice president repeatedly refused to comment on specific
allegations raised in Atlanta. ``I'm not good at being a slash and
burn candidate,'' he said. ``Why respond to a bunch of frantic
name-callers?''
   Told that Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., had attacked him as a
do-nothing vice president, Bush said: ``The good thing about the
absolute wilderness is you don't have to listen to Ted Kennedy. I
recommend it.''
   In his speech Wednesday to the largely Ukrainian-American
audience, Bush declared, ``America's work will never truly be done
until all the captive nations and peoples of this earth are set
free.''
   He said that if Congress didn't soon vote support for
anti-government Contra forces in Nicaragua, that nation would
become ``another tragic entry into the list of captive nations.''
   ``Congress has been shameful and destructive on this issue,''
Bush said.
   The vice president, who also appeared at a GOP fund-raising
dinner at a private residence here Wednesday evening, planned to
campaign in Wisconsin and New Jersey on Friday, Tennessee and
Florida on Saturday and in New Mexico on Sunday.
</TEXT>
