<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TobaccoStudy     07-21 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tobacco Study,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Chewing Tobacco Elevates Nicotine Levels More Than
Cigarettes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quarter-ounce wad of chewing tobacco kept
in the mouth half an hour produces about as much nicotine in the
bloodstream as smoking three cigarettes, a University of California
researcher reported.
   Dr. Neal L. Benowitz, a UC professor of medicine and chief of
pharmacology at San Francisco General Hospital, said his study may
even underestimate the amount of nicotine absorbed in the
bloodstream because some users of chewing tobacco and snuff keep it
in their mouths for hours.
   A half-ounce chunk of tobacco kept in the mouth for an hour or
so could cause as much absorption of nicotine as eight to nine
cigarettes, Benowitz said Wednesday.
   His report is based on measurements of smokeless tobacco made
during a four-day study involving 10 volunteers. It is being
published in the July issue of the Clinical Phamacology and
Therapeutics journal.
   Nicotine is the most addictive chemical in tobacco and has been
linked to such health dangers as increased blood pressure and heart
rate, as well as damage of blood vessel walls.
</TEXT>
