<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WildfiresRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0945 07-21 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0945,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Near Yellowstone Fought On New Front, California Blazes Swell</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 1st graf to reflect that officials are now saying
sprinkler system in Bridger-Teton is not yet running. Subs 6th graf
`Some of' with 2 grafs of details and later comments. Subs grafs
18-19 pvs bgng `The 3,100' to UPDATE with northwrst Colorado fire
contained, acreage of Glenwood Springs fire reduced.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyoming firefighters battling a nearly 15,000-acre blaze two
miles from Yellowstone National Park gathered equipment to create
an artificial rain storm Wednesday to keep the fire from jumping
lines, while California firefighters struggled with two blazes
believed started by arson.
   Fires also raged on in Alaska, Colorado and Utah.
   In Wyoming, the fire had consumed at least 14,857 acres of
Bridger-Teton National Forest's Teton Wilderness, and officials
expected it to cross into the park in the next few days.
   Spokeswoman Amy Vanderbilt said if the fire does cross over onto
park land it will not be fought because of the park's policy of
letting natural fires burn.
   ``We haven't even set a date or estimation for containment or
control,'' said forest spokesman Doug Huntington.
   The more than 600 firefighters have made inroads, but ``the
behavior of the fire is running them ragged, especially in the
blowdown areas'' of downed timber on the fire's southern edge
around Enos Lake, said Dale Jarrell, the incident commander.
   Officials were hoping on Thursday to start up a sprinkler system
with marine pumps and hoses to moisten the Yellowstone Meadows, on
the border of Yellowstone National Park and some 2 miles from the
flames, said Fire Information Officer Ed Waldapfel.
   Yellowstone officials already were monitoring a half-dozen
smaller fires covering more than 15,000 acres scattered throughout
the park.
   While all of Yellowstone's roads and front country campsites
were open, camping restrictions were imposed throughout the
backcountry, and some backcountry campsites were closed.
   Two blazes in northern California's Calaveras County had burned
at least 9,000 acres by Wednesday evening, forestry officials said.
   The fires on Tuesday destroyed at least three houses, a mobile
home and other structures worth about $500,000, California
Department of Forestry spokesman Robert Watson said at the fire
camp in Railroad Flat. Officials said they suspect arson although
they have not found any incendiary devices. The blazes erupted at
about the same time and followed arson fires set in the area Monday.
   Crews plan to dig 13 miles of control lines that will allow the
fires to burn at least 16,000 acres, said chief state fire
spokeswoman Karen Terrill. The blazes were about 40 percent
contained by evening.
   Although the two fires are separate, crews are treating them as
one in their strategy. They are burning southeast toward the
mountain resort community of Arnold, on Highway 4, the town of
Sheep Ranch, and scattered homes and subdivisions. The area is
about 150 miles east of San Francisco in the Sierra Nevada.
   Rugged terrain, gusting winds and heavy smoke hindered
firefighters, who got a slight respite from the 100-plus degree
weather of previous days when temperatures eased into the mid-90s.
   Elsewhere in the state, a 4,700-acre fire in Los Padres National
Forest jumped fire lines Wednesday, dashing hopes that the blaze
could be contained by nightfall.
   ``The wind kicked up on us this afternoon,'' said Earl Clayton,
spokesman for the U.S. Forest Service. ``We've lost containment and
we don't know when we'll control the fire now.''
   The blaze, near San Luis Obispo, began Sunday.
   In Colorado, all but two of the fires that have charred more
than 21,000 acres since Saturday have been declared under control.
   A 3,100-acre fire near the Dinosaur National Monument in
northwest Colorado was contained Wednesday night, while
firefighters were scrambling to douse a 145-acre brush fire east of
Glenwood Springs, said Teresa Ross, a dispatcher with the Bureau of
Land Management at Craig.
   Firefighters in eastern Utah controlled two mountain blazes,
only to be sent to the southern part of the state, where a fire of
undetermined size broke out Wednesday afternoon in mountains
between Cedar City and Beaver.
   In Alaska, where fires have burned 1,300 square miles _ larger
than Rhode Island _ this season, the state Fire Service has left
most blazes to burn themselves out. It has been monitoring about 50
wildfires, some of them weeks old.
   The biggest is a 225,000-acre blaze 60 miles north of Fairbanks
that approached the Alaska pipeline earlier this month but was
stopped about 12 miles from it. The pipeline is covered with
heavy-gauge metal and was not threatened, Alyeska Pipeline Service
Co. said.
</TEXT>
