<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneCrash     07-21 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crash,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Officials Probe Twin-Engine Crash That Killed Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are studying the
wreckage of a twin-engine passenger plane to determine the cause of
a crash that killed the plane's pilot shortly after takeoff.
   The propeller-driven aircraft went down Wednesday afternoon on
the end of the eastern-most runway at Washington-Dulles
International Airport, said Dave Hess, a spokesman for the
Metropolitan Washington Airport Authority.
   Hess said the plane was owned by Fairways Corp., a charter
service based at nearby National Airport, and was en route to
National when the crash occurred.
   The Washington Post, citing unidentified aviation sources,
reported in today's editions that Fairways is operated by the CIA.
Agency spokesman Bill Baker said the agency could not confirm or
deny a relationship with the corporation.
   The pilot, believed to be the only person on board, was not
immediately identified.
   The National Transportation Safety Board was investigating the
crash, and NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz said the pilot ``issued
no distress radio signal to anybody.''
   Witness Brian De Poorter, who works in a nearby building, said
the plane ``came almost to a stop in the air. It stalled in a
nose-up position and it sort of cartwheeled toward the left, dove
straight down into the ground and immediately burst into flames.''
</TEXT>
