<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KorbSuit     07-21 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korb Suit,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawsuit By Ex-Pentagon Official Dismissed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dismissed a $500,000
lawsuit by an ex-Pentagon official who claimed he lost job with a
defense contractor after Navy officials complained about his calls
for cuts in the defense budget.
   U.S. District Court Judge Claude M. Hilton on Tuesday dismissed
the suit brought by Lawrence J. Korb, who joined Raytheon Co. in
1985 after four years as Pentagon manpower chief.
   Korb had filed suit against former Navy Secretary John F. Lehman
Jr. and his assistant secretary for research, Melvyn R. Paisley.
Paisley is under investigation for alleged fraud in the
government's current probe of military contracting.
   Korb had alleged that he was deprived of his right of free
speech because he was fired by Raytheon after Navy leaders objected
to his public calls for defense cuts.
   In dismissing the suit, Hilton ruled that ``there is no evidence
that defendants threatened or coerced Raytheon to induce the
company to silence or remove Dr. Korb and no causal link between
defendants' conduct and plaintiff's termination.''
   Hilton also dismissed similar allegations by Korb against
Everett Pyatt, assistant Navy secretary for shipbuilding, and Carl
M. Smith, minority staff director of the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
</TEXT>
