<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--SealedConvention     07-21 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Sealed Convention,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Hall Closed Again By Overcrowding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The keynote speaker and dozens of other
dignitaries were locked out of the Democratic National Convention
because of overcrowding in The Omni arena, forcing them to miss the
climax of their confabulation.
   Delegates, party leaders, convention staffers and reporters
milled about in frustration outside the blockaded walkway to the
hall Wednesday as the delegates inside nominated Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis for president.
   It was the second time in as many nights that the hall was
closed by fire marshals. Some of those locked out angrily denounced
the Democratic National Committee for choosing the relatively small
arena for the convention of more than 4,000 delegates.
   ``I want to go vote. I want to hear the nominations. I don't
understand this,'' said Blanche Preston McSmith, a delegate who
traveled from Auke Bay, Alaska, to cast her vote for Jesse Jackson.
``They won't let me in.''
   ``Who's sitting in my seat? I want him out,'' thundered Michael
Stein, a delegate from Chicago. ``I am being prevented from
representing the people who elected me. This is an injustice. ....
It's outrageous.''
   Others, including the party leaders caught outside the hall,
accepted their fortune mildly. ``There was no hassle at all,'' said
Texas Treasurer Ann Richards, the keynote speaker Monday night. ``I
came late and the hall was full.''
   She went back to her hotel room and watched the roll call on
television.
   Rep. Robert Garcia of New York barely made it into the hall, and
said he had left behind colleagues including Sen. J. Bennett
Johnston of Louisiana and Reps. Paul Kanjorski of Pennsylvania, Jim
Slattery of Kansas and Brian Donnelly of Massachusetts.
   Seen standing outside were Sen. Bob Graham of Florida, Reps.
Peter Rodino of New Jersey and Les Aspin and Gerald Kleczka of
Wisconsin, former Wisconsin Gov. Patrick Lucey and Bert Lance, a
Jackson adviser and former director of the Office of Management and
Budget for President Carter.
   ``If Pete Rodino and Les Aspin are on the outside, I'm with
them,'' Lance said. Rodino managed to gain entry later. Aspin did
not, despite his delegation's appeal from the convention floor for
him to be admitted.
   Critics of The Omni's selection had warned that it would be too
small to accommodate convention crowds. Fire Chief William H. Hamer
said he would allow about 12,500 people inside _ there were 11,000
seats _ and the DNC stationed workers at each door to count those
entering and leaving.
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young earlier blamed the crowding on
reporters in the hall. But Joel Justice, a delegate from Atlanta,
said convention planning was at fault.
   ``We thought we had all this problem worked out beforehand,'' he
said. ``Evidently it didn't work out exactly like they planned.''
</TEXT>
