<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--ConventionQuotes     07-21 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Quotes,370</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Notable quotes from the Democratic National
Convention:
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, after the Massachusetts governor clinched the
Democratic presidential nomination: ``It's all a little bit like a
play.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, after saying he would urge that the Dukakis
nomination be made unanimous: ``This is the appropriate time for
the transition of leadership for the fall campaign to take place.''
   
   BILL CLINTON, governor of Arkansas, giving the nominating speech
for Dukakis: ``As governor, Michael Dukakis hasn't just played with
issues the way some politicians do, he's wrestled them to the
ground. He's made the hard decisions: to balance budgets, to create
jobs, to fight crime and drug abuse, to increase day care and
health care, to do all those things that a leader has to do.''
   
   WILLIAM WINPISINGER, president of the International Association
of Machinists, nominating Jesse Jackson for president: ``He has
seized history by the mane and he is in the process of helping us _
leading us _ as we write a new chapter, not only in the annals of
American history, but in the chronicles of humankind's long and
torturous progress toward peace and prosperity for all in a global
community.''
   
   MAXINE WATERS, a California assemblywoman, delivering the second
nominating speech for Jackson: ``As his name goes into nomination,
so does yours. For this one man's message has transformed a nation.
We will never again be the same.''
   
   DUKAKIS, when a Boys Club official who introduced Dukakis to a
group of youngsters thanked the governor for taking time away from
his busy schedule: ``The problem with being a candidate is they
never let you out of the hotel room. So this is a joy to me.''
   
   REP. MORRIS K. UDALL, D-ARIZ., on the convention itself:
``Somebody said, `Everything has been said but that not everyone
had said it.'''
</TEXT>
