<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--GreekPride Bjt   07-21 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Greek Pride, Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Y'assou! Say the Convention's Proud Greek-Americans, Right On!</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Greek-Americans among the Democratic
delegates, the nomination of Michael Dukakis was a culmination of
their dreams in America as well as a tribute to their heritage in
Greece, the place where democracy was born.
   ``America is my country. But tonight, I'm Greek in my heart,''
said Nick Poulos, who immigrated from Athens in 1955, built his own
construction company in New Jersey and, in the last year, raised
more than $1 million for Dukakis' campaign.
   Like other delegates and supporters of Greek heritage on the
floor of The Omni _ some sporting T-shirts exclaiming ``Y'assou,''
or ``Right on!'' _ Poulos said his heritage gives him a special
bond with Dukakis.
   ``I worked hard to be a success and tonight I see again that
this country gives you the opportunity to be whatever you want to
be,'' said Poulos, who left the Republican Party for Dukakis.
   Agnes Anthonakes Ricko credits her parents' dinner-table
discussions of civil duty and social responsibility with her
interest in politics. It's a Greek trait, she said.
   ``Maybe it was because democracy was born in Greece,'' the
Massachusetts delegate said. ``He (Dukakis) reflects all of our
American values as well as our forefathers' values.''
   Dukakis' parents immigrated from Greece. His father Panos put
himself through college and medical school and became a successful
family doctor specializing in obstretics. His mother Euterpe worked
in the mills and became a schoolteacher.
   As a Massachusetts politician from the comfortable Boston suburb
of Brookline, Dukakis rarely mentioned his Greek heritage. He was a
candidate who spoke for middle-class suburbanites interested in
clean, efficient government, rather than a representative of
blue-collar immigrants.
   Then in a trip to Greece in 1976, he discovered his roots and
slowly he began mentioning his family's story _ the classic tale of
uneducated immigrants building successful lives in America.
   But in his presidential campaign, Dukakis found that the
American dream played well: he rarely failed to mention his
parents, especially when campaigning before others relatively new
to this country.
   When he talks of his roots in speeches, he tells of other
immigrant groups as well, of the American immigrant story. He
always says something in Spanish when before a Hispanic audience.
   But Greek-Americans say he's talking to them. And as one of
their own was nominated for president, they were overwhelmed.
   ``It's a feeling you can't explain,'' said Ohio state Dukakis
director Anne Drake, who was born Anastasia Drakopoulos. ``Probably
the only other people who can understand that feeling here tonight
are the black Baptists with Jesse Jackson. I understand that
feeling they have. It's an awesome feeling.''
   Dukakis, she said, ``represents the American dream for us and
for every other immigrant group.''
   Terre Haute, Ind., Mayor Pete Chalos arrived in the United
States from Greece at age 14. He believes Dukakis' nomination
reaffirms the ideals that drew his father across the ocean.
   ``This is probably the only country where the son of an
immigrant can become president,'' Chalos said. ``This tells people
that even if your dad came from a foreign country and didn't speak
English that well, that's not a handicap. You can still accomplish
something.''
   Leo Condos said as a child he remembered his father wishing
there would be a Greek president someday.
   ``Tonight I get to vote that dream in for him,'' Condos said.
``The Greek immigrant, like most immigrants, wants a better life
for his children, and then he wants to turn around and pay the
country back.
   ``Michael Dukakis fulfills that dream for a lot of immigrants,''
Condos said. ``Y'assou!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Convention-TV     07-21 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention-TV,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clinton Bombs, But Networks Stay for Dukakis Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The boring-convention prophecy finally came to
pass on the third day of the Democratic National Convention,
leaving the television networks time to fill in the middle of prime
time.
   After Jesse Jackson's riveting speech on Tuesday night,
Wednesday night's speech by Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton nominating
Gov. Michael Dukakis was like switching from ``The Cosby Show'' to
``My Mother the Car.''
   But the networks ran over prime time again to capture the
watching-the-grass-grow excitement of the nominating vote.
California put Dukakis over the top at about 11:15 p.m. EDT. ABC
beat a retreat shortly after 11:30. NBC and CBS stayed for the
anticlimax to the anticlimax when Jackson's campaign manager,
Willie Brown, ascended the podium to move for nomination by
acclamation. NBC signed off at 11:45. CBS at 11:55.
   Clinton's speech surely gave the network control rooms a
workout, trying to find spots to fill in. ABC cut from the droning
to an interesting background piece on Dukakis by Jeff Greenfield.
   Otherwise, the networks filled in with commentary and by going
frequently to the floor reporters for how-boring-is-he? reports.
   ``Bill Clinton is continuing his speech despite the best efforts
of people up here on the podium to get him to stop,'' reported
NBC's Connie Chung.
   ``You've got to admit as an actress, he lost the crowd,'' NBC's
Chris Wallace told rather than asked Olympia Dukakis, the
candidate's cousin.
   By contrast with Clinton, it was high entertainment to watch
ABC's Peter Jennings request comment from co-anchor David Brinkley,
whose clip-on microphone had fallen off. ``Here, use mine,''
Jennings offered, before noticing that his mike cord was about 18
inches long.
   ``I've always wanted to get close to you,'' he said as the two
leaned together so Brinkley could talk into the mike.
   At about 10:20, the balloting finally began. Gone are the days
when viewers kept their own tallies, anxiously wondering which
state would be the one to put the favorite over the top. The
Democrats struggled to get through the roll call before prime time
ended at 11, but Dukakis didn't get the nomination until 11:15.
   When Americans Abroad cast fractional votes, all three network
computers disgorged a different opinion of the figure after the
decimal point. NBC's added 0.9, ABC's voted for 0.7, CBS 0.8. Cable
apparently didn't suffer math anxiety and came up with 0.25 for the
final fraction.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The number of television viewers increased during Jesse
Jackson's speech on national television Tuesday night.
   According to figures from the A.C. Nielsen Co., NBC's rating
rose from an 8.7 for the 10:30-11 p.m. EDT period to a 10.4 after
11 p.m. Jackson began speaking just before 11. ABC's went up from a
7.8 to a 9.3, and CBS' went from 6.9 to 8.7.
   NBC won the night with an 8.8 rating and 17 share. ABC had a 7.8
and 15 and CB 6.7 and 13. CNN had a rating of 2.3. It's rating rose
to 2.8 during Jackson's speech.
   The rating is a percentage of 88.6 million total homes with
televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in use. CNN figures
are based on the markets where it is available, about half as many
as the networks.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Comedians are a hot TV commodity at the Democratic National
Convention.
   Al Franken, a writer and performer on NBC's ``Saturday Night
Live,'' is a commentator for CNN.
   ``It's great to be here for CNN, which is the only network
providing gavel-to-gavel coverage,'' he said. ``For CNN's sake, I
hope it's an exciting convention. Otherwise, I think Ted Turner
should just colorize the 1960 Democratic convention and show that.''
   The Fox Broadcasting Co.'s syndicated newsmagazine show ``A
Current Affair'' is originating from Atlanta and employing not one
but two comedians, impressionist Jim Morris, who has been running
around playing George Bush, and political humorist Will Durst as
commentator on the media.
   Durst said the convention was being covered by ``anybody who can
make a satellite uplink out of a Hoola Hoop and some tinfoil.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TV quotes du jour:
   ``I'm here to tell you that since the day they met, television
and politics have been laced together in the kind of embrace that
gives unsafe sex a bad name.'' _ Linda Ellerbee, commentating on
CNN.
   ``I walked out there on the (convention) floor, and so many
people had seen the show, I was stunned.'' _ Michael Murphy of
HBO's ``Tanner '88,'' who isn't a political candidate but plays one
on TV.
   ``Do you get any impression now that it's a bit sterile, this
convention?'' ``It's very lively. You've got all these red banners
and posters going. It's very exciting.''_ ABC's Peter Jennings and
David Brinkley analyzing the boredom level of the convention.
</TEXT>
