<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--RollCallRhetoric     07-21 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Roll Call Rhetoric,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Roll Call: Free TV Commercials For Home State Virtues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mississippi is the state that is ``moving beyond
the politics of race,'' Jesse Jackson is ``the man who excited our
hearts,'' and in every one of the nation's 50 states and far-flung
outposts, Michael Dukakis is ``the next president of the United
States.''
   Hyperbole? Not at a political convention, a free prime-time
forum. A convention roll call is an invitation to advertise.
   ``The Empire State, proud and unified in support of what will be
the greatest election this country ever had, proudly casts ... ''
was New York's report. No state ever humbly casts.
   Before the convention, Dorothy Bush, the 71-year-old secretary
of the Democratic Party, had said she wanted the delegates to know
she was glad they came and that ``the personal touch is important.''
   In this, her 12th consecutive convention roll call, Mrs. Bush
gave it the personal touch.
   In calling for Mississippi's vote, she noted that it ``happens
to be the state where I was born.'' In response, the chairman of
the delegation noted that the state was moving beyond the politics
of race and ``making sure Mississippi will never be last again.''
   Jackson may have lost the nomination, but he was praised
effusively.
   Montana said he ``made Americans stand a little taller,'' New
Jersey found him to be ``a man who excited our hearts and a man we
have come to love,'' and Ohio saw him as ``that extraordinary voice
for the future.''
   Dukakis did not get such lavish tributes, but he got the votes.
   The states' self-praise knew no bounds. Arizona not only was the
home of the Grand Canyon but was ``the ideal site for the
superconducting super collider.'' Historic Delaware started the
nation, the District of Columbia is ``soon to be the state of
Columbia'' and Florida is ``the state of choice for 1,000 residents
each day.''
   Minnesota was home to world-class champions Hubert Humphrey and
Walter Mondale, both losers as presidential candidates, and to the
Twins, winners of the 1987 World Series.
   Nebraska is the good-life state, New Mexico is enchanted by its
many cultures and Oklahoma is committed to excellence.
   Oregon ``made the U.S.A. from sea to shining sea'' while
Pennsylvania's working people outproduce the world.
   Vermont voted only once in its history for a Democratic
candidate for president _ in 1964 _ but this is the year it's going
to do it again. Washington's ``union-made planes carried you to
Atlanta.''
   Wisconsin cast its votes and declared that ``if anyone has seen
Congressman Les Aspin, they wouldn't let him into the hall this
evening.'' If the doors hadn't been closed because of overcrowding,
the sad tale went, ``we would have cast one more vote for Mike
Dukakis.''
   It was Texas that delivered a line Democrats can sink their
teeth into. Texas, said the chairman, is ``home to 16 million
hard-working Texans and one tourist from Kennebunkport, Maine.''
   George Bush will have a chance to rebut the charge next month,
when Republicans unveil their own messages of hype and hope.
</TEXT>
