<HEAD>Finally, Dukakis Backers Rise And Explode In Celebration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After sitting patiently on their placards while
Jesse Jackson's supporters enjoyed the spotlight the night before,
Michael Dukakis' faithful were unleashed to shout and dance in the
aisles when their turn came. Then they took their carnival outside
to the streets.
   The floor of The Omni was a mass of ``Duke, Duke, Duke'' signs
Wednesday night as the California delegation put Dukakis over the
top and gave him the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Some floor leaders hugged as delegates threw red, silver and
blue streamers and batted giant beach balls about.
   Delegates linked arms and swayed in unison as singer Dionne
Warwick performed, then moved outside for a fireworks show, a
marching band and echoing chants for Dukakis.
   In the Georgia delegation, Sen. Sam Nunn clapped to the rhythm
and former President Carter flashed his toothy smile.
   ``I'm very pleased we nominated a man who's going to win and be
a great administrator,'' Carter said.
   Over at in New York delegation, Gov. Mario Cuomo said he, too,
couldn't be happier.
   ``This is a winning combination if I ever saw one,'' Cuomo said.
   For Jackson delegates, the night held mixed feelings _ delight
in seeing their candidate nominated, disappointment at the expected
loss.
   ``They are using Jesse Jackson's message without the man,'' said
a still angry Mark Allen from Chicago, who paraded through the
Dukakis forces with a Jackson sign.
   ``Jesse Jackson will still be the conscience of the Democratic
Party,'' he said.
   The rowdy Dukakis fans chanted ``We Want The Duke,'' and ``We
Want Mike'' after the nomination, but they didn't get him just yet.
Dukakis will formally accept the nomination in a speech tonight.
   His forces did get a move for a unanimous vote from Jackson's
side, and there were only a handful of ``No's'' when the unanimous
vote was taken.
   Cuomo said he was eager to campaign for the nominee.
   ``I'll go to California. I'll go to Michigan. I'll go
whereever,'' Cuomo said. ``I'll go for sandwiches if he wants.''
