<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShootingSpree     07-21 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shooting Spree,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources Say Deputies Not Given Go-Ahead To Fire On Gunman</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Deputies were denied permission when
they asked to fire on a gunman who killed four people in their
cars, according to people who were listening to Forsyth County
Sheriff's department radio reports.
   Authorities on Wednesday served Michael Charles Hayes, 24, with
four murder warrants in the neighborhood shootings Sunday night
that also left five people wounded. The gunman also fired on
deputies, but they were uninjured.
   Hayes, who was bound to his hospital bed by leather straps
holding his arms and legs, is being treated for wounds suffered
when deputies finally shot him near the moped shop he operated.
Hayes' family had sought to have him committed to a mental hospital
the day before the shootings.
   Steve McGuire of Winston-Salem said he was tuned in to radio
conversations between deputies and the sheriff's dispatcher during
the 12-minute rampage Sunday night.
   ```A civilian has been shot,''' McGuire recalled hearing. ```Do
I have permission to take him down?'''
   Maguire said a supervisor replied, ``No, wait until I get
there.''
   A man named Robert, who declined to give his full name, gave the
Winston-Salem Journal this account of the radio traffic during the
shootings:
   Deputy: ``I'm 50 to 60 yards in front of moped shop, and he's
shooting at the car.''
   Dispatcher: ``What?''
   Deputy: ``He shot a civilian in the car.''
   When the deputy requested permission to fire on Hayes, it was
denied, Robert told the newspaper.
   The car belonged to the third victim, Melinda Hayes, 21, no
relation to Hayes.
   By then Crystal Suzanne Cantrell, 16, and Thomas Walter
Nicholson, 24, had been killed. Within minutes, Ronald Lee Hull,
32, would be fatally wounded.
   Another source, who also listened to the transmissions and
insisted on anonymity, corroborated the two accounts.
   County Sheriff E. Preston Oldham declined to comment on his
department's investigation into Sunday night's events.
   ``It is still under investigation,'' Oldham said. ``I have
nothing else to say.''
   Earlier, Oldham said the investigation is expected to be
completed next week and that a news conference will be scheduled
then.
</TEXT>
