<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Harris     07-21 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Harris,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jean Harris Seeks Clemency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former headmistress Jean Harris says she
wants her freedom after having served more than seven years of her
15-year-to-life prison term for the murder of Scarsdale Diet
developer Dr. Herman Tarnower.
   Mrs. Harris' supporters are seeking to gather signatures on
petitions to send to Gov. Mario Cuomo to reinforce her personal
letter requesting executive clemency.
   As of Aug. 23, Mrs. Harris will have served 7{ years at the
Bedford Hills Correctional Facility. State law requires that half
the minimum sentence be served before clemency can be considered.
She will be eligible for parole in 1996, when she serves the
minimum 15 years.
   ``She has paid her debt to society,'' Anne Lennox, a founder of
the Jean L. Harris Defense Fund in Monroe, N.H., said Wednesday.
``She has had two heart attacks, she suffers from angina and she
really is no threat to anyone.''
   Ms. Lennox started the petition drive, sending copies of the
petition to the 3,000 or so people nationwide who have expressed
interest in Mrs. Harris' case.
   Mrs. Harris, 65, was convicted in 1981 of shooting Tarnower at
his Purchase home in 1980 after Tarnower threw her over for a
younger woman.
   Mrs. Harris, who was headmistress of the exclusive Madeira
School for girls school in McLean, Va., always maintained she meant
to kill herself when she accidentally shot Tarnower four times.
   She first sought clemency two years ago after suffering two
heart attacks.
   But the governor's three-person clemency committee turned her
down, pointing out the time-served provision and declining to grant
her a waiver of that requirement.
   Now that the requirement has almost been met, supporters are
more optimistic.
   Mrs. Harris' attorney, Michael Kennedy, said he was preparing a
brief detailing why Cuomo should free Mrs. Harris and all the
documents, Mrs. Harris' letter and the petitions, would be sent to
Albany in late August or early September.
   Anne Crowley, a spokeswoman for the governor, said Mrs. Harris'
request would receive the same scrutiny as any other case.
   ``Each case is individual and that's how they're reviewed,'' she
said.
   Any clemency granted by Cuomo must be approved by the state
parole board.
   Since her incarceration, Mrs. Harris has written two books, one
an autobiography, ``Stranger in Two Worlds,'' and another due for
release next month, ``They Always Call Us Ladies,'' about prison
life and the need for prison reform.
</TEXT>
