<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Polaroid-Disney     07-21 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid-Disney,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roy Disney Firm Makes $2.84 Billion Bid for Instant-Film Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. hinted it would reject a
proposed friendly takeover by the nephew of the late Walt Disney,
who announced a bid that values the instant-film company at $2.84
billion.
   Roy E. Disney, an investor with an estimated personal wealth of
$560 million, announced the offer Wednesday, and disclosed that he
already owns 6.9 percent of Polaroid through his family's Shamrock
Holdings Inc.
   Polaroid, based in Cambridge, Mass., responded it was reviewing
the $40-a-share cash offer with the help of outside advisers, but
suggested management would look unfavorably on a buyout.
   Referring to a retrenchment plan involving layoffs and
cost-cutting that was announced last week, Polaroid said in a news
release: ``We firmly believe that this is, without doubt, the right
course for Polaroid and for all of its shareholders, employees,
customers and communities.''
   Polaroid's stock shot up $6 a share to $40 a share on the New
York Stock Exchange on Wednesday.
   Polaroid's retrenchment plan, announced July 12, was widely seen
as an anti-takeover measure, and analysts said the timing of the
Shamrock offer suggested it was the trigger for the Polaroid
changes.
   ``It would be very hard to say they're unassociated,'' William
Relyea, who follows Polaroid for Eberstadt Fleming Inc. in New
York, said of the offer and the changes announced at Polaroid.
   Polaroid said it would cut up to 8 percent of its U.S. workforce
and save $50 million a year by reducing overhead and research and
development costs. The company also announced it would repurchase
$300 million of its own shares and create an employee stock
ownership program that owns 14 percent of the company's stock.
   Polaroid also said it would enter the $7 billion-a-year world
market for conventional film, challenging Eastman Kodak Co. and
Fuji Photo Film Co. Ltd.
   Disney described Polaroid's planned foray into the conventional
film business as a misguided attempt to regain momentum in the face
of a stagnating market for instant cameras and film.
   ``The announcement ... appears to be a pedestrian attempt to
give the company new direction,'' Disney lieutenant Stanley P.
Gold, Shamrock president and chief executive officer, said in a
news release. ``It betrays Polaroid's heritage of invention and
creativity in the development of new products and markets.''
   Gold also denounced Polaroid's stock repurchase and employee
stock ownership plans as a ``management entrenchment scheme.''
   In a letter delivered to I. MacAllister Booth, Polaroid
president and chief executive officer, Shamrock proposed that
Polaroid management cooperate with the takeover offer.
   Polaroid has 71 million shares outstanding, including a recent
issue of 10 million shares that created the employee stock
ownership program. The $40-a-share offer thus places a value of
$2.84 billion on the company.
   Shamrock already holds 4.93 million shares, or 6.9 percent. To
buy the rest at $40 a share would cost Shamrock $2.64 billion.
</TEXT>
