<DOCNO> AP880721-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland-Draft     07-21 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Draft,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poland to Free 95 Conscientious Objectors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist authorities will free 95 young
men convicted or awaiting trial on charges of avoiding the military
draft, the state-run news agency PAP said.
   Wednesday's announcement came two days before the anniversary of
the 1944 establishment of Poland's Soviet-supported government and
one week after Parliament enacted a law allowing conscientious
objections to military service.
   But the most prominent conscientious objector, Slawomir
Dutkiewicz, 24, a supporter of the outlawed peace group Freedom and
Peace, will not be freed.
   The dispatch said Dutkiewicz, who friends say has been on a
hunger strike since November and is being force-fed, refuses to
perform alternative non-military service required by the new law.
   PAP said those to be freed include eight people sentenced to
prison for refusing military service because of their personal
moral convictions and 86 who refused for religious reasons.
   The releases ``have been prompted above all by humanitarian
principles. This is one more proof of democratization of life in
this country, of respect shown for citizens' views and convictions,
of consistency in the pursuit of the policy of national
reconciliation,'' the agency said.
   In addition, a prosecutor will ask for acquittal of one
unidentified person who refused induction into the army for
``pseudo-pacifist motives,'' PAP said.
   The decision came on a motion of the chief military prosecutor
to the Council of State, chaired by Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski.
   ``It's not a surprise,'' said Freedom and Peace founder Jacek
Czaputowicz, whose group has waged a three-year civil disobedience
battle for enactment of a conscientious objectors' law.
   ``It's very positive, except for Dutkiewicz. It means they
accepted our goals. They accepted alternative service as an
institution and now we see that they would like to release almost
everybody.''
   He said the group would continue to press for Dutkiewicz's
release.
   Under the new law, people can apply for alternative service
working in a state enterprise for moral or religious beliefs. A
draft board comprised of military and civilian members will judge
the applicants.
   If granted, alternative civilian service is to last one year
longer than regular military service. Under Poland's draft law,
every young man is required to serve two years in the army, or one
if he is a university graduate.
   Czaputowicz said hsi group has been successful because its goals
were ``very concrete. It was realistic as we see now.''
   Last month, the group achieved another chief goal _ changing
Poland's military oath to remove a reference to serving alongside
the Soviet Red Army.
   ``Now is a good time for such demands because of perestroika,''
said Czaputowicz, referring to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
campaign for fundamental social and economic reforms that do not
challenge the leading role of the Communist Party.
   ``We can pressure the authorities,'' he said. ``And now is the
time ... because of Gorbachev's peace offensive. They (authorities)
don't want people in prison.''
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said Tuesday that if draft
resisters were freed, time served in prison probably would be
applied against their alternative service obligations.
   July 22, the Communists' national day, was when martial law was
lifted in 1983. It has been associated with amnesties of various
kinds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
