<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PanAmHeist     07-21 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pan Am Heist,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Men Flee JFK Airport With $1 Million in Cash and Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three unarmed men posing as guards for an
armored car company got away with more than $1 million in cash and
checks from a Pan Am airlines counter at John F. Kennedy
International Airport.
   The Pan Am employees didn't realize they'd been robbed until the
real guards showed up 15 minutes later, Port Authority police said.
   The men entered the Pan Am building at 1:35 p.m. Wednesday and
walked into the ground-floor cashier's office, said Allen Morrison,
a spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey.
   They were wearing uniforms and presented what appeared to be
legitimate identification cards from the Vets International Armored
Transport in Brooklyn. They did not have guns, said another Port
Authority spokesman, Tom Middlemiss.
   The trio signed for a pickup and received two bags containing
$50,000 in cash and more than $950,000 in non-negotiable checks,
Morrison said. The men then fled the terminal.
   ``Fifteen minutes later the real guys showed up,'' Middlemiss
said, and police were called.
   Pamela Hanlon, a spokeswoman for Pan American World Airways,
declined to comment on the incident and referred all questions to
the Port Authority.
   The Port Authority police and the FBI are investigating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
