<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0552EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Eastern     07-21 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern, Machinists To Continue Talks Despite Layoff Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and its machinists union plan to
continue contract talks despite reports that the money-losing
carrier is preparing to lay off 4,000 workers and make deep service
cuts.
   The layoffs would affect mostly non-union reservations and
airport workers, The Miami Herald reported. Most of the cuts would
affect Eastern destinations in the West and diminish Kansas City,
Mo.'s status as a hub.
   The moves, which the newspaper said would cut the Miami-based
carrier's work force by 12.5 percent in up to 20 cities by this
fall, are expected to be announced Friday.
   ``They don't communicate with us, they never tell us, there's no
cooperation,'' said Charles Bryan, president of Machinists District
100 and head of Eastern's 12,000 mechanics and ground-services
workers. ``They have no credibility, absolutely none.''
   Bryan said seven months of federally arbitrated contract talks
would continue this week, but last month's fragile agreement with
management on safety matters could be jeopardized by the imminent
reductions.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern and its Houston-based Texas
Air Corp. parent and three union leaders, including Bryan, under
federal guidance signed a peace treaty aimed at resolving disputes
over safety matters.
   In Miami, Eastern spokesman Robin Matell called Tuesday's
published report ``speculation.''
   Eastern, which last November laid off 3,500 employees, mostly in
Miami and Atlanta, and closed a reservations center in Chicago,
also reportedly is considering closing one or more of its remaining
nine reservations centers.
   Managers who supervise the affected areas have been summoned to
Miami for briefings Friday when negotiators for Eastern and the
pilots union are also scheduled to meet.
   Shrinking since its acquisition by Texas Air in 1986, Eastern
has cut its work force over the past two years from 42,000 to
32,000. The carrier serves 130 U.S. and foreign cities, down from
145 two years ago.
   Lorenzo has said Eastern, which is losing $1 million a day, will
sell assets and shrink to cover losses. Management has blamed much
of the losses on high labor costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
