<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TransatlanticTrash     07-21 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transatlantic Trash,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plans Abandoned To Dump U.S. Garbage In Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears of health hazards have derailed plans to
dump 7.5 million tons of American garbage in northern England, the
domestic news agency Press Association reported.
   The Manchester Ship Canal Co. will not be allowed to import the
waste from New York, Boston and Philadelphia over five years and
dump it near Warrington, near the northern city of Chester, the
agency said Wednesday.
   Winston Churchill, grandson of the wartime leader and member of
Parliament representing the area, said Wednesday: ``It is
unacceptable that the northwest should be made the world's
dustbin.''
   His comments echoed earlier protests by members of the Cheshire
county council, who asked the government in June to stop the
importation on health grounds.
   ``We understand that the rubbish will contain untreated waste
from New York hospitals as well as animal fats and rotting
vegetation,'' Councilor Derek Bateman was quoted as telling the
Daily Telegraph newspaper. ``The rubbish will not be covered, so we
will have the prospect of it blowing all over Cheshire and exposing
people to potential health risk.''
   The garbage, which would have arrived in open-topped containers
in Liverpool, would have been dumped on 390 acres owned by the
company and leased by the council, the Telegraph reported.
   A spokesman for the Department of the Environment said Wednesday
that the council had ruled against allowing the company to dump the
waste at the site.
   The company has the right to appeal, the spokesman said.
   No waste can be imported into Britain without approval of the
Ministry of Agriculture and the Department of the Environment.
</TEXT>
