<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JailDeath-March     07-21 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jail Death-March,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Groups to March in Protest Over Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEMPHILL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 demonstrators from Texas and
Louisiana civil rights groups plan to march next month to protest
the acquittal of three white lawmen in the beating death of a
jailed black man.
   The marchers from Hemphill, Houston, Dallas, Beaumont and
Shreveport, La., are expected to take part in an Aug. 6 rally at
the Sabine County courthouse, said Vollie Grace, president of the
Hemphill chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People.
   ``We plan to march to the courthouse,'' Grace said Wednesday.
``We'll be protesting the outcome of the trial.''
   Last week, the three lawmen _ Hemphill Police Chief Thomas
Ladner, 41, and Sabine County deputies James ``Bo'' Hyden, 35, and
Bill Horton, 58, _ were acquitted of civil rights violations in the
beating death of Loyal Garner Jr., a truck driver from Florien, La.
   Garner, 34, died of head injuries Dec. 27 in a Tyler hospital
after being arrested on a drunken driving charge Christmas Day and
taken to the Sabine County Jail.
   The three still face trial in Tyler on murder charges in
Garner's death. The trial is set to begin Aug. 8.
</TEXT>
