<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WhalingShip     07-21 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Whaling Ship,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explorers Club to Help Raise 19th-Century Whaler</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of explorers plans to raise the world's
largest 19th-century steam whaling ship from the frigid depths of
the Chukchi Sea off Alaska, and even has visions of sailing the old
vessel again.
   The 177-foot whaler Orca, which sank in September 1897 after it
got wedged between two pieces of floating ice, is like ``an
underwater time capsule,'' said project director Dan W. Shirey.
   ``We have found that the year-round, below-freezing temperatures
of the water makes the ocean environment marine organism-free. No
other area of the world can offer such ideal preservation
conditions for marine antiquities.''
   Indeed, the vessel, once the pride of America's whaling fleet,
is believed to be so well preserved that Shirey dreams of sailing
it to a new home _ perhaps next to the Queen Mary in Long Beach,
Calif., or to the South Street Seaport in New York.
   ``In this melting pot of New York, the ship could find a home
under the shadows of the lady (Statue of Liberty) herself,'' he
said at a news conference Wednesday at the Explorers Club, a
private organization of professional explorers and scientists.
   Ninety-one years ago, the Orca, owned by the Pacific Steam
Whaling Co. of San Francisco, sank, stern-first, in about 100 feet
of water off Point Franklin, Alaska. The captain and crew escaped.
   ``You couldn't have asked for a gentler shipwreck,'' said
Shirey, a former Coast Guard search-and-rescue diver who founded
the Ocean Research Center of the Arctic, a non-profit organization
for preserving the region's maritime heritage. It was established
in 1985 at Point Barrow, Alaska.
   On Aug. 6, he will lead a team of nine explorers to a base camp
at Peard Bay, Alaska. They will survey and photograph the wreck
using small boats, sonar and remote-controlled, undersea vehicles,
until about Sept. 30, when the ice moves back into place for the
winter.
   The $2.5 million Phase 2 _ dredging beneath the 628-ton vessel,
attaching large slings to its frame and lifting it with barges _ is
to begin late next summer.
   Time is limited, because a proposed offshore pipeline might
disturb the historic wreck, Shirey said at the Explorers Club,
which is underwriting the $150,000 first phase.
   ``We found the whaling ship's timbers to be worm-free and as
structurally strong as if they were hewn and assembled in 1987,''
said Shirey.
   Scott Murray, dive coordinator, said that in 1982, he helped
raise a 186-foot metal ship that sank in the 1930s in Panama. But
no vessel as old as the Orca has ever been recovered whole, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
