<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Convict-Analyst     07-21 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Convict-Analyst,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graduate Of Penitentiary Investment Class Lands Finance Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY O'DELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he saw one of the characters in the
movie ``Wall Street'' led away in handcuffs after being arrested
for insider trading, Tom Dorsey thought about his newest employee
and smiled at the irony.
   The movie character faced the prospect of adjusting to life in
prison. Dorsey's employee, Thomas Walker, is finding his niche in
the world of finance after being paroled from the State
Penitentiary.
   The convicted felon is a graduate of an investment strategies
course Dorsey taught in the prison. Walker kept in touch with
Dorsey until his release last November and now is a securities
analyst for Dorsey, Wright and Associates.
   ``He created his own position,'' Dorsey said. ``He would come in
at night and read the wires and work with the computers on his own,
and eventually I started giving him certain tasks. Before long, he
became instrumental in the operation.''
   Walker, 31, was convicted in 1979 of arson, armed robbery,
burglary and solicitation for murder and was sentenced to 36 years
in prison.
   ``I don't know if I could have gotten a job in this business if
it hadn't been for Tommy,'' Walker said. ``Getting your foot in the
door is the hardest part.''
   Walker, who was a business administration major at The College
of William & Mary before he ran afoul of the law, said that before
college he already had met ``a lot of people who were maybe a
little shady.''
   ``Most of the things we were involved in were burglary and
arson,'' he said. ``We always rationalized what we did by saying
our victims were probably insured.''
   Walker said the solicitation for murder conviction was based on
an undercover officer's testimony that he tried to have the officer
kill three people who had testified against him.
   Walker said it was the excitement of ``living on the edge'' that
prompted his criminal behavior.
   ``It's like turning on `Miami Vice,''' he said. ``You can either
sit there and watch it, or you can play `Miami Vice.' I was playing
it.''
   Dorsey, who was a vice president at Wheat First Securities
before opening his own business in 1987, said Walker's criminal
background likely would have kept him out of other firms.
   ``There's no way we could have hired him at Wheat,'' he said.
``But all I care about is performance. I don't give a damn if he
has been in prison.''
   Walker had served three years when he signed up for Dorsey's
first investment strategies course.
   ``I was always interested in business anyway,'' said Walker, who
is continuing his education at Virginia Commonwealth University.
``When I heard about Tommy's course, bells and whistles went off.''
   Dorsey's course started with the basics of supply and demand,
and he used the analogy of convicts swapping or selling cigarettes
to illustrate his lessons. When the students advanced further, they
were given a fictitious $15,000 to invest with prize money going to
the three who made the greatest profit.
   ``I didn't do very well with my $15,000,'' Walker said. ``I was
too conservative.''
   But Dorsey still was impressed.
   ``He was one of the more quiet and reserved students,'' Dorsey
said. ``But he never missed a class, and he always completed his
assignments on time. It was obvious he was serious about this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
