<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Typhoon 1stLd-Writethru a0475 07-21 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Typhoon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Typhoon Kills Six, Causes Extensive Damage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A typhoon that slammed into the southern city of
Shantou killed at least six people and caused millions of dollars
in damage to ships, homes, power lines and rice paddies, officials
said today.
   Typhoon Warren hit Shantou and neighboring counties in coastal
Guangdong province on Tuesday night with 80 mph winds and
torrential rains before dissipating inland.
   The overseas edition of the People's Daily today reported six
deaths and 70 people injured in the Shantou municipal district.
   But the China News Service said 106 were injured. It said total
damage from the storm was estimated at $160 million.
   Li Lieqin of the Shantou Foreign Affairs Office said by
telephone that six of the injured were hit when a wall toppled over
at a chemical plant. He said one person was in serious condition.
   China News said the typhoon washed away 147 hydraulic projects,
toppled more than 4,000 houses and 14,300 huts and damaged 38,000
other houses during its 16-hour strike. It said more than 432,000
acres of crops were damaged.
   The People's Daily estimated the damage to rice paddies at $9.5
million and said $6 million worth of fruit trees were uprooted. Li
said there was heavy damage in particular to the region's orange
and banana crops.
   The news service said the typhoon damaged telephone
communications, knocked down four bridges, smashed more than 30
miles of roads and destroyed nearly 200 ships, seven of which sank.
   The People's Daily said hundreds of electric poles were knocked
down and more than 19 miles of river embankments and 16 miles of
see levees washed out. Li said four bridges in the Shantou area
were destroyed but did not say how big they were.
   The city's electricity and telephone service were restored today
after a 24-hour outage.
   Guangdong provincial officials said there were no deaths or
extensive damage in Canton, a city of more than 2 million about 190
miles southwest of Shantou.
   Details of cleanup operations were not disclosed. Li said armed
police were called in before the typhoon hit to take protective
measures at the Shantou oil depot, and the air force battened down
the city airport.
   Peasants in the area, warned of the coming storm, labored the
day before the typhoon hit to bring in grain, but Li said early
estimates showed 55,000 tons were lost.
   Southeastern China was battered by heavy rains and flooding in
May and June. Official reports said five people were killed and 370
injured in Guangdong and at least 171 were killed in neighboring
provinces in those storms.
</TEXT>
