<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Bulgaria     07-21 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Bulgaria,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Politburo Members Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two prominent members of Bulgaria's
Politburo were dropped from the ruling Communist party body, the
official Bulgarian news agency BTA said.
   It said Choudomir Alexandrov, 52, was dropped Wednesday and
relieved of his duties as a secretary of the Central Committee at
his own request.
   Alexandrov became a Politburo member in 1984 and a Central
Committee secretary in 1986 and was seen last year as a potential
successor to Bulgarian leader Todor Zhivkov.
   Veteran Communist Stanko Todorov, whose wife Sonya
Bakish-Todorova joined an unofficial committee to protect the
environment, also was dropped from the Politburo at his own
request, BTA said.
   It said the policy-making Central Committee dropped Svetlin
Roussev, an artist who led the environmental committee.
   BTA did not say whether the officials would get other top party
or government posts or who their replacements would be.
</TEXT>
