<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Vietnam-USFliers     07-21 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US Fliers,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Wants Reimbursement Of Expenses For Rescuing Fliers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has asked the United States to
pay all expenses involved in its rescue of three U.S. Navy aviators
whose plane made an emergency landing in the South China Sea, a
U.S. Embassy spokesman said today.
   ``Vietnamese authorities have asked the U.S. government to pay
all expenses involved in the rescue, transportation and
accomodations of the crew members. This request is under review,''
said spokesman Bill Schauer.
   He said the request was made while arrangements were being made
for the return of the aviators.
   Vietnam's communist government previously has demanded large
sums for the return of Americans and other foreigners picked up in
its territorial waters.
   A spokesman for the Vietnamese embassy said he had no
information on the request.
   The aviators flew out of Vietnam's Ho Chi Minh City, formerly
Saigon, on Tuesday and returned to Subic Bay Naval Base in the
Philippines. They said they were grateful to Vietnamese authorities
for the good treatment they received.
   The aviators were the pilot, Lt. Richard K. Maurer, 30, of
Harvey's Lake, Pa.; the pregnant co-pilot, Lt. j.g. Elizabeth A.
Steinnecker, 29, of Corpus Christi, Texas; and Petty Officer First
Class Michael A. Neel, 34, of Albuquerque, New Mexico.
   U.S. Embassy officials in Bangkok said the three were flying
back to base from Singapore on July 12 when the navigational
equipment on their CT-39E twin-engine jet failed and they couldn't
make it to Malaysia for a scheduled refueling stop.
   They landed in the sea in the vicinity of the Spratly islands,
some of which are occupied by Vietnamese military forces.
Vietnamese navy vessels took them to the mainland.
</TEXT>
