<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Protests     07-21 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Protests,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-War Protests Lead To Bomb Scare, Arrests, Veterans End Vigil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM E. SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen peace demonstrators were arrested,
police destroyed a bag apparently holding juice instead of a bomb,
and a goose was held hostage for the homeless outside the
Democratic National Convention.
   Also Wednesday, Vietnam veterans ended a 72-hour vigil,
supporters of Tawana Brawly demonstrated and 126 abortion opponents
arrested Tuesday continued to sit in jail because they refused to
give authorities their names.
   The 18 activists from No Business as Usual were arrested after
entering the U.S. Department of Energy regional office during a
larger demonstration by the anti-nuclear weapons group, said Jackie
Barrett of the convention police command center.
   Shortly afterward, a bag found outside was destroyed by the
police bomb squad, said Ms. Barrett.
   She initially said the bag contained an explosive device, but
later reported: ``It was not an explosive. It was a clear liquid.
We're thinking it was apple juice.''
   Homer the goose _ a real, honking goose _ appeared in the
designated demonstration area outside the convention site with
members of the Street People's Advisory Committee, an Austin,
Texas, advocacy group for the homeless.
   Several months ago, the street people had vowed to kill Homer,
then a tiny gosling they had bought for $8, unless more attention
was paid to the homeless. Homer lived.
   ``He's here to speak out about the problems of the homeless,''
James Williams, president of the group, said as the goose honked
and chased after bystanders' feet.
   Wednesday evening, as veterans appealed to the Democrats to get
an accounting of the Americans missing in Southeast Asia, the same
group staged an impromptu rally in a street adjacent to the protest
area. Police cleared the street, taking four people into custody.
   Jere Beery of Newnan, Ga., coordinator of the National
Forget-Me-Not Association for POWs and MIAs, said he would like to
see actress Jane Fonda intervene on behalf of MIAs.
   Miss Fonda's apology to Vietnam veterans for her trip to North
Vietnam during the conflict, ``has broken the ice,'' he said. ``She
has said she is sorry, but can we trust that? We need some sign.''
   Former POW John Parcells urged Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis to appoint the Rev. Jesse Jackson as a special
envoy to Vietnam to work for an accounting of Americans who are
missing, dead or being held prisoner in Southeast Asia.
   In the same two-acre parking lot near The Omni arena, about 60
people rallied in support of Tawana Brawley, the 16-year-old New
York girl who maintains that she was the victim of a sexual and
racial assault but who has refused to cooperate with prosecutors.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, Miss Brawley's adviser, attacked nominee
Michael Dukakis, calling on him to state his positions on injustice
against black people.
   Miss Brawley looked on expressionless during the rally, which
also featured independent presidential candidate Lenora Fulani of
New York, whose campaign has become a fixture in the protest area.
   Across town, 126 abortion opponents arrested earlier continued
to sit in jail Wednesday because they refused to give authorities
their names. They were allowed to visit with their relatives
through a jailyard fence.
</TEXT>
