<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0643EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--DukakisVillage     07-21 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Dukakis Village,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Nominee's Ancestral Home Celebrates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PELOPI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the ancestral home of Michael
Dukakis feasted on lamb, danced and drank ouzo toasts early today
at an all-night party to celebrate his nomination as the Democratic
presidential candidate.
   More than 200 people gathered at the village cafe cheered wildly
as state-run Greek television announced in its midnight newscast
that the Massachusetts governor was ``certain to get the
nomination.''
   ``It's an important event for our village tonight, it's one more
step towards the November election,'' said Costas Stefanou, 42,
president of the this mountain village of 640 residents on the
northern Aegean island of Mytilene.
   The crowd toasted the man they call ``our Michalis'' with beer
and ouzo, an anise-flavored drink that is an island specialty. Then
they feasted on spit-roast lamb and danced to bouzouki music,
watched by a line of children perched on a fence wearing ``Mike
Dukakis for President'' buttons.
   Both of Dukakis' paternal grandparents were born in Pelopi but
moved away in the 1880s to open a store in the Turkish town of
Edremit, where the governor's father was born. Edremit is 40 miles
from Mytilene across a narrow Aegean Sea strait.
   A local priest, the Rev. Lefteris Kamiris, said that Nov. 8, the
presidential election date, is ``especially auspicious'' for the
island.
   ``Now that Michalis has the nomination, there's no way he's not
going to get elected on that day,'' Kamiris said.
   Kamiris said Nov. 8 is the feast-day of St. Michael, the patron
saint of Pelopi. That day, too, marks the date in 1921 that
Mytilene was granted independence from Turkish rule.
   Kamiris, who paints icons _ sacred pictures of saints displayed
in Greek Orthodox churches _ also was responsible for the signs
that identify Pelopi in Greek and English as ``the hometown of
Michael Dukakis.''
   ``We feel proud that someone from our island can get so far.
It's changed our lives,'' he said.
   A trickle of tourists has started coming to Pelopi, looking for
the Dukakis family home.
   ``All the visitors bothered us a bit at first, but we don't mind
now. It's good to have people wanting to visit the house where it
all started,'' said Yiannis Manolis, whose father bought and
rebuilt the ruined Dukakis home in 1933.
   The yellowing sale contract signed by Panos Dukakis, the
governor's father, is proudly shown to visitors.
   Panos Dukakis emigrated to the United States in 1913 and became
the first Greek-American to graduate from Harvard Medical School.
   The village council already has renamed the main street Michael
Dukakis Street and intends to offer the presidential candidate a
mountainside plot of land where he can build a summer home.
   ``Michalis could do some gardening, maybe grow watermelons,''
said Stefanou, who recalled that on his one and only visit to
Pelopi in 1976, the governor enjoyed the local melons.
   ``We're proud that someone who hails from Pelopi might become
the most powerful man in the world,'' said Alexander Chiotellis,
who acted as Dukakis' host on that visit and claims to be his
second cousin.
   The villagers, mostly sheep- and goat breeders, also say a
Dukakis election victory might improve the quality of life in
Pelopi.
   ``If he's elected the government may finally decide to pave the
top part of the road to the village. After all, if he comes here as
president he can't drive up a dirt track,'' Stefanou said.
   A self-styled local poet already has composed what he calls an
``Ode to Dukakis''.
   ``Dukakis comes from our village, our beautiful island of
Lesbos,'' Eleftherios Yiannakos recited on Wednesday night.
   Lesbos is the ancient Greek name for Mytilene.
   ``All the villagers are lovingly concerned to see him as
president in America,'' the 20-line poem continues.
</TEXT>
