<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrimeSpree     07-21 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crime Spree,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Virginia Couple Sentenced For Utah Portion Of Six-State Crime
Spree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Virginia man and woman were sentenced
to 120 days in jail for crimes committed in Utah during what a
judge called ``a cross-country criminal lark.''
   In addition to the jail time, Ronald Allen Feathers, 18, of
Winchester, Va., and Angie Smith, 20, of Strausburg, Va., were
placed on 18 months probation and ordered to pay $471.15 in
restitution.
   The pair allegedly stole a car in Front Royal, Va., abandoned it
later, stole another car in Ponchatoole, La., and drove it through
Utah, according to a Washington County sheriff's report.
   The report said the couple then drove to Wichita, Kan., where
they allegedly stole a briefcase from a pickup truck that contained
credit cards and used the cards to purchase gas and oil.
   Later, the couple allegedly stole a small travel trailer in
Colorado and abandoned it in Utah, where another trailer was
stolen, authorities said.
   They were apprehended by police in Utah after an officer noticed
the trailer had no tail lights and learned the vehicle had been
stolen.
   In 5th District Court Wednesday, Judge J. Philip Eves told
Feathers he couldn't believe the couple got as far as they did.
   Court documents presented during the pair's appearance show they
were charged with auto thefts in Colorado, Mississippi and
Virginia, credit card theft in Kansas, various criminal charges in
Louisiana and several federal charges.
   The Utah jail time for both will be waived if they are
extradited to face charges in other states or federal charges, Eves
said.
</TEXT>
