<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Re-education Camp, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0568,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Some 38,000 People Sent To Army Camps In 1980</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with length of re-education period.
Pick up 4th graf pvs: `Authorities said...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today they have destroyed
the criminal records of about 38,000 people sent to army
``re-education'' camps in a 1980 crackdown on dissent.
   Police said the names were removed from police computers and
other lists to prevent unfair treatment of the former suspects.
Having such a record would make it difficult to get employment.
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan sent tens of thousands of people
to army barracks for ``re-education'' periods of four to six months
in an extensive crackdown in 1980 after he seized power with
military backing.
   Authorities said at the time that people sent to the camps were
criminals and hooligans. Dissidents contend many were
anti-government activists and innocent of any crimes.
   Dissidents have claimed a number of people were killed or
injured in the camps.
   Army Chief of Staff Lee Jong-ku told the National Assembly
Wednesday that the army operated the re-education camps in 1980 to
``purify'' criminals. Opposition lawmakers called for government
compensation to victims.
</TEXT>
