<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Australia-Smoking 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-Smoking, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0549,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Driver Awarded $52,000 For Exposure Passive Smoking</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS last graf, `Australian laws...' to CORRECT that smoking
banned on all domestic flights.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 59-year-old bus driver with lung
cancer he said was caused by smokers riding in his bus was awarded
$52,000 from the Melbourne Transit Authority.
   The Victoria state government's Accident Compensation Tribunal
heard Sean Carroll's claim and on Wednesday ordered the authority
to pay him $24,000 in compensation and $28,000 in damages for
negligent exposure to tobacco smoke.
   Carroll, who was diagnosed with cancer in February, was exposed
to the smoke for 24 years at work, said Stephen Woodward, executive
director of the anti-smoking group Action on Smoking and Health.
   Woodward said today that the passive smoking award was the first
of its kind in Australia.
   ``I predict that all of Australia's workplaces will be
smoke-free in 1989,'' he said. ``Any employer who continues to
allow smoking at work is taking a grave risk with both workers
compensation and common law claims.''
   Carroll drove Melbourne buses beginning in 1952. Smoking was
banned on public transportation in 1976.
   The transit authority could not be reached immediately for
comment.
   Australian laws restricting smoking are among the world's most
stringent, prohibiting it from all government offices, domestic air
flights and public transportation.
</TEXT>
