<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0734EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VoodooMayor     07-21 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Voodoo Mayor,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snake-Draped Mayor Kicks Off `National Voodoo Week'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLORALA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mayor who donned a white turban, red cape
and two rubber snakes as he proclaimed ``National Voodoo Week'' is
an ``embarrassment'' and should be removed from office, Alabama's
attorney general said.
   But Florala Mayor H.T. Mathis, 85, said he was only seeking
publicity Wednesday with his candle-lit midnight news conference
near a table covered with Halloween masks and a black, rubber bat.
   Attorney General Don Siegelman has accused Mathis of
mismanagement and improperly pardoning drunken drivers. Mathis is
fighting the charges and faces an impeachment trial next month.
   ``He continues to be a threat to the public safety and an
embarrassment to the people of Florala and Covington County,''
Siegelman said.
   Mathis said the voodoo week is aimed at promoting publicity and
peace for his town of 2,200 on the Alabama-Florida border.
   Mathis denied believing in black magic and said the media had
turned him into the ``voodoo mayor,'' so he would use the
opportunity for publicity.
   ``The voodoo story, like a television commercial, has notified
thousands of people that Florala is a solid little town and it's
ideally located for any type of industry,'' Mathis said.
   Mathis attracted national attention last fall when he sprinkled
what he said was ``voodoo dust'' around City Hall.
   Following the initial reports of the voodoo dust, Mathis said
the powder actually was cornstarch he placed there because the
police chief believed in voodoo. The chief denied such beliefs.
   In a telephone interview Wednesday, Mathis said the powder was
neither voodoo dust nor cornstarch.
   ``Back right after I was elected we had some information that we
had some witchcraft going on in City Hall, and we figured it was
making a difference. Somebody gave me the idea that if I sprinkled
sulfur and put up some pictures of owls that would take care of it,
scare them.
   ``They tell me people who are interested in witchcraft are
definitely scared of sulfur. Sure enough, the so-called police
chief came in and pitched a fit. What it was, I just wasn't careful
enough.''
   Police Chief A.V. Patrick has denied believing in the occult,
but declined to comment Wednesday. ``I just don't put nothing in
the paper. I don't even want to talk about it.''
</TEXT>
