<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-21 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors at the University of Alabama say
they have no plans to trade their scalpels for spatulas and make a
few bucks flipping burgers.
   Officials for a group of some 500 physicians in the non-profit
Alabama Health Services Foundation say they probably will sell
their Wendy's Old Fashioned Hamburgers franchise, purchased in
March to get the land for a planned $103.5 million outpatient
clinic.
   The doctors paid $1.6 million for the land near the university
campus and the $400,000 for the hamburger franchise rights, said
Dick Briggs Jr., acting president of the foundation.
   The restaurant remains open, ``but,'' Briggs said, ``we don't
have any long-range visions of making our fortunes in the burger
business.''
   After all, he said, ``It may be hard to push
cholesterol-lowering diets in our building with a Wendy's next
door.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Michigan Supreme Court justice saw two men
trying to swipe a $79 television set from his downtown office and
even offered to help them.
   Justice Dennis Archer thought the 5-inch black-and-white set
they were taking from the 14th floor of the Lafayette Building
about noon Wednesday looked familiar.
   When he offered to lend a hand, ``They laughed and one said,
`No, we're waiting for my aunt,''' Archer said.
   He returned to his office and noticed his set was missing.
   The justice then rounded up a group to collar the men. They
split up into two teams, said Archer, who along with Ken
Poindexter, a maintenance man, nabbed the pair.
   ``You security?'' one of the men asked the justice.
   ``I guess you could say that I'm the biggest security you've
ever seen,'' Archer told him. But when he explained who he was,
``it didn't seem to register.''
   Police said the men, ages 21 and 23, were being held on breaking
and entering charges.
</TEXT>
