<DOCNO> AP880721-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0822EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Damages     07-21 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Damages,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Wins Big Medical Damages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The High Court today awarded $1.126 million in
damages to a woman who suffered massive brain injuries during an
abortion.
   Pearl Cunningham, a 46-year-old mother of three, suffered a
heart attack that led to brain damage during the operation at
Dulwich Hospital in southeast London in January 1983.
   The award of 655,126 pounds against Camberwell Health Authority
is one of the highest in Britain for medical negligence. A record
1.03 million pounds ($1.77 million) was awarded last summer to a
student who suffered brain damage caused by negligent care at a
hospital.
   Hedley Cunningham, who brought the malpractice suit on his
wife's behalf, said he was not satisfied with the award and would
seek legal advice about an appeal.
   ``It is far from a big award,'' he said.
   The Camberwell Health Authority admitted liability but was
contesting the amount of damages.
   Mrs. Cunningham, a former nurse, can speak and enjoy her
family's company but cannot coordinate the movement of her limbs,
said her lawyer, Benet Hytner.
   The judge, Sir Philip Otton, praised the ``heavy burden''
shouldered by Cunningham, 47, who quit his job as a security guard
to care for his wife and their three children.
   Doctors allowed Cunningham to take his wife home in December
1985. The judge said she would require full-time care and
supervision for the rest of her life.
</TEXT>
