<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UtahRocketBonds     07-21 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utah Rocket Bonds,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislature Approves Bonds To Attract Rocket Fuel Plant From
Nevada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature has authorized $33 million
in industrial revenue bonds to finance construction of a rocket
fuel plant in southern Utah to replace one destroyed by an
explosion in Nevada.
   The bill, supported by Gov. Norm Bangerter, would benefit the
Pacific Engineering and Production Co.
   The company is looking at one site in Utah and two in Nevada to
replace its Henderson, Nev., plant, which was destroyed May 4. Two
people died in the blast and fire.
   The company makes ammonium perchlorate, a fuel component used in
the space shuttle booster rockets and solid-fuel missiles such as
the MX and Minuteman.
   Kerr-McGee Corp. operates the only remaining U.S. plant
manufacturing the component. Members of Congress have expressed
fear of a critical shortage of the chemical.
   Company spokesman Keith Rooker said a site would be chosen soon
_ ``certainly by next week.''
   The bond authorization bill passed the House 64-2 following
several hours of debate Wednesday and was quickly approved 23-1 in
the Senate.
   Pacific Engineering has said it must break ground on the plant
by Aug. 1 and begin production by Feb. 1 to meet contractual
obligations. The company said current employees would be offered
jobs first, even if the plant were relocated to Utah.
</TEXT>
