<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0459,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Capital Reported at Work; Strike Continuing in
Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with situation today in Yerevan,
strike in Nagorno-Karabakh, signs of crackdown continue. Changes
byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Factories were operating and mass transit was
running today in the Armenian republic despite a strike call by
activists seeking to annex a part of neighboring Azerbaijan,
residents and state-run media said.
   Soviet authorities increased pressure on leaders of the
5-month-old campaign to make Nagorno-Karabakh part of Armenia. The
government on Wednesday ordered a leading Armenian nationalist,
Paruyr Ayrikyan, stripped of his citizenship and expelled.
   Speakers at a Wednesday night rally in Yerevan, Armenia's
capital, called for a five-day strike to protest the Soviet
leadership's refusal to alter the status of Nagorno-Karabakh, a
mostly Armenian enclave that has been part of Azerbaijan for 65
years.
   Khovik Vasilyan, an Armenian activist, said the strike call had
no obvious effect in Yerevan today.
   ``The city today is working. Factories are in operation, and
mass transit is running,'' the former political prisoner said in a
telephone interview.
   The official Tass news agency, in a dispatch from the city of
1.1 million, said that since Monday ``more and more industrial
enterprises of Armenia have begun to work at a normal pace.''
   ``Those who did not work or didn't work at their full capacity
are returning to their jobs in Yerevan, Kirovakan and other
cities,'' Tass said.
   A watch officer at Armenia's Ministry of Internal Affairs, which
handles police matters, said ``everybody is working, and the
situation is normal.'' He identified himself only as Grant.
   However, a worker with the Gostelradio state broadcasting
authority in Stepanakert, Nagorno-Karabakh's administrative center,
said today that a general strike begun in May in the mountain
enclave was continuing.
   ``The people are embittered,'' said the worker, who refused to
give his name. ``We don't know what to do. But we know that the
refusal to make Nagorno-Karabakh part of Armenia wasn't just.''
   Most Armenians are Christians, while most Azerbaijanis are
Moslem. Most of the disputed region's 160,000 people are
Aremanians. The Armenians there say they are discriminated against
by the Azerbaijanis.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, with the blessing of Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, ruled Monday that annexing the region
to Armenia would violate the Soviet Constitution, since Azerbaijan
had objected to the transfer.
   Activists said at least 400,000 people attended Wednesday's
rally near a Yerevan historical institute. Those figures could not
be independently confirmed because Moscow-based Western reporters
are prevented from traveling to the region.
   Speakers at the rally read the official Tass news agency report
about Ayrikyan's expulsion. People raised fists and shouted
``Ayrikyan, Ayrikyan! Freedom, freedom!''said an activist who spoke
on condition of anomymity.
   The Presidium on Monday also authorized police to ``take
essential measures'' to end strikes and ``any activities directed
at kindling national strife and attempts to misuse democratic
rights for anti-democratic purposes.''
   Today's Tass dispatch from Yerevan attacked leaders of the
annexation drive by name, accusing them of criminal activities and
of trying to stir up ethnic tensions.
   It said five people, including writer Vano Siradegyan and Rafael
Kazaryan of Armenia's Academy of Sciences, ``tried to provide a
cover-up for `shadow economy' dealers, for clans of career-seekers
and bribe-takers.''
   Vartan Silikyan and Martin Barsekyan, both active members of the
``Karabakh committee,'' a group created to organize the annexation
drive, were arrested when they brought 35 gasoline bombs to a
Monday rally in Yerevan, Tass said.
   It called the committee a ``group of demagogues who wish to
further their selfish aims under the cover of problems of
Nagorno-Karabakh,'' and said some members received wages during an
earlier general strike in Armenia.
   The first major target of the official crackdown was Ayrikyan,
39, who has been jailed or exiled for 17 years beginning in 1969
for his political activities.
   Tass said the Presidium stripped him of citizenship Wednesday
and expelled him ``for his active instigation to inter-ethnic
strife.'' The news agency did not say where the activist was headed
or whether he had left Soviet territory.
   Ayrikyan helped organize the drive to annex Nagorno-Karabakh and
provided frequent reports to foreign correspondents. He was
arrested March 25 and charged with defaming the Soviet state.
   Tass said he was pardoned before being expelled.
</TEXT>
