<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-American     07-21 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-American,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Term Reduced For American Convicted On Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appellate court today reduced to six years a
prison term imposed on an American financier convicted of smuggling
$17.1 million worth of cocaine into Britain.
   The three judges reduced David Wesley Medin's nine-year sentence
after learning that the 45-year-old Detroit man agreed to testify
for the prosecution against other members of an alleged drug ring.
   Medin admitted he had worked for the Mafia.
   ``Anyone crossing the path of the Mafia is in peril of losing
his life,'' senior appeal judge Lord Watkins said. ``This appellant
is now in that select company.''
   Watkins said Britain and other European countries would have
been flooded with cocaine had the drug plot not been foiled.
   Medin was arrested in January 1987 and charged with possessing
cocaine with intent to supply. He was sentenced in April 1987.
   Scotland Yard has said Medin provided police with detailed
information on money laundering and drug-supply routes. Prosecutor
Roy Amlot said at Medin's trial that Medin cooperated and ``named
names'' in organized crime circles after his arrest.
</TEXT>
