<HEAD>Dukakis' Actress Cousin To Take To Podium Tonight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with Olympia Dukakis quotes, picks up 3rd
graf pvs, ``The theme</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Olympia Dukakis, who will introduce
Michael Dukakis at tonight's convention session, today compared
being his cousin to one of ``the great parts.''
   ``It's a very special time in your life,'' said Miss Dukakis,
just hours before she was to present the Democratic presidential
nominee to the delegates before a nationwide television audience,
many of whom saw her spirited pitch for him when she accepted an
Academy Award in April.
   ``My dream was and still is to play the great parts,'' she said
in an interview on CBS-TV. Asked if being the candidate's cousin is
a great part, she replied: ``It certainly is.''
   On Wednesday night, Miss Dukakis sat among the New Jersey
delegation as Dukakis formally won the nomination. Tonight she will
take to the massive convention rostrum before Dukakis delivers his
acceptance speech.
   ``The theme will be very simple: Michael Dukakis,'' the actress
said in a brief interview on the floor of the crowded Omni
convention hall. ``Michael Dukakis and the leadership and values he
will bring to America.''
   The seasoned stage and movie actress acknowledged being a bit
nervous about her appearance at center stage of the Democratic
National Convention.
   ``On Broadway you get a chance to rehearse,'' she said. ``Here I
don't get much of a chance to rehearse.''
   Dukakis' and Miss Dukakis' fathers _ both Greek immigrants _
were brothers and raised their families near each other in the
Boston area. She now lives in New Jersey, where she failed in an
attempt to win election as a delegate for Dukakis but was later
named an at-large delegate.
   When she accepted the Oscar for her supporting role in the movie
``Moonstruck,'' Miss Dukakis held the trophy high over her head and
called out: ``OK, Michael, let's go!''
   That came just before the New York primary, which Dukakis won in
the early part of a string of primary victories that secured him
the nomination.
   He returned the surprise a few weeks later, strolling
unannounced onto the set of a Boston television program as she was
being interviewed.
   In the months to follow, Dukakis would frequently tell his
campaign audiences of his and his cousin's successes, declaring
1988 ``the year of the Dukaki,'' a comment she also made backstage
after claiming her Oscar.
   Miss Dukakis spent much of her week in Atlanta doing interviews
and said she spoke to Dukakis several times. She promised to
campaign vigorously for her cousin in the fall campaign.
   She also is filming a new movie.
   When asked if perhaps 1989 would be an even better year for the
``Dukaki,'' she shrugged her shoulders in a manner characteristic
of her politician cousin.
   ``Why not?'' she asked.
</TEXT>
