<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Bourne 1stLd-Writethru a0554 07-21 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Bourne, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0554,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nutritionist, Histologist Dies In New York At Age 79</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `In 1962,...' to include that Bourne was in
charge of Aneruicab medical students during U.S. invasions.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Geoffrey Bourne, an internationally known
nutritionist and medical researcher who wrote an important
historical overview of hunger in Europe during wartime, has died.
He was 79 years old.
   Bourne, who was vice-chancellor of the St. George's University
School of Medicine on the Caribbean island of Grenada, died Tuesday
at Bellevue Hospital's coronary care unit, where he was admitted
two weeks ago, a spokesman for the university said.
   The Australian native was the author of several books, including
`Nutrition and the War'' (1941) and ``Starvation in Europe''
(1943). The latter book was placed in the British Imperial War
Museum as a historical document.
   Bourne also founded and edited the World Review of Nutrition and
Dietetics and the International Review of Cytology.
   He earned bachelor's, master's and doctor's degrees from the
University of Western Australia, and another doctoral degree from
Oxford University.
   From 1938 to 1947, Bourne taught physiology at Oxford. During
World War II, he also served as a member of the British Special
Operations Executive in charge of biomedical research for Special
Forces in Southeast Asia with the rank of major.
   In 1945-1946, he was chairman of the Pan Malayan Nutrition
Council, which assessed Malaya's food needs after the Japanese
surrender.
   Between 1948 and 1957, Bourne was professor of histology at the
University of London. He later became professor and chairman of
anatomy at Emory University Medical School in Atlanta.
   In 1962, he became director of the Yerkes Primate Research
Center at Emory, a post he held until joining the St. George's
University School of Medicine in 1977 as vice-chancellor. He was
also a professor of nutrition at St. George's, and was in charge of
scores of American medical students trapped in Grenada before the
U.S. invasion in October 1983.
   Bourne was a fellow of the Institute of Biology in England, the
Zoological Society of London and the American Society of
Gerontology. He was a fellow of the Royal Society of Medicine for
more than half a century.
   Funeral services for Bourne were to be held in Atlanta and a
memorial service was to be held in Grenada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
