<1ST_LINE>u i PM-CVN--ConventionAbroad 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0995</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Abroad, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0574,1036</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreigners View The Democratic Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs with Israeli reaction. Pick up 1st graf
pvs, Britain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<HEAD>ISRAEL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir reacted to the nomination of
Michael S. Dukakis by saying he hoped whoever wins in November will
maintain friendly ties with Israel.
   ``America is a very large country.... and what will matter is
the administration's policy and the majority of the American public
opinion,'' Shamir said. ``I hope that from this point of view,
nothing will change and relations between Israel and the United
States will continue to be those of allies, like today.''
   Shamir has pledged not to get involved in internal U.S.
political debate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Times of London (independent) said in an editorial today:
   ``Gov. Michael Dukakis has proved that he is a highly successful
campaign chief executive. He now has to prove that he can campaign.
   ``He can raise money _ far more than his rivals. He showed
himself sufficiently able in matters of policy to survive the early
loss of his principal adviser. His tough, not to say brutal,
treatment of the Rev. Jesse Jackson has insured against one of the
easiest jibes aimed by Republicans at Democratic leaders: that they
are weak under pressure.
   ``He can learn from past mistakes. It is plain that the chief
errors made by the Democrats in the last two presidential races
will not be repeated. Above all, the link to narrow but vocal
single-interest campaigns has been broken.
   ``The inclusion of Mr. Jackson as a third force behind the
ticket has been done without apparent cost in terms of unacceptable
policies. The convention declined to support Mr. Jackson's calls
for increased taxes on the wealthy or an undertaking on
no-first-use of nuclear weapons.
   ``The Democratic platform this year is, for the first time in
many campaigns, not a liability to the candidate.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Le Figaro (conservative) on Dukakis: ``Certainly his lack of
humor, his mechanical elocution, his technocratic vocabulary, his
stormy character _ he's said to have fragile nerves _ are not in
his favor. But he compensates for these faults with a serious
nature and a sense of organization without fail. And his
Mediterranean charm, drawn from contained passion, pleases women!
   ``The result is that the party is more united than it has ever
been. Does the credit go to Mike Dukakis himself? To the choice of
a southern conservative, Lloyd Bentson, as running mate? To the
support of Jesse Jackson? To all of these elements put together?
Opinions, as always, are split.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Liberation (leftist) on the Democratic platform: ``Dukakis will
go into combat in November without being weighed down by specific
promises or excessive engagements. Tuesday, the convention approved
the shortest and most neutral Democratic platform in history. Five
thousand words of generalities and platitudes, overcoming easily
Jackson's more robust propositions. Like a steamroller, the Dukakis
camp eliminated the black reverend's views on the use of nuclear
weapons, taxes on the rich or the Middle East.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Milan's Corriere della Sera (moderate) on the convention:
   ``The three great television channels had to close down
transmission at 11 at night, but when Jackson started to speak all
timetables were ignored, and the tyranny of programming and
publicity was for once shattered. Those who direct great shows know
how to recognize one when they see it. Or maybe, after all, it
turns out that it is not true that we are in the era of passionless
politics, one empty of values, preset by experts, determined by the
polls, articulated by professional speechwriters, and sold like a
detergent.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Rome's Il Messaggero (moderate): ``The hearts of many delegates
are with Jackson who in his sermon dragged out both laughter and
tears from the public, raising emotions with a speech about hope
destined to remain in history as a follow up to the memorable
statement by Martin Luther King Jr., `I have a dream.'''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AUSTRIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Kurier, Austria's second largest circulation daily, marked
Dukakis' nomination with a profile of the man it called ``a doer
knocking on the White House door ... the new fast climber of U.S.
politics.''
   Kurier noted that Dukakis' program to date is ``short, not
dangerous and politically vague,'' but said that ``in one essential
point, he is different from other politicians: he keeps political
promises, but tries in advance to avoid them.''
   Describing Dukakis' lifestyle, the paper noted that he has very
few close friends, but that ``elegance and some eccentricity are
provided by his wife Kitty, the daughter of a well-known Boston
musician of Jewish religion.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The conservative Vienna daily Die Presse said in a news story
that although Dukakis won out in the campaign, ``the black preacher
Jesse Jackson dominated the scene.''
   In a feature, the paper stressed Jimmy Carter's comeback among a
general overview that presented the catchword ``Let's party'' _ at
the cost of several million dollars _ as the essence of the
convention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWEDEN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The conservative Svenska Dagbladet newspaper published a column
saying that if Swedes were voting for the U.S. president, Dukakis
would win easily, but that he will lose because he is not a Swede.
   Ingemar Dorfer, a researcher on political and security affairs
at the Defense Research Institute, wrote: ``Dukakis would naturally
win in Sweden. He is liberal, he is a representative of the
professional trades, just like the Swedish journalists covering his
campaign. America has a natural Democratic majority.
   ``Wrong. It's only the Swedish state of Minnesota that voted
Democratic in four of the five latest presidential elections. While
the House of Representatives, now and nearly always, has a
Democratic majority, the position of president has as a rule a
Republican one.
   ``Ideology is not going to decide the election. The majority of
people are now against state intervention in their lives. That goes
especially for emigrants from Asia and Latin America who, in their
old homelands, saw authorities as enemies.''
</TEXT>
