<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Protest     07-21 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Protest,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Stage Anti-Government Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 radical students demanding
the arrest of former President Chun Doo-hwan on corruption charges
clashed with riot police in the South Korean capital today.
   The students, who came from various schools in the capital,
marched into the streets after a rally at the Hongik University
shouting, ``Punish Chun Doo-hwan!''
   Riot police fired tear gas, touching off a fierce battle with
the students who countered with firebombs and rocks. There were no
injuries or arrests reported in the clash, which lasted about an
hour.
   In a prepared statement, the students criticized the government
of President Roh Tae-woo for trying to protect the ex-president,
who they said ``stood at the forefront of all corruption and
irregularities.''
   During the rally, the students burned effigies of Roh and Chun
and shouted that they would fight until their demands were met.
   It was one of the few anti-government student protests reported
in recent weeks. All universities are on summer vacation until the
end of August.
   Chun, whose term ended in February, has come under fire for
alleged involvement in financial and other scandals. One of his
brothers is on trial for allegedly embezzling millions of dollars
in official funds.
   Roh replaced Chun after December elections. He was Chun's choice
as a successor.
</TEXT>
