<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0952EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OfficialFired     07-21 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Official Fired,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dallas' Highest-Ranking Hispanic Official Fired Over Alleged
Embezzlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant City Manager Samuel Moreno, Dallas'
highest-ranking Hispanic employee, has been fired in the wake of a
judge's ruling that he defrauded his company before it sought
bankruptcy protection in 1983.
   City Manager Richard Knight told City Council members Wednesday
he had ``no choice'' but to fire Moreno, a move criticized by some
Hispanic leaders. He said the matter had cast ``a shadow'' over the
city's integrity.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Harold Abrahamson ordered Moreno to repay
$131,164 he said was obtained through embezzlement and fraud from
Moreno's former oil-field supply company, Petroleum Energy
Equipment Co.
   Abrahamson on May 25 also ruled that Moreno, who at one point
had about $2.5 million in personal and corporate debts, improperly
altered corporate records and took out illegal loans.
   Knight said he learned of Abrahamson's ruling Tuesday.
   Moreno, 60, hired as one of four assistant city managers in
1986, declined to comment on his firing by Knight.
   ``He's sits in the hot seat,'' Moreno said. ``I'm not going to
second-guess his decision.''
   Moreno oversaw the Dallas Convention Center and Reunion Arena,
international affairs, the Fire Department, the public library
system, Love Field and Redbird Airport. His annual salary was
$78,417.
   Marcos Ronquillo, president of the Dallas Hispanic Chamber of
Commerce and a lawyer, characterized the firing as premature and
said Knight should have considered suspending Moreno or placing him
on leave.
   ``The guy's had his problems, but I don't know that they relate
this to his performance on the job,'' said Joe May, a member of the
mayor's Hispanic Task Force.
</TEXT>
