<DOCNO> AP880721-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1001EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CambodiaTalks     07-21 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia Talks,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodian Resistance Leader Will Not Participate in Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Norodom Sihanouk, former head of the
Cambodian resistance movement, said today he will go to Indonesia
this weekend but will not participate in informal talks on
achieving peace in Cambodia.
   ``How could they be a success?'' Sihanouk said to reporters
after meeting with French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas.
   Sihanouk, a former Cambodian head of state, resigned this month
from the presidency of the three-party guerrilla coalition that is
fighting Vietnamese troops occupying Cambodia. He appointed his
son, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, to represent him at the talks, which
start Monday in the resort city of Bogor, 37 miles south of Jakarta.
   The meetings, the first to include all parties to the
long-running Cambodian conflict, are being called ``cocktail
party'' talks because they will be informal discussions rather than
negotiations. Participating will be the guerrilla coalition, the
government in Phnom Penh and Vietnam.
   Sihanouk said two factors are working against the talks: what he
called ``fundamental contradictions'' between Khmer Rouge forces
allied with China and the government in Phnom Penh, and what he
said was Vietnam's refusal to discuss Cambodia's real problems.
   But he said he had accepted an invitation from Indonesian
President Suharto to come to Jakarta in the hope that he could
``contribute to the success'' of the talks.
   Sihanouk headed a resistance coalition that grouped his own
forces, the Khmer Rouge and a non-communist group headed by former
Son Sann.
   The Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of people during
its bloody rule from 1975-79. Vietnam drove the Khmer Rouge from
power and set up a pro-Hanoi government.
   The Vietnamese have said they will withdraw their troops by
1990, or possibly earlier if there is a political settlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
