<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0496,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says 11 Contras and Seven Civilians Killed In Rebel
Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Tunnermann throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven rebels and seven civilians were
killed this week in three rebel attacks that violated the leftist
Sandinista government's unilateral cease-fire, the Defense Ministry
said.
   Also Wednesday, the Foreign Ministry requested a U.S. visa for
Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann, whom the Reagan administration
expelled last week.
   The Defense Ministry statement said a Contra rebel band ambushed
two vehicles on Tuesday near Juigalpa, 55 miles east of Managua,
killing seven civilians, including two children aged 7 and 9.
   Five civilians were wounded in the attack, it said.
   Nine rebels were killed Monday when Sandinista troops fought off
an attack near Muelle de los Bueyes and Muhan, neighboring villages
in southern Nicaragua near the Caribbean coast, the ministry said.
   It did not mention any government casualties.
   Two more rebels were killed and one wounded in a Tuesday attack
on troops near San Rafael del Norte, 110 miles north of the
capital, the ministry said. It said the troops repelled the attack
by the U.S.-supported rebels.
   President Daniel Ortega announced Tuesday that the government
was unilaterally extending to Aug. 30 its cease-fire with the
Contas.
   Each side in the 7-year-old war has accused the other of
violating the truce, which began when a preliminary peace accord
was signed March 23, a month after Congress voted against renewed
military aid for the Contras.
   Negotiations for a lasting peace broke down June 9.
   State-run Voice of Nicaragua radio said Tunnermann needs to
travel to the United States to take part in an international
education contest and functions related to his job as ambassador to
the Organization of American States.
   U.S. Embassy officials refused to comment Wednesday night.
   The United States on July 11 ordered Tunnermann and seven other
Nicaraguan diplomats to leave to retaliate for Nicaragua's
expulsion of eight American diplomats, including Ambassador Richard
Melton.
   The Sandinistas said Melton and the others were implementing a
U.S. plan to incite domestic unrest.
</TEXT>
