<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LabBomb     07-21 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lab Bomb,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Against Dwyer Dropped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of a bombing outside a
nuclear weapons laboratory Nov. 28 will be confined to a mental
hosital for 18 months in a deal with prosecutors under which
criminal charges will be dropped.
   The agreement concluded Wednesday with Stephen Dwyer, 40, of
Palm Desert, was reached a day after U.S. District Judge Marilyn
Hall Patel criticized the government's handling of an immunity
agreement with him.
   ``We felt it was in the government's interest and the public's
interest to secure his commitment to some facility rather than risk
the outright dismissal of the case and his release,'' said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Joel Levin.
   Dwyer was charged with setting off a dynamite bomb next to the
Lawrence Livermore Laboratory, a facility 40 miles east of San
Francisco where U.S. nuclear weapons are designed. He could have
received up to 40 years in prison.
   The bomb demolished a laboratory employee's car, damaged three
other cars, broke dozens of windows and scattered debris for 400
yards.
   Dwyer was charged with interstate transport of explosives,
making and possessing a bomb and damaging federal property.
   ``From the standpoint of my client, he's going to be getting
some medical help that I think he needs,'' said Public Defender
Barry Portman. ``There's no getting around what he did. This isn't
a person with all his wits about him.''
   The FBI said Dwyer, a miner, bought materials for the bomb at a
shop in Reno, Nev.
   Dwyer's lawyers had contended the charges were based on evidence
provided by Dwyer under a promise of immunity. Prosecutors said the
agreement was not binding because Dwyer lied about a bomb at a
nuclear facility in the Los Angeles area.
   The agreement was not written down because of the apparent
urgency of the situation, said J. Stephen Czuleger, the federal
prosecutor who handled the case in Los Angeles.
   Patel on Tuesday said she was unsatisfied with the ``cursory,
casual way'' the government had handled the immunity agreement.
</TEXT>
