<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneDitches 1stLd-Writethru a0521 07-21 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Ditches, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0521,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Presumed Dead As Salvadoran Cargo Plane Crashes Into Swamps</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with search resuming; PICKS UP
4th graf pvs, `The TACA ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A search resumed today for three crewmen
aboard a Salvadoran cargo plane that ran low on fuel and crashed in
Louisiana swamps near the Gulf of Mexico, the Coast Guard said.
   Thirty to 35 people searched along a canal where the chartered,
four-engine DC-6 went down Wednesday night, said a Lafourche Parish
sheriff's dispatcher who would not identify himself.
   ``There apparently were no survivors, but you never know,''
Sheriff Duffy Breaux said Wednesday.
   The TACA International Airlines charter was on a five-hour
flight from San Salvador, El Salvador, to New Orleans with 22,000
pounds of handicrafts, seafood, plants, electronics and other
cargo, said Gary Mascaro, TACA cargo manager at New Orleans
International Airport.
   It was the second time in two months that a TACA flight was
forced down short of the airport.
   An FAA controller who asked not to be identified said the
plane's pilot reported at 7:20 p.m. Wednesday that he had just 15
minutes of fuel remaining, that he would be unable to reach New
Orleans and had to find a closer airfield.
   The nearest field, north of Grand Isle at Fouchon, had a
3,000-foot runway but the propeller-driven DC-6 needed 5,000 feet
and its pilot decided to ditch, the FAA spokesman said.
   The plane hit a levee and crashed in a drainage canal about 300
to 400 yards west of Louisiana Highway 1, about 40 miles south of
New Orleans, Breaux said. The area is surrounded by swamps and
marshes, accessible only by boat and helicopter.
   ``We didn't see any survivors and it's a pretty deep canal with
about 15 feet of water,'' Breaux said. ``The plane was submerged,
with only its wings still sticking up.''
   The Coast Guard sent a jet plane, a helicopter and boats to the
scene, Lt. Bruce Campbell said at the Coast Guard's 8th District
headquarters in New Orleans.
   ``They found a great deal of wreckage just alongside Bayou
Lafourche, right alongside a roadway. He (the pilot) may have tried
to land on the roadway and slid off,'' Campbell said.
   TACA is a Central American airline, based in El Salvador, with
offices in New Orleans. TACA operates two round-trip cargo flights
weekly between San Salvador and New Orleans, and rents planes from
other companies when there is a lot of cargo to haul, Mascaro said.
   TACA leased the plane from Fiorella Crew Inc. of Miami and the
men aboard were Fiorella employees, Mascaro said. He said he did
not know their names and Fiorella officials could not be
immediately reached in Miami.
   On May 24, a TACA jet flight with 41 people aboard experienced
engine trouble during a a violent thunderstorm and its pilot made
an emergency landing on a grassy strip of land in swampy eastern
New Orleans. No one was injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
