<HEAD>Seven Dead In Bomb Explosion and Revenge Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb believed set by militant Tamils
killed four people in northeast Sri Lanka today, and enraged
villagers then hacked at least three Tamils to death, military
officials and residents said.
   The bomb exploded in a shop in Trincomalee owned by Sinhalese.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, comprise about 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and say they are discriminated against by
the majority Buddhist Sinhalese.
   Military officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity under
briefing rules, said at least four people in the shop were killed
in the blast.
   At least 12 others were injured in the blast, they said.
   According to officials, the explosion was caused by Tamil
radicals campaigning for an independent homeland in the north and
east of Sri Lanka.
   Tamil residents, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Sinhalese, angered by the explosion, then hacked three Tamils to
death in the area.
   Military officials could not confirm the Tamil deaths.
