<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0603,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Says He Wept Over Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf: `The American...' to CLARIFY that U.S.
officials made comments, not investigating team. Pick up 9th graf
pvs: `The Islamic...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's parliament speaker, Hashemi
Rafsanjani, said today he wept listening to Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini say that Iran would accept a U.N. cease-fire resolution,
Tehran Radio reported.
   Rafsanjani also told Iranians not to question the decision.
   ``We should not ask why and how, not create more problems for
the society,'' Rafsanjani, who is also commander of the armed
forces, said in parliament.
   A U.N. team will visit Iran and Iraq this week to try to work
out details of implementing the resolution.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, also said that four more bodies
from the Iran Air jetliner shot down by a U.S. missile July 3 had
been recovered. The bodies, all male, were found near the southern
coastal city of Bandar-Lengeh, about 120 miles from the area of the
southern Persian Gulf where the plane went down, it said.
   The bodies of 186 of the 290 people on board have been
recovered. The Navy said troops mistook the plane for an F-14
fighter and shot it down.
   The radio report said Iran obtained the equipment needed to
search for the flight recorder and would begin hunting for it soon.
   U.S. officials have said they hope the recorder will reveal
whether the civilian pilot monitored warnings from the missile
cruiser USS Vincennes.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency reported that Iraq shelled the
village of Sardasht in northern Azerbaijan province along the
Soviet border and killed one civilian and injured two.
   On Wednesday, Khomeini said he accepted the advice of other
Iranian leaders and agreed to a U.N. resolution calling for a
cease-fire in the war between the Persian Gulf neighbors that began
in September 1980.
   Rafsanjani said Iranians could take stock of the reason for
accepting U.N. Resolution 598 some time in the future, and that
they would accept the fact that Khomeini changed his mind.
   Until this week, Khomeini had been adamant in opposing an end to
the war and vowed to continue until President Saddam Hussein of
Iraq was driven from power.
   Rafsanjani repeated that Iran will continue to man the
warfronts, and Mohsen Rezai, commander in chief of the
Revolutionary Guard corps, said the same in an interview today.
   ``If any change occurs in the resolution, we will stand against
it and will respond to any aggression,'' Rezai said.
   Khomeini, in his statement, stressed how difficult it was for
him to accept the resolution.
   ``I shall say again that the acceptance of this issue is more
deadly to me than poison, but I am happy to submit to God's will
and drank this cup for his satisfaction,'' the 87-year-old
revolutionary patriarch said Wednesday.
   Although the statement said he could not immediately reveal the
reasons for changing his mind, it said he acted on the
recommendation of military and political leaders. Khomeini's
statement was his first since the government said Monday it would
accept the cease-fire resolution.
   Iran's acceptance of U.N. Resolution 598 does not mean the war
is over, Khomeini said, but he said the decision was not just a
tactic to allow the Iranian military to regroup. Iraq has made that
accusation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
