<HEAD>Australian Fails for Second Time to Put Up Money to Buy PTL</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `Morehu, reached ...' to ADD that he was
reached by the Observer.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claims to be an Australian
businessman ready to pay $200 million in cash for PTL's property
has failed for the second time to meet a deadline to produce $50
million as earnest money.
   And Australians interviewed by The Charlotte Observer say that
from February until June, Gavin Morehu circulated through the
Melbourne, Australia, area proposing multimillion-dollar deals that
failed to go anywhere.
   ``That's what I think you're going to find here,'' PTL trustee
M.C. ``Red'' Benton said Wednesday. ``I really don't think he has
any substance behind his offer.''
   Benton added: ``We will not be able to spend any additional time
with him, and he's been told that ... if he comes, he must have the
money.''
   Morehu has not paid PTL more than $800 in telephone and
room-service charges from a several-day stay at the television
ministry's Heritage Grand Hotel, which he left without checking
out, Benton said. He failed Wednesday to meet a deadline to produce
$50 million toward his proposed purchase.
   Morehu, reached by the Observer on Wednesday at what is
apparently his home in Bedford, Ind., said: ``Things are looking
good and we're negotiating. We've been advised by our legal
attorneys not to comment on anything.''
   Morehu refused to answer questions about his background or about
what appear to be discrepancies in information he has given people
in the United States and Australia.
   ``Somehow you haven't got your facts right, nor have the
Australian press,'' Morehu said.
   When pressed further, he said, ``You better get the true facts,
because you don't want a $1 billion lawsuit against you. ... If you
get hard on us, we can get hard on you.''
   According to Australian news accounts and interviews with
Australians to whom Morehu has spoken, he has listed U.S. addresses
for what he says are his companies' offices, that, when checked,
were vacant.
   The company of which he claims to be president, Morehu
International, opened in April and closed in June, Australian
newspapers reported. He has claimed to own a Christian TV network
in this country that has proved to be nonexistent.
   The Australian Broadcasting Corp. said it had contacted members
of Morehu's family in Melbourne, who said he once had a small
construction business that went broke. They also said they had seen
little of him for eight years until last Christmas.
   Also on Wednesday, former PTL secretary Jessica Hahn said she
agrees with a judge's order and will return hush money paid her by
PTL for her 1980 sexual encounter with Jim Bakker that led to the
PTL founder's downfall.
   ``I feel in my heart that the money belongs in the ministry and
I hope that it will now be used properly and not for Jim Bakker's
or anyone else's personal gain,'' Ms. Hahn said in a prepared
statement.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds ruled Tuesday that PTL
should get back nearly $200,000 of the $363,700 it paid to buy Ms.
Hahn's silence.
</TEXT>
