<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     07-21 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Overruns Rebel Camps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops backed by
helicopter gunships and mortar fire overran six major communist
rebel camps, killing 12 rebels, state-run television reported today.
   The attack brought to 31 the number of people killed across the
Philippines during a 24-hour period in clashes between communist
guerrillas and the army.
   The television quoted Lt. Col. Cris Maralit, spokesman of the
Philippine Constabulary, as saying the offensive occurred Wednesday
in the central province of Negros Occidental, about 310 miles
southeast of Manila.
   Maralit said the soldiers killed 12 rebels and captured 25. They
also recovered 25 high-powered rifles, 3,500 round of assorted
ammunition and about $714, he said.
   The clashes were reported three days after the communist New
People's Army rejected a call by Roman Catholic bishops for a
resumption of peace talks between the government and the rebels.
The talks broke down in February 1987.
   President Corazon Aquino appealed this month for an end to the
killings, saying they are undermining the public's confidence in
her government.
   An association of lawyers charged today that more human rights
lawyers have been killed or harassed during Mrs. Aquino's first two
years in office than in the last nine years of her deposed
predecessor's 20-year rule.
   The Free Legal Assistance Group made the accusation in a report
to a convention of human rights lawyers attended by representatives
from nine countries and the London-based human rights organization
Amnesty International.
   The group said four human rights lawyers were slain over a
nine-year period under Ferdinand Marcos, but five human rights
lawyers have been killed since Mrs. Aquino came to power in
February 1986.
</TEXT>
