<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Brezhnev     07-21 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Brezhnev,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brezhev Clan Stripped of Undeserved Rights, Pravda Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors of former Soviet leader Leonid I.
Brezhnev have been stripped of unmerited privileges and will
receive only the retirement benefits they earned by their own
labor, Pravda said today.
   The decision reported by the Communist Party daily was a further
blow to the legacy of Brezhnev, whose name is now virtually
synonomous with corruption and stagnation and whose reign is blamed
for many of the problems that Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev is
combatting.
   The move also bolsters Gorbachev's call for social justice and
could broaden public faith in his reform program.
   Brezhnev led the move by top-ranking Kremlin officials in 1964
to topple Nikita S. Khrushchev. He replaced Khrushchev as Communist
Party chief and held the post until his death in 1982.
   Galina Brezhnev, his daughter, scandalized Moscow with her
high-rolling lifestyle in the final years of Brezhnev's rule.
   Official media have said Galina's husband, Yuri Churbanov, will
be put on trial for abusing power during his five years as deputy
interior minister and for accepting bribes equivalent to 270 years'
pay for the average Soviet factory worker.
   In an interview with the social minister of the Russian
federation, Viktor A. Kaznacheyev, a Pravda correspondent said
there were rumors that Galina, her brother Yuri, Brezhnev's brother
Yakov and Churbanov's father Mikhail were receiving a ``special
pension.''
   Kaznacheyev replied, ``I can announce that a decision has been
taken in our ministry according to which all the named people have
been deprived of their undeserved pensions and other privileges.''
   He said they had been left with ``normal pensions in accordance
with the positions that they held. And according to the norms that
are defined by legislation.''
   Kaznacheyev did not specify what retirement benefits the members
of the Brezhnev clan would retain. It was a harsh decision by
Soviet standards, under which the survivors of supreme state or
government officials often retain access to private country homes,
lavish Moscow apartments and other perks.
   The Kremlin, however, has been looking with increasing disfavor
on the legacy of the Brezhnev years as Gorbachev wages his campaign
for a modernized economy and a reduction in bureaucrats' powers. In
January, the Soviet government stripped Brezhnev's name from a
city, town squares and a Moscow neighborhood, claiming citizens had
demanded a decisive break with the late leader's legacy of
corruption and economic stagnation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
