<HEAD>Film Director Fined For Animal Cruelty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magistrate fined a prominent television
director $128 Thursday for causing unnecessary suffering to a
turtle, but cleared her on charges of causing similar suffering to
a sparrow.
   Rachel Zen, 37, a director for Radio Television Hong Kong, was
fined in connection with the making of the drama ``Life Goes On''
about a cancer patient.
   In one scene, a woman poured scalding water onto a turtle in a
wok to make a special soup that reputedly helps fight cancer. In
another scene, a sparrow was shown struggling in a burning cage
until it died.
   Zen defended the scenes in court, saying that she wanted to show
the character, a cancer patient's wife, was trying every method to
save her husband.
   The fire scene was to show that life was merciless, she said.
   Zen was found innocent of the sparrow charge, as a hole had been
made to allow the bird to escape. Magistrate Peter Line said she
was negligent but not reckless.
</TEXT>
