<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Floods Bjt   07-21 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Floods, Bjt,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>370 Dead from Floods and Resulting Disease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floods and disease spread by
contaminated water have killed at least 370 people since the annual
monsoon rains began late last month, officials and news reports
said Thursday.
   Cholera and gastroenteritis have reached epidemic proportions in
New Delhi, overwhelming hospitals and prompting severe criticism of
how the city handles water and sewage facilities.
   Cases of the two diseases also have been reported in Uttar
Pradesh and Punjab states north of the capital. Officials
throughout the region have urged people to boil water used for
drinking or cooking.
   Agriculture Minister Bhajan Lal said this year's monsoon, which
began in late June and is expected to last through August, has been
the best for crops since 1983 and should bring good yields of grain
and vegetables for India's 800 million people.
   Crops depend on the annual rains, but the monsoon also is
putting too much water into heavily silted rivers. Water seeping
through garbage and sewage has contaminated wells.
   The number of people killed by drowning or house collapses rose
to to 212 on Thursday with 12 deaths reported in Kashmir, a
northern state, and the western state of Maharashtra, Indian news
agencies reported.
   At least 96 people have died of cholera and gastroenteritis in
New Delhi this month, acording to government figures issued
Thursday. Many were children.
   A New Delhi official, who insisted on anonymity, said more than
7,152 people had been treated in the city's hospitals _ more than
four times the number for all of July 1987. He reported 239
confirmed cholera cases.
   Fifty deaths from the two diseases were reported in Punjab state
to the north and 12 in Ghaziabad, near New Delhi in Uttar Pradesh
state.
   Heavy rains have sent rivers over their banks in 11 of India's
25 states, said A.M. Bhola, a Central Water Commission official. He
estimated at least 2.5 million acres of land were underwater.
   Bhola criticized state governments, which are responsible for
flood control, for concentrating on stop-gap measures and delaying
dam construction. ``We find that the states do not allocate full
funds'' for flood prevention, he said.
   News dispatches said roads were submerged and telephone lines
down in northern Himachal Pradesh state, landslides blocked
highways near the hill town of Darjeeling and rail service was
disrupted in eastern Assam state.
   In New Delhi, the spread of water-borne disease has overtaxed
health facilities to the point that some hospitals put three
children in a bed and patients lie on blankets on the floor.
   Much of the disease is found in densely populated slums near the
Yamuna River that are not connected to the city water system and
rely on wells.
   The opposition Janata (People's) Party demanded this week that
the mayor of New Delhi and its lieutenant governor, the chief
administrator, resign because of ``criminal negligence and
concealment of facts.''
   A party statement said official figures understate the death
toll and 200 people may have perished from water-borne diseases. It
said city officials were ``directly responsible for the spread of
the epidemic.''
   An editorial Thursday in the Times of India said much of the
disease was spread by contaminated water taken by slum dwellers
from shallow wells provided by the city, and declared:
   ``The Delhi administration did not anticipate the water
contamaination, a sad reflection of its indifference. The concerned
officials were simply not ready with a strategy what are considered
to be statistically established annual deaths.''
   City agencies blame each other.
   Officials of the Delhi Development Authority, previously
responsibile for water and sanitation in the slums, say no problems
existed when authority was transferred June 1 to the Delhi
Municipal Corporation.
   Municipal Corporation officials told a news conference Wednesday
garbage had not been collected in the slums since February and the
epidemic was the development agency's fault.
</TEXT>
