<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuns Resign,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuns Resign From Order Over Abortion Stand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two nuns who were threatened with
expulsion for supporting a right to an abortion said today they
have resigned from their order.
   In June, officials of the Roman Catholic Church had sent word
from Rome that they would not proceed with the ``process to
dismiss'' Sisters Barbara Ferraro and Patricia Hussey from the
Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur.
   ``We now believe that the leadership has affirmed the right to
be a member and hold public positions on non-infallible teachings
that differ from official church teachings,'' the nuns said in a
letter of resignation made public today.
   The controversy began in 1984 when Hussey and Ferraro, along
with 95 other Catholics, signed an advertisement in The New York
Times saying that there is a diversity of opinion about abortion
with the church.
   Since then, the church repeatedly has asked Hussey and Ferraro
to retract their support of a woman's right to choose abortion. The
nuns have refused.
</TEXT>
