<DOCNO> AP880721-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CollegeGift     07-21 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-College Gift,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Scholarship For Every Senior</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EMERYVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school district that ``used to be
the laughing stock'' because of its financial troubles now has
enough money to give $1,000 scholarships to all its college-bound
graduates.
   ``We can afford it,'' said Superintendent Peter Corona. ``We've
managed these funds so well that we can now put more into the
education of our students.''
   The scholarship fund is similar to much-publicized private
endowments promised to students in Oakland and New York's Harlem
district. ``Everybody gets a fair shot,'' Corona said. ``We'll pay
for books, supplies, everything.''
   The scholarship plan was approved unanimously Monday by the
Board of Education. It could amount to about $30,000 next year for
the estimated 30 seniors who would be eligible.
   ``These poor kids don't have anything,'' Corona said of students
in the district with one high school, one elementary school and
fewer than 500 students. The district is 99 percent minority.
   ``We're telling them that there's a light at the end of the
tunnel, and we really care about you,'' he said.
   The district, located between Oakland and Berkeley, was broke
and on the verge of extinction five years ago.
   Most students come from single-parent households supported by
welfare, and the district's income had fallen becuase of budget
cutbacks and inefficient management, said Corona, who took over in
1982.
   Corona is credited for much of the district's turnaround since
it was forced to take a $600,000 state bailout loan in 1983. Staff
and expenditures were cut drastically and the district gradually
built its funds, he said.
   ``This district used to be the laughing stock,'' he said. ``It
isn't that way anymore. What we've had to overcome in this district
far surpasses what Iacocca had to do with Chrysler.''
   He said there will be no problem fitting the scholarship fund
into the district's $3 million budget _ which includes a $1.3
million reserve.
   Test scores in the district also have improved dramatically. In
1987, student test scores jumped more than those of any other
district in the state.
</TEXT>
