<DOCNO> AP880721-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--TechTower Bjt   07-21 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Tech Tower, Bjt,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lower The Lights! Go Music!: Orchestrating the Convention for TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California delegation was poised to give
Michael Dukakis a nominating majority. ``Sneak 'em down, sneak 'em
down,'' producer Gary Smith told his light man. ``Stand by, ready
to bring 'em up, ready music, NOT NOW _ NOT NOW... GO! MUSIC!''
   The floor demonstration erupted on cue and Smith, exhilarated by
his handiwork, stood up and clapped before returning to the
business before him: orchestrating the Democratic National
Convention for TV consumption.
   From the Boy Scout color guard to the singing of the national
anthem, through endless speeches and stirring musical interludes,
Smith was on alert, barking instructions and throwing hand signals
to operatives all over the cavernous hall.
   ``Lower the lights! Hold it! Hold it! Lower the podium! And _
music!'' Smith yelled into his telephone headset as a 13-year-old
walked on stage to lead the national anthem.
   No sooner had he finished than Smith was gesticulating wildly at
the podium from his lofty perch atop the camera platform, a
makeshift control area known familiarly as Tech Tower. Nothing
serious. The Boy Scouts in the color guard couldn't figure out when
to leave. ``I told them to watch me,'' he explained.
   Smith, a compact man with glasses and a mustache, relaxed
occasionally with a cigar but spent much of his night in overdrive.
His eyes flickered among five television monitors; he covered his
podium schedule with scribbles; he answered his red phone
incessantly; and he talked steadily into an open headset line to
the stage manager, the TelePrompTer operator, the orchestra
conductor and his partner, the director of the show, Dwight Hemion.
   In contrast, low-key sound and lighting technicians sipped Cokes
and ate tacos at their wide consoles, controlling the convention
atmosphere almost offhandedly between bites.
   ``I've worked for everyone from Sting to Kiss,'' said Don Tyra,
who designed the convention light system. ``This is not as
fast-paced, but it's very critical due to the fact that you're live
to the world. There's no room for error. Any mistake will be seen
by millions.''
   There were plenty of small mistakes, but Smith handled them.
   When an Indiana delegate tried to introduce three governors
using a dead mike, Smith sized up the situation instantly and
switched on a mike at his desk. ``Ladies and gentlemen,'' he said
in the deep voice of a master of ceremonies, referring to his
podium schedule. ``The governor of Colorado, Roy Romer.''
   The schedule was in constant flux as the program fell further
and further behind. Smith said he wasn't worried because a
46-minute ``recess'' had been built in for just such a possibility.
   But when the recess arrived, party officials had not yet decided
whether to cancel it. Long seconds passed with an empty podium and
apparent anarchy in the hall.
   Ah, but there really was someone in charge. ``Some music!''
Smith shrieked into his headset. ``Some music!'' On with the show.
   Between his shouts to the conductor and the simple hand gestures
he used to communicate with Tyra, Smith drew combinations of music
and lighting that literally stopped and started floor
demonstrations in addition to underscoring dramatic or significant
moments.
   Plans for the instant Dukakis would clinch the nomination were
made nearly five hours before it happened, as California Lt. Gov.
Leo McCarthy was telling delegates that the least his state could
do to atone for sending the nation Ronald Reagan was to send George
Bush home, ``wherever that is.''
   ``California's going to be putting him over the top,'' Smith
told Tyra. ``They want California to pass (on the first round of
voting) ... You'll feel it in the hall. We'll bring the lights
down. They'll say California, and we'll bring the lights up.''
   Tyra took the hall slowly into darkness as the moment
approached, then blasted it with light as California announced its
235 votes for Dukakis. The orchestra burst into a medley of ``It's
a Grand Old Flag'' and ``The Washington Post March.'' Smith was so
moved _ or perhaps relieved _ that he stood and clapped briefly
along with the exuberant delegates.
   But he was quickly back to himself. ``Turn the lights down a
little bit,'' he told Tyra. ``Keep the spotlights going.'' A
horrible realization dawned. ``Is NBC gone? IS NBC GONE? YES?''
Into the headset, ``OK! CUT IT!'' The orchestra fell instantly
silent, the demonstrators subsided.
   The networks, it turned out, had abandoned the long
demonstration and returned to local programming. It was a cue that
Smith, the veteran Hollywood professional, could not ignore.
</TEXT>
