<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--ForeignMedia     07-21 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Foreign Media,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Covering the Convention, Poolside</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among European broadcasters covering the
Democratic National Convention, Tony Naets henceforth will be known
as the man who ``blew up'' the foreign pool at Atlanta.
   In this case, the pool in question is a small, orange,
inflatable variety. It sits on bare asphalt in a small clearing
among 22 mobile office trailers clustered together in a fenced-in
section of a subterranean parking lot on the outskirts of the
convention center.
   At night, during convention lulls, the foreign reporters who
work in the complex sit around the pool. They drink beer and toss
coins into the water as they trade gossip and news tidbits.
   ``Some people jokingly call this complex the `European
ghetto,''' said Naets, the New York-based bureau chief of the
European Broadcasting Union, a cooperative that includes 37 nations.
   The EUB is the largest member of the Foreign Broadcasting
Service, an organization set up by the American television networks
to provide working facilities and technical assistance, including
satellite access, to foreign broadcasters.
   ``We've got about 400 people working in this complex,'' said
Bill Headline, a Cable News Network executive who is running the
FBS operation at the convention.
   The broadcasting operations in the FBS complex range in size
from the CBC, which had four trailers and more than 60 employees,
to Monaco Radio, with just one reporter.
   ``This place may not look like much,'' Headline said, ``but it
is a very sophisticated technical operation that provides our
clients with video and audio feeds, a collective studio and
stand-up positions both here and in a sky booth at the convention
hall.''
   The catch, of course, is that all 39 broadcasting agencies using
the facilities must share the one studio and the two stand-up
positions.
   ``These people are professionals and they understand they're at
the bottom of everyone's list,'' Headline said. ``The Democrats are
blatant enough to simply say outright that the foreign broadcasters
really don't matter to them because their viewers aren't voting in
this election.''
   Still, conditions have been trying at times, said Francois
Champey, a broadcaster for La Cinq, a French television station.
   ``It can be pure hell,'' she said. ``There are six or eight
cubicles in the editing trailers and somebody in the one next to me
always seems to be yelling in loud Italian or German when I'm doing
a taped voice-over.''
   Naets looked out the window toward the ``village green'' where
the orange plastic wading pool sat steaming in the sizzling
afternoon sun.
   ``We're taking all of our trailers with us down to New Orleans
for the Republican convention in August,'' he said. ``I'll be
taking the pool along, too, but unfortunately we won't have a
village green down there. Instead, we'll be lined up in grid, like
an American trailer park.''
   What about the coins in the pool?
   ``I'll scoop them out when I deflate the pool since I'm the one
who blew it up,'' he said, laughing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PrisonAnniversary Bjt   07-21 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Anniversary, Bjt,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pontiac Still Dangerous Place 10 Years after Deadly Prison Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former prison guard Danny Dill still has
nightmares about the day 10 years ago when he clung to life, bloody
and swollen, on a cellhouse floor for two hours while rampaging
inmates beat and stabbed three fellow guards to death.
   But Dill dreams that the story of his ordeal at the Pontiac
Correctional Center will make prisons safer.
   ``It was pure hell but I believe God spared me for one reason _
to speak out and try to change things,'' said Dill, who is
completing a book on his experiences at the prison that holds some
of the state's toughest criminals.
   However, some things have not changed since the riot on July 22,
1978. No one has been convicted of murdering the guards. And,
despite improvements in security, officials say another deadly riot
could happen.
   In addition to the three guards who were killed, three were
wounded and there was more than $4 million in damage to the
19th-century prison in a residental neighborhood in this small
northern Illinois city of 11,000 people.
   Dill, 40, left the department after two years on medical leave
and 38 operations in one year. The other wounded guards returned to
Pontiac.
   ``I still have nightmares,'' said Dill. ``I think of my fellow
officers and friends who were tortured and killed.''
   ``This anniversary does not pass easily. We'll always
remember,'' said Corrections Commissioner Michael Lane. ``I believe
the place is more safe and humane than it was 10 years ago, but it
is not safe enough.''
   The violence erupted on a quiet Saturday morning when 550
inmates were being taken from an exercise yard to their cellhouse,
and 600 more prisoners were leaving an auditorium after a movie.
   About 250 riot-equipped officers restored order. The violence
was over in an hour and the prison was declared secure eight hours
after it all began. Hundreds of homemade knives and other weapons
were recovered.
   ``They wanted to take control of the whole prison,'' said Dill.
``Gang leaders had a list of targets _ we were tough but firm and
they didn't like that. I heard every one of our names called out.''
   Dill maintains the riot was planned and should have been
expected. State officials said it was a surprise _ perhaps
triggered by the heat, overcrowding or a gang fight that got out of
control.
   Thirty-one inmates were indicted on charges ranging from
burglary to murder, but only eight eventually were convicted, on
the lesser offenses.
   The guards' families sued prison officials, and in 1984 a
federal jury ruled there was negligence and awarded the plaintiffs
$852,637. However, an appeals court set aside the judgment in 1986
saying the guards knew the risks when they went to work at the
prison.
   ``The state must protect those it throws into snake pits, but
the state need not guarantee that volunteer snake charmers will not
be bitten,'' the appellate opinion said.
   There have been some improvements at Pontiac. There are more
guards and fewer prisoners. The state also has spent about $30.6
million since 1978 for new guard towers, more fencing, catwalks and
better lighting.
   Lane calls those ``Band-aids'' for a prison that needs ``major
surgery.''
   He wants the state Legislature to approve money for new
cellhouses, and to recognize that, despite the opening of some new
prisons, the department needs additional funds to handle an overall
prison population that has doubled to 20,000 in 10 years.
   ``We're out of room now,'' said Lane. ``The population is going
back up at Pontiac. I have no place else to go with them.''
   Since 1978, two other employees have been killed at the Pontiac
prison.
   ``There may be fewer inmates but they are younger, more
aggressive, more volatile and more gang-oriented,'' said Bob
Ellinger, president of the local guard union. ``Pontiac is still a
very dangerous place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
