<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq 4thLd-Writethru a0635 07-21 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0635,0795</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Observers To Go To Gulf To Arrange Cease-fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details of team announced, U.N. saying
separate group will investigate prisoner of war situation. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Photo NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teams of U.N. observers will travel to
Iran and Iraq in the next days to work out details of a cease-fire
in the war and investigate the situation of war prisoners, U.N.
officials said today.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani told reporters that Iran had
given assurances of safe conduct and cooperation for the teams but
that Iraq had not yet made a similar commitment.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar announced Wednesday
that military observers would travel to the warring nations to help
implement a U.N. cease-fire resolution passed one year ago but not
accepted by Iran until Monday.
   Giuliani said Perez de Cuellar was dispatching a second team to
investigate the situation of prisoners of war in both countries.
Repatriation of POWs is part of the U.N. plan to end the nearly
8-year-old war.
   Iraq has complained that thousands of its prisoners of war in
Iran are tortured and murdered.
   Giuliani said the second group was being asembled in Geneva and
was expected to go to Iran over the weekend, then visit Iraq. It
will return to Geneva to prepare its report, he said.
   ``The mission will endeavor to ascertain the facts and inquire
into the concerns expressed by the two governments with a view to
ensuring observance of relevant rules of international humanitarian
law,'' Giuliani said.
   U.N. officials said the eight-member group of military observers
will leave Vienna and Jerusalem in the next few days. It will
include military officers from the U.N. Truce Supervision
Organization based in Jerusalem, two observers already in Tehran
and Baghdad, and Raymond Sommereyns, a senior officer in the office
for Special Political Affairs in New York.
   The exact itinerary was not announced, but the group was
expected first to visit Tehran this weekend, then travel to Baghdad.
   Lt.-Gen. Martin Vadset will head the group.
   ``We will start from scratch, and the main issue now is to have
the parties agree on the technical implementation of a truce which
can form the foundation for the peace negotiations,'' Vadset said.
   The 57-year-old Norwegian general was in Vienna and was
interviewed by Norwegian media.
   The first dozen or so observers eventually will be joined by up
to 250 officers from various countries who would monitor cease-fire
implementation.
   The group investigating the prisoner of war situation includes
Wolfram Karl, professor of international law at the University of
Salzburg, Austria; Torkel Opsahl, professor of international law at
the University of Oslo, Norway; and Maj. Gen. Rene Bats of the
Belgian Army, Giuliani said.
   G.B. Ramcharan, a senior political officer in the U.N.
Secretariat, will accompany the mission, he said.
   Giuliani also said that Perez de Cuellar had no comment on
Iraq's five-point proposal to help implement the cease-fire
resolution.
   That proposal, contained in a letter released Wednesday, called
for direct, formal U.N.-sponsored talks between Iran and Iraq,
along with Iranian promises not to attack Iraqi or other shipping
in the Persian Gulf.
   Iran rejected the idea of direct talks.
   On Monday, Iran announced after a year's delay that it had
accepted Security Council Resolution 598, which demands an
immediate truce and troop withdrawal and sets out a peace plan to
end the war.
   Iraq at first calar a message saying Iraq wants direct talks with
Iran.
   Iraq proposed opening talks at the United Nations, then moving
them to Baghdad and Tehran. Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar
Mahallati told reporters Iran rejected direct talks.
   But another Iranian diplomat, Mohammad Javad Zarif, said his
country will observe a cease-fire during the technical team's visit
and continue an informal cease-fire later if Iraq does the same.
   Iraq raided Iranian industrial targets on Tuesday and Iran
responded in kind on Wednesday. Today, Iraq shelled the village of
Sardasht in northern Azerbaijan province, killing one civilian and
injuring two, IRNA said.
   Perez de Cuellar said the team would limit its consultations to
military aspects of the cease-fire: ``I expect the report of the
team will allow me to announce the implementation of the
resolution.''
   The Peruvian said that would include naming the day the
cease-fire takes effect; setting dates for the beginning and
completion of troop withdrawals and exchanges of war prisoners; and
setting a date for the beginning of negotiations on a lasting peace.
</TEXT>
