<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SterilizationSentence     07-21 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sterilization Sentence,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Suggests Lighter Sentence If Woman Seeks Sterilization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman convicted of criminal neglect in her
son's death has been offered the possiblity of a reduced sentence
if she is sterilized.
   Melody S. Baldwin faces a possible 20-year sentence after
pleading guilty to neglect of a dependent in the Sept. 5, 1986
death of her 4-year-old son, Joshua.
   Miss Baldwin, 29, is seven months pregnant. She was hospitalized
last week for treatment of malnutrition, authorities said.
   When she was unable to appear in court for her sentencing
hearing July 13, Marion Superior Court Judge Roy F. Jones ordered
her confined for the health and safety of the fetus, and appointed
a guardian to protect its interests.
   Miss Baldwin has agreed to surrender the child for adoption.
   At a hearing Wednesday on Miss Baldwin's medical status, Jones
recommended to Miss Baldwin's attorney, Michael J. Donahoe, that
Miss Baldwin undergo sterilization, and suggested that he might
reduce her sentence if the procedure is completed.
   The judge's remarks followed testimony by two physicians that
Miss Baldwin may have tried to interfere with her intravenous
feeding.
   ``From what I have heard already and what's been presented to
the court, I think it's the court's position she's the type of
person that definitely does not need any children in the future,''
Jones said.
   The judge said that although he had no jurisdiction over whether
Miss Baldwin opts for sterilization, ``I don't think it's something
that I think we should leave unsaid.''
   Donahoe said he would pass along the judge's recommendation to
Miss Baldwin, who did not attend the hearing.
   Representatives of the Indiana Civil Liberties Union called
Jones' proposal outrageous and an impermissible condition of
sentencing.
   ``The U.S. Supreme Court struck down the sterilization of
criminals in 1942,'' said ICLU attorney Richard Waples.
   Timothy L. Bookwalter, a lawyer appointed by the judge to guard
the fetus' interests, said he favors sterilization.
   ``We can't protect her every time she gets pregnant. She is a
dangerous person and could kill this kid too,'' he said.
   During Wednesday's hearing, psychiatrist Balwant S. Mallik said
Miss Baldwin is sane but has a personality disorder and is suicidal.
   Testimony during the sentencing hearing July 13 revealed that
Miss Baldwin had induced her son to take lethal levels of
antipsychotic drugs which had been prescribed for her.
   While the child was hospitalized, nurses discovered that someone
had disconnected alarms on the cardiac and respiratory monitors.
His condition deteriorated and he was declared brain dead on Sept.
3. He was removed from artifical life support systems two days
later and was declared dead.
</TEXT>
