<HEAD>Reward Offered For Arrest of Illegal Dumpers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROXBURY TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck company owner says he is
sick of medical waste washing up on New Jersey and New York beaches
and is posting $10,000 to help find the culprits.
   ``I'm totally disgusted,'' said Brad Honigsberg. ``It's a
natural God-given resource that should not be denied any citizen.
To have a few discourteous people acting in a criminal fashion ...
''
   Honigsberg said Wednesday the reward is being offered in the
name of his air freight trucking company, Air Contact Transport Inc.
   The 39-year-old Hopatcong resident said he is a longtime
beachgoer and has many friends who rely on the summertime beach
economy. He said he decided to post the reward after visiting Point
Pleasant beach this week.
   ``It's absolutely dead down there,'' he said. ``The boardwalk
should be teeming with people.''
   Syringes, vials of blood and other waste have washed up on the
New Jersey shore this summer, and miles of popular beaches on New
York's Long Island were closed over the July 4 weekend because of
medical waste.
