<2ND_LINE>PM-Escape Attempt, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0613,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convict Nearly Escapes Prison Posing As Lawyer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with the grafs to ADD that inmate didn't get past
interview room door; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Inside the ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug dealer who disguised himself as a
lawyer nearly escaped from prison but was tripped up by his
distinctive walk, authorities said.
   Elrader ``Ray Ray'' Browning Jr. was wearing street clothes, an
Afro wig and false mustache and was carrying a briefcase and a copy
of the Rules of Criminal Procedure when he summoned a guard and
asked to be released from the prison's attorney interview room
Saturday, said Assistant U.S. Attorney John Gordon.
   A guard, who hadn't recognized Browning on sight, did recognize
his jaunty gait, Gordon said. The inmate got no farther than the
interview room door, the prosecutor said.
   Inside the briefcase, authorities found a driver's license, a
credit card, a jail jumpsuit and the glue that apparently had been
used to affix the mustache.
   ``All we can hypothesize at this point is he'd been squirreling
away these items,'' Gordon said.
   Loose ceiling tiles in the interview room at Terminal Island
federal prison indicated that the items may have been brought in by
visitors to the low- to medium-security facilty over the last few
weeks, he said.
   Browning, said to be the leader of a $2 million-a-month cocaine
and heroin ring, acted as his own attorney during a trial at which
he was convicted of 43 drug-related felonies. He faces a mandatory
term of life without parole at sentencing Aug. 22.
   Deputy U.S. Marshal Walter Dayton said Browning and another man
met with attorney Larry Elkins in the interview room Saturday.
   Elkins left about an hour before the escape attempt, Gordon
said. He added that authorities had been unable to reach Elkins. A
call to his office before business hours today went unanswered.
   The incident was the seventh escape or attempted escape in the
last four months at Terminal Island, the only federal prison in the
Los Angeles area.
   Warden R.D. Brewer attributed the recent rash of escape attempts
to a nearly 50 percent increase in the number of prisoners awaiting
sentencing housed at Terminal Island, which he said was never
designed to house the kind of high-risk inmates often held there.
</TEXT>
