<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0653 07-21 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0653,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets, Chinese Set Peace Talks On Cambodia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3rd graf ``This is'' with further detail, including
names of officials</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and China have agreed to meet
in Beijing next month in an attempt to work out a peace settlement
for Vietnamese-occupied Cambodia, a U.S. official said Thursday.
   If successful, the talks could remove the remaining obstacle to
a summit meeting between the world's two biggest communist powers,
who have been at odds for some 30 years, the official said.
   This is the first time the two sides are holding a meeting with
Cambodia as the sole agenda item, although they have been
conducting periodic talks on the foreign ministry level since 1982,
the official said. The Soviets will be represented at the August
meeting by Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev and the Chinese by
foreign ministry official Zhu Qizhen, the official said.
   While neither the Soviets nor the Chinese have a direct role in
the long-running Cambodia conflict, both powers hold sway over
allies who are directly involved.
   Secretary of State George Shultz was informed of the planned
talks during his visit to Beijing last week, said the official,
speaking only on condition of anonymity.
   But he cautioned that the success of the Cambodia meeting hinges
on the upcoming ``cocktail party'' talks among the three-party
Cambodian guerrilla coalition, Vietnamese officials and the
Vietnam-appointed government in the capital of Phnom Penh.
   The talks are scheduled to begin Monday in Indonesia, but Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, former head of the Cambodian resistance movement,
is already predicting failure.
   Sihanouk, who resigned this month from the presidency of the
three-party guerrilla coalition, accused Vietnam on Thursday of
being unwilling to conduct serious talks.
   Vietnam moved into Cambodia in 1979, driving out the
Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge rulers who killed hundreds of thousands
of people in their bloody four-year rule. China has promised Shultz
it would seek to prevent Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot from returning
to Cambodia, the official said.
   Under pressure from Moscow, Vietnam announced in May that it
would withdraw its estimated 125,000 troops by 1990.
   The U.S. official said China had indicated to the United States
that Soviet cooperation over Cambodia would clear the way for a
rapprochement. China had also been holding out for a Soviet
withdrawal from Afghanistan, which began in May after more than
eight years of occupation.
</TEXT>
