<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0620,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Previous Pact With Directors Reportedly Stalling Writers
Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with two grafs to CORRECT that two sources were not
negotiators; piks up graf 3, ``The two</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of the striking Writers Guild of
America say they were told by the head of 20th Century Fox that a
``gentleman's agreement'' between producers and directors has
blocked a settlement of the walkout.
   According to two of 40 guild members who met Tuesday with Barry
Diller, chairman and chief executive officer of Fox Inc., Diller
said the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers agreed
privately with the Directors Guild of America last year on payments
for TV reruns.
   The two writers spoke on condition that they not be identified.
   ``He said that the producers had made a gentleman's agreement
with the DGA that they would not give the WGA a penny more for
residuals,'' one of the writers in attendance said. ``He said that
the producers felt obligated to uphold that agreement. He said, `We
cannot go back on our word to the Directors Guild.'''
   Diller would neither confirm nor deny the report.
   Glenn Gumpel, executive director of the DGA, said that he ``was
not going to contradict Barry Diller's statement.'' However, he
would not say whether the DGA had entered into such an agreement
with the producers.
   ``We don't negotiate for the WGA,'' Gumpel said. ``Writers are
entitled to ask for and negotiate for whatever they want to.''
   Cheryl Rhoden, spokeswoman for the Writers Guild, said Diller's
reported admission ``in the 20th week of the strike answers many
questions about the refusal of the alliance to negotiate.''
   ``I got tremendously uspet when I heard about Diller's
comment,'' said Del Reisman, vice president of the WGA and
co-chairman of the negotiating committee.
   ``But if such a pact existed, why didn't he talk about it
earlier? It's incredibly late in the negotiationg process to come
out with that kind of statement.''
   The WGA and the producers have been sharply divided over
payments for reruns since the strike by the 9,000 film and TV
scriptwriters began March 7.
   Union leaders have said repeatedly that the producers have been
largely unwilling to make any compromises on payments for TV shows
rebroadcast domestically and all programs shown overseas.
   The strike has resulted in sweeping layoffs throughout the
entertainment industry.
   The DGA is considered to be one of Hollywood's most potent
unions because its members, once on strike, can shut down all
television and film production. Effects from a writers' strike, on
the other hand, are felt more slowly.
   Herb Steinberg, a spokesman for the producers' alliance, said
Diller's remarks were taken out of context.
   ``What the alliance said to the directors was that there was no
more money for residuals,'' Steinberg said. ``To give the writers
any more would destroy any credibility. They have to be
consistent.''
   ``The WGA is not going to get any more (for television
residuals) than any other union. That has been our bargaining
position from the very beginning and we have not wavered from that.
The writers don't deserve any more'' than the DGA, Steinberg said.
   Negotiators for the WGA and the producers are scheduled to meet
with each other and a federal mediator on Saturday. The talks will
be the first between the full negotiating teams since June 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
