<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Born in the USA'' is OK in communist East
Germany.
   So is rock star Bruce Springsteen, who brought down the house
when he sang his popular tune before the country's largest-ever
gathering of rock fans.
   The Communist Party daily newspaper Neues Deutschland said
Thursday the song points out ``the senselessness of war.''
   ``Springsteen's sympathy goes out to those who must live on the
dark side of the American reality,'' the story said.
   Springsteen performed for 160,000 screaming, cheering fans
Tuesday night. Hundreds of people at the four-hour concert waved
handmade American flags.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rocker David Lee Roth heats up a stadium
when he performs.
   Thirty-five spectators were treated for heat exhaustion at his
concert Wednesday night.
   ``Three of the kids were treated for heat-related illnesses and
one for drunkenness,'' said American Red Cross spokesman Patrick
Fitzsimmons. ``None of them were serious.''
   The building had been cooled to 65 degrees before the concert,
``but the body heat just caused the temperature to soar,'' said
Civic Coliseum director Rick Hamilton.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz singer Ella Fitzgerald, who took a
tumble on the stage of the Hollywood Bowl, came back from a short
break and sang ``Since I Fell For You.''
   Miss Fitzgerald, 70, fell and injured a leg as she was moving
downstage Wednesday night.
   ``I think the light got in my eyes,'' she said Thursday. ``The
lights were changing and I didn't see that (one) step down as I
moved to sing to the audience. It's more embarrassing than
anything.''
   Miss Fitzgerald's backup trio rushed to her aid, along with
people from the wings of the stage.
   ``It's OK. I'm OK. I'll just sing from down here,'' she said.
   Miss Fitzgerald underwent open heart surgery in September 1986
and was treated for complications of diabetes in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sonia Braga says movie actors who hang out in
their dressing rooms between scenes are missing out on a chance to
learn about their craft.
   ``An actor should learn about movies,'' Ms. Braga says in the
Aug. 8 issue of Us magazine. ``I don't want to show up for a movie
and face some kind of camera I've never seen before, or some new
light I've never seen.''
   The Brazilian actress, who appeared in ``Dona Flor and her Two
Husbands,'' ``Kiss of the Spider Woman,'' ``The Milagro Beanfield
War'' and most recently ``Moon Over Parador,'' says she wandered
around the set between scenes, following the lighting crew or
dropping in on wardrobe.
   ``You have to do things,'' she says. ``Otherwise, it gets
boring.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City Mayor Edward Koch wore the
Dublin lord mayor's gold chain of office for a few moments Thursday
and said he wished New York mayors had something similar.
   The heavy chain and seal was draped over Koch's shoulders by
Mayor Ben Briscoe, who was at Dublin Airport to greet his New York
counterpart on his first visit since 1982.
   ``It's the kind of chain I would hope to see mayors in New York
City have, but I don't think our people would have it,'' he said.
   Koch and Briscoe's jobs are vastly different.
   The Dublin mayor is elected by fellow city councilors, the
functions are largely ceremonial and the term is one year.
Re-election rarely occurs.
   Koch is here to join a pilgrimage led by Cardinal John O'Connor
of New York to promote peace in Northern Ireland.
   ``I am a Jewish soldier in a Christian army at this moment,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. David Karnes says the hour he spent
Thursday reading the weather and spinning records enabled him to
work out his latent disc-jockey tendencies.
   The Republican senator, who is running against former Gov. Bob
Kerrey in the general election, did the stint on KQKQ-FM's
drive-time ``Breakfast Flakes'' show.
   He dedicated the Pointer Sisters' song ``Jump'' to his 4- and
5-year-old daughters, who he said were jumping on the bed when he
left home.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MARANELLO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enzo Ferrari, the 90-year-old sports car
builder and racing pioneer, is suffering from kidney disease.
   ``He is being treated at home for kidney troubles and for
ailments typical of his age,'' said Franco Gozzi, spokesman of the
Ferrari racing team. ``We can't say he is in good health, but
certainly he is not in critical condition.''
   Company officials commented on Ferrari's health Thursday in
response to a Milan newspaper report that he was in serious
condition.
   Ferrari, founder and chairman of the company which makes luxury
sport cars and renowned Formula One racers, was forced to reduce
his business activities last February when he got influenza.
   Ferrari's health prevented him from meeting Pope John Paul II
when he visited the factory last month.
</TEXT>
