<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Defector     07-21 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Defector,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Rejects Claim on Libya Raid Made by American Defector</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Thursday denied
charges by an American who defected to the Soviet Union that the
United States targeted the French Embassy when it bombed Libya in
April 1986.
   Deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley called the allegations
``ridiculous and absolutely untrue.''
   Glen Michael Souther, a former U.S. Navy intelligence specialist
who recently defected to the Soviet Union, said on Soviet
television Wednesday that he had access to secret photographs used
to plan the bombing attack on Tripoli. He said that he learned that
the French Embassy was a target several days before the raid.
   Foreign reporters who visited the bombed area after the raid saw
damage to the French Embassy in the Bin Ashur neighborhood of
Tripoli.
   A Soviet announcer charged that the embassy was targeted in
retaliation for France's refusal to allow U.S. bombers to fly over
its territory en route to Libya from bases in Britain.
   The Pentagon had no immediate comment on Souther's allegations.
   However, two days after the raid, then-Defense Secretary Caspar
W. Weinberger said that damage to the French Embassy may have been
caused by an American plane that was apparently shot down in the
raid and was not the result of the embassy being a target or near a
target.
   ``The simple correct answer is, we don't know how that (damage)
occurred,'' Weinberger said then. ``But it's a mile away from any
of the target areas and it was specifically rejected as a target
even though there's a large intelligence building right next to the
French Embassy.''
   Mrs. Oakley said U.S. diplomats have requested Soviet assistance
in arranging a meeting with Souther. Such meetings are considered
normal practice for the purpose of ensuring that a defector is
acting under his own free will.
</TEXT>
