<DOCNO> AP880721-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Networks     07-21 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Networks,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Might Cut Back on Republican Convention Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC might cut back its prime-time coverage of the
GOP convention in August because the Democratic National Convention
has been such a bore, ABC News President Roone Arledge said
Thursday.
   ``It might be less at the Republican convention. Depends on what
they do,'' Arledge said.
   NBC News President Lawrence K. Grossman said NBC would not cut
back on the GOP out of fairness after giving so much prime time
exposure to the Democrats, but would reassess the amount of
coverage in 1992.
   CBS, which scheduled an extra hour of coverage for Thursday,
plans to stick to the same schedule for the Republicans and defends
extensive prime time coverage in the future. ``I'd do more, not
less,'' said anchor Dan Rather.
   Ratings for convention coverage have been in a steady decline
since 1976. Ratings for this year's Democratic convention were
boosted by Jesse Jackson's appearance on Tuesday night, but overall
have been about 10 percent lower than in 1984.
   ``Regardless ratings and shares and so forth, this is a moment,
perhaps the only moment, and there are four days of it, when the
American people can get to know the political leaders,'' said CBS
News President Howard Stringer. ``Otherwise it's a minute-twenty
and sound bites.''
   But Arledge said he thinks the spectacle of a staged convention
``increases the cynicism about politics in this country,
particularly among young people who look at this and just can't
imagine that the windbags and speeches and demonstrations and
orchestrated happenings are an important part of the political
process.
   ``If the parties want to continue to do that, it's their
business, not mine. I think it's a mistake,'' Arledge said.
   Earlier this year, the networks were excited by the prospect of
contested nominations in both parties and the idea of returning to
gavel-to-gavel coverage was even discussed. But by the time the
Democrats arrived in Atlanta, there was little drama left.
   Nevertheless, all three networks devoted two hours a night of
prime time to the convention.
   As for future coverage, Arledge said, ``I think it might be less
in '92, if the situation were identical.''
   NBC's Grossman said he would cut back on coverage in New Orleans
when the GOP meets if the network had not devoted more time to the
Democrats. Vice President George Bush has the nomination sewed up,
but he hasn't yet selected a running mate.
   ``On a basic editorial judgment we would be hard put not to go
to an hour special a night summarizing the convention in New
Orleans, except for the fundamental issues of fairness and
balance,'' Grossman said.
   The networks are not constrained by law to give equal time
because the conventions are considered news events.
   As for 1992 prospects, Grossman said, ``I think the networks
will all play a role, but it would be hard to think that we would
give the same kind of coverage. We may do hourly summaries.''
   Former CBS anchor Walter Cronkite, who has been covering
conventions since 1952, agrees they have become less functional.
   ``We are in the position of covering a staged entertainment, and
it turns out the parties are not nearly as good at that as they are
at politics.''
   But he did not favor cutting coverage. ``I think it's a shame
the public is not more attentive to these proceedings. The mere
gathering of these people in one hall is, I think, fascinating into
itself.''
   ``Not everything in life can be or should be made for
television. Some things are more important,'' Rather said. ``Not
everything in life can be or should made to conform to
entertainment values.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
