<HEAD>U.S. Rejects Bid By Nicaraguan Envoy To Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday it has
rejected a request by Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann to
return to the United States for the purpose of resuming his duties
as Sandinista representative to the Organization of American States.
   Tunnermann and seven Nicaraguan colleagues were expelled from
the United States last week after Sandinista authorities ordered
home eight U.S. diplomats from Managua, including Ambassador
Richard Melton.
   In rejecting his visa request, State Department deputy
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said that Tunnermann had abused his
privileges of residence in the United States and therefore is not
welcome in this country.
   Tunnermann, who served as both ambassador to the United States
and the OAS, denied the charges and said the administration had
exceeded its authority in expelling a diplomat accredited to the
OAS.
