<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   07-21 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Killed, Violence in Jerusalem and West Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos JRL1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Palestinians were killed and 16 wounded
Thursday in clashes with Israeli soldiers in the West Bank, and
Jerusalem police used bulldozers to clear streets of crowds
protesting the early closing of Arab schools.
   It was the second day in a row that three Palestinians were
fatally shot and was among the worst in seven months of Palestinian
rebellion.
   At least 231 Palestinians have been killed since since the
uprising began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million who live in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel has occupied since capturing them
from Jordan and Egypt in the Middle East 1967 war. Four Israelis
also have been slain.
   Army authorities imposed curfews on about 225,000 Palestinians
in the occupied areas in an effort to end the violence and to
punish those who joined a commercial strike ordered by the
rebellion's underground leadership.
   A new directive from the underground leadership, the 22nd since
the violence began, praised Israeli Arabs in Jerusalem and
elsewhere for joining the uprising and warned against Israeli
secret agents posing as ``journalists or news agency reporters .. .
in spying and arresting people.''
   Thursday's protests stemmed from Palestinian anger over an
Israeli order to close the schools Thursday, a month early.
   They swept from Arab east Jerusalem to the West Bank cities of
Nablus, Hebron and Ramallah. Protesters burned tires, blocked roads
and hurled stones at Israeli vehicles and police.
   West Bank schools, which 300,000 Palestinian children attend,
have been closed more than four months of this academic year by
army order. Teachers wanted hold classes through the summer to make
up, but Israeli officials said schools had become centers of unrest
and ordered them closed.
   About 600 Arabs marched through the winding streets of the
open-air marketplace of Nablus, the West Bank's largest city 45
miles north of Jerusalem, chanting anti-Israeli slogans and waving
outlawed Palestinian flags.
   Soldiers opened fire and two Palestinians were killed, the army
said.
   Officials at two Nablus hospitals said 15 people were wounded,
including three 13-year-olds, and identified two of the dead as
Maher Abu Ghazaleh, 22, and Hussam Abdel Aziz, 23, both of Nablus.
   Army spokesmen said Palestinians and soldiers fought in the
Tulkarem refugee camp and the nearby village of Zinabeh.
   Officials at the Tulkarem hospital said soldiers opened fire,
killing 17-year-old Muhamad Seth and wounding another demonstrator.
   A military spokesman confirmed one Palestinian wounded and said
the army was investigating whether there were other casualties.
   Soldiers imposed curfews on Nablus, Tulkarem and Beit Sahour in
the West Bank and on the Jabaliya, Khan Yunis and Beach Camp
refugee camps in the Gaza Strip.
   At Beach Camp, soldiers fired rubber bullets to disperse
protesters, an Arab reporter said. He said a 15-year-old boy lost
an eye and nine people were injured.
   Protests in east Jerusalem began in Arab neighborhoods and on
Salah Eddin, the main commercial street across from the walled Old
City.
   Police Chief Yosef Yehudai called them ``a spontaneous eruption
of emotions over the end of the school year.'' He said 48
Palestinians were arrested.
   Arab children hurled rocks at passing cars on Salah Eddin,
smashing the windows of a police van, authorities said.
   Stones also shattered windows in an Israeli-owned bank, four
homes and a restaurant in a tourist area near the biblical Mount of
Olives. Police used bulldozers to clear streets of protesters and
stones, Israel radio reported.
   Other protests were broken up by police on horseback and riot
control troops with clubs. Soldiers overturned the carts of Arab
bread vendors in trying to clear protesters from the central bus
station.
   ``There were a lot of kids. They were chanting something and
threw many stones. I was a little afraid,'' Ahuva Schindler of Los
Angeles, a visitor to one of the homes that were stoned, said on
the radio.
   About 100 Jewish seminary students prayed for an end to the the
violence, the newspaper Yediot Ahronot reported. It said they
gathered at the grave of the 16th century rabbi Isaac Luria, known
as the ``Holy Lion,'' during a pilgrimage to the holy city of Safed
in Galilee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
