<DOCNO> AP880721-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FoxValleyProstitution     07-21 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fox Valley Prostitution,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>5-Month Trial Shows Other View of Community</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>APPLETON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-month trial involving prostitution
and racketeering turned over quite a few rocks in this quiet
community, and residents haven't liked the secrets which came into
view.
   Witnesses, many of whom were granted immunity from prosecution,
told about prostitution, arson and even soliciting a killing.
   ``We have been shocked by the ugliness of this organization, how
big it was, how extensive it was,'' said Mayor Dorothy Johnson.
   The jury, selected from Racine County about 125 miles to the
south, began deliberating Thursday in the case against William
Evers. Evers, 49, who once owned massage parlors, is charged with
three counts of racketeering, 32 prostitution-related charges and
one misdemeanor theft charge.
   In closing arguments, defense attorney Eric Stearn said the
community was trying to blame Evers for all its problems.
   At a preliminary hearing in September, in fact, a judge blamed
the community.
   ``None of it would have been possible without the patronage of
the people of the Fox River Valley,'' Reserve Judge Albert Twesme
of Galesville had said. ``They are the ones who made all this
despicable behavior possible. It was they who made these activities
lucrative.''
   Twesme said he had been shocked by testimony that some of the
prostitutes were busiest after Sunday church services.
   Appleton, a community about 64,000 on the Fox River in
northeastern Wisconsin, is home to several paper companies, a
university, freshly painted homes, clean streets and plenty of
smiling faces.
   ``This is considered a family community,'' said William Welch,
president of the Fox Cities Chamber of Commerce.
   Outagamie County Assistant District Attorney John Des Jardins,
who called more than 100 witnesses and introduced nine boxes of
state exhibits, described a criminal enterprise that ran a
prostitution network in Appleton, Oshkosh and Green Bay dating back
to the late 1970s.
   Johnson and investigators pointed out that many of the patrons
of the businesses came from other areas to Appleton, which has
become a retailing center in the area.
   ``If anything, perhaps government and attitudes here are so
clean that people are so circumspect that when a problem like this
comes up, it gets more attention,'' said Welch.
   Des Jardins said prostitution was no greater a problem in the
Fox Valley than in other areas of similar size but the Evers case
may have opened peoples' eyes.
   ``It wasn't running rampant, but there was a lot more going on
that some people thought,'' the prosecutor said.
   Twesme said he did not know how it could have gone on so long in
the community.
   ``How is it able to go on in all our metropolitan area? Maybe
people look the other way, I don't know,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
   Johnson, mayor since 1980, said the city never turned its eyes
away and she believed it was a credit to the city that local police
and authorities pursued the case.
   She said Appleton was one of the state's fastest-growing cities
and the case described in court is ``not an unusual situation by
any means in any city that is growing.''
   Investigators first began receiving some information on the
businesses in 1980. The Appleton investigation began in late 1986
and officers over the years made arrests for ordinance violations,
said Appleton Police Lt. John Parker.
   ``It was an unusual situation for this community. We knew it was
there but we had to build our case,'' Parker said.
   ``You can keep arresting the girls and the proprietors and
managers,'' Parker added, ``but what good does it do?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
