<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Republican-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru a0693 07-21 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Republican-Ethics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0693,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Crow About ``Democratic Sleaze Factor''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of ``sow'' in 10th graf bgng ``The
Republicans.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright's role in this week's
convention has underscored a ``Democratic sleaze factor'' that's
stifled virtually all rhetoric about Attorney General Edwin Meese,
Republican critics said Thursday.
   ``I think they have felt uncomfortable talking about sleaze when
the camera right over the shoulder of the speaker focuses on Jim
Wright,'' said Rep. Guy Vander Jagt, R-Mich.
   ``I'm never happy when you're talking about which sleaze is the
greatest,'' he added, ``but I sure don't think the Democrats want
to open the door to the debate as to whose sleaze stain is
biggest.''
   Capping a weeklong GOP ``truth squad'' effort, a panel of
Republican officials launched some of their sharpest attacks on
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis, and insisted that ethical
questions surrounding Meese and others in the Reagan administration
have been effectively defused by Wright's problems.
   Wright is under investigation by the House Ethics Committee over
allegations that he channeled royalties from a book of his writings
into his campaign fund and that the book was edited by a staffer on
his congressional payroll. He has rejected any suggestions of
wrongdoing.
   The Texas congressman is presiding over this week's Democratic
National Convention, despite some suggestions that he should have
stepped aside.
   Meese, who has resigned and will leave office next month, has
been the subject of two investigations over his finances and
ethics. Independent counsel James McKay, in a report filed this
week, said Meese had probably violated some tax and
conflict-of-interest laws, but said he found no grounds to indict
him.
   While Meese's name has been mentioned during the week, his legal
troubles have not been a central issue during the convention.
   Mike McCurry, spokesman for the Democratic convention, said that
in general the Democrats have steered away from highlighting
Meese's problems because ``we felt in was important to stay focused
on delivering a positive message about what Democrats would do.''
   The Republicans also worked hard to sow some divisions among the
Democratic ticket of Dukakis and Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   Vander Jagt said Dukakis has benefited throughout the primary
process because he's been running against Jesse Jackson, and that
casts him in the role of the moderate alternative.
   With the more conservative Bentsen at his side, Vander Jagt
said, voters will begin to view Dukakis as a liberal, damaging
Democratic hopes.
   ``It is Lloyd Bentsen that is going to help us turn off the
Reagan Democrats and conservative, because by comparing Bentsen's
voting record and what Dukakis is for, that paints Mike Dukakis as
the lefty, liberal that he is,'' Vander Jagt said.
   ``It is Bentsen that is our salvation,'' Vander Jagt said. ``It
has been a great convention for Republicans.''
</TEXT>
