<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-WaterProblems     07-21 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Water Problems,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Counties Declare Emergency Because Of Water Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two counties have declared states of
emergency because of nearly 100 complaints from people who say
agricultural irrigation has caused their residential wells to dry
up.
   One legislator said he has seen water sprayers going in the heat
of the day and sending water onto roads.
   The declarations were made by Kankakee County Board Chairman
Marwood Hendrix and Iroquois County Board Chairman Russell
Rosenboom.
   The declaration means ``the county has exhausted all of its
resources and this allows the county to get outside help,'' said
Vicki Senesac, office manager of the Kankakee County Planning
Department.
   State Sen. Jerome Joyce and state Rep. Phil Novak said the
Illinois State Water Survey would investigate the complaints about
irrigation and well failures.
   The Illinois Department of Agriculture also is to send staff
members to the area next week to determine how many high-capacity
irrigation wells there are in the two counties.
   Officials of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers went to Papineau
on Wednesday at the request of Ted Horner, Iroquois County
Emergency Services Coordinator, to see if they could help.
   Corps officials said they could transport water, but that local
governments would have to pay if new wells were drilled.
   ``One optimistic thing is that we have got the state agencies to
begin to look at these complaints,'' said Novak. ``This is becoming
a serious issue about water rights and the allocation of
underground water is becoming very serious.''
   Joyce called for a show of ``neighborliness.''
   ``Yesterday, I took a drive around Pembroke Township and over
around Papineau, and right at high noon I saw some irrigation
equipment shooting water up in the air _ the most inefficient
method at that time of day particularly,'' said Joyce. ``Also, on
the road to the Iroquois Conservation Area, you could stop in the
middle of the road and get your car washed.''
</TEXT>
