<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CVN--ConventionAbroad     07-21 0898</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Convention Abroad,0939</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreigners View The Democratic Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Le Monde (independent), said in an editorial Thursday on the
Democratic convention: ``Barefoot in sneakers, installed at the end
of a sofa next to his wife, a man quietly watches television. At a
certain moment, he smiles, lifts his arm half-way but refuses the
glass of champagne offered to him. The Democratic Party convention
has just made him its candidate for the election for president of
the United States. The hall rocks, one can see delegates wave their
signs, shout and cheer. He, too, is visibly happy _ but there's
really no reason he should move from his seat. After all, it's only
the next day that he will make his acceptance speech.
   ``The scene takes place in a large hotel suite, several hundred
meters (yards) from the convention: astonishing scene, scene which
would be intimate if, here like elsewhere, the television cameras
were not present, for, as always, it is an arranged scene. We will
never know how Michael Dukakis might have behaved in `true
intimacy.' ''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRAZIL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Correspondent Paulo Francis of the liberal Folha de Sao Paulo
newspaper of Sao Paulo said in a report from Atlanta: ``Dukakis'
ideas are good. But I confess I'm little scared, because he has so
many ideas. This almost always fouls things up. Better to be a big
healthy dope like Ronald Reagan and confuse Bolivia with Brazil
than to be a guy who insists on interfering everywhere, like
Dukakis.''
   The independent newspaper Jornal do Brasil of Rio said: ``A
campaign promise is something so sacred that it doesn't occur to
the American politician not to keep it, when assuming an executive
post. That's why the backroom negotiations between Michael Dukakis
and Jesse Jackson, before the elaboration of the candidate dukakis'
final platform, were so important. ... It is one of the greatest
demonstrations of how the mechanism of democracy works, when it is
practiced conscientiously.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTH AFRICA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Leave us alone,'' was Foreign Minister Pik Botha's message to
Dukakis.
   ``Fight your election on American issues,'' Botha said. ``They
are important and complicated enough. Leave us alone to solve our
problems.'' He spoke Wednesday night at a news conference.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ISRAEL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir expressed hope Thursday the next
administration retains friendly ties with Israel.
   But an American Jewish leader said Jewish voters will reserve
judgment _ and votes _ for Dukakis until he clarifies his positions
on Israel.
   ``There should be concern not to lose the Jewish votes,'' Israel
Singer, executive director of the World Jewish Congress, said on
Israel's Army radio. ``In previous elections the Jewish votes
almost always went for the Democrats, but he must worry not to lose
them.
   He said many Jewish voters are still ``waiting'' to hear from
Dukakis about Middle East issues.
   Shamir remained loyal to a pledge of neutrality in internal U.S.
political debates.
   ``America is a very large country ... and what will matter is
the administration's policy and the majority of the American public
opinion,'' he said.
   ``I hope that from this point of view, nothing will change and
relations between Israel and the United States will continue to be
those of allies, like today.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST GERMANY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On Jesse Jackson's appearance at the convention, the
conservative newspaper Die Welt said Thursday: ``Up to now, such a
thing has not been part of any nominating convention.''
   ``It was sheer Jackson lyrics _ the kind of stuff that has
captured his public and is loaded with both anger and hope,'' said
the Bonn-based paper.
   ``Each thoughtful analysis reveals him ever more strongly as the
champion of the underdogs and underpriviledged in America.''
   The conservative Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper was
not complimentary.``Jackson was defeated just like the five other
Democratic challengers who lost to Dukakis in the primaries,'' it
said. ``Even with the weight of supporters in Atlanta, he cannot
enforce even a break in the convention's meetings if it is not the
will of the Dukakis troops.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEXICO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Mexico City's independent El Universal wrote: ``In the
Convention of Atlanta the liberal character with which the
Democratic Party historically has navigated in the stormy waters of
U.S. politics has been ratified. ... Abroad, the nomination of
Dukakis encourages groups that traditionally have wanted to find in
the Democratic Party a synonym for better understanding between the
United States and the nations of the Third World.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWITZERLAND</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Der Bund (Bern, independent)
   ``One man has been the focus of the Democratic Party convention
in Atlanta: Jesse Jackson. He dominated the media, the politicians
and the delegates. His speech captivated those listening in the
overcrowded Omni Coliseum and millions of television viewers,''
wrote Der Bund, an independent in Bern.
   Tages-Anzeiger, a Zurich independent paper, said: ``Jesse
Jackson has made it: he said firmly and clearly what he has always
said, and he preserved party unity.''
   The conservative Neue Zuercher Zeitung wrote of the Democratic
platform: ``The document is no longer the famous laundry list,
summarizing the causes of all Democratic interest groups and making
concrete demands. Rather, it is a paper limited to general
guidelines. Yet this effort does not seem to have turned out very
concise or powerful. (...)
   ``The Democrats now want to rebuild the nation with a national
investment strategy. To this end, they promise everything good
under the sun without listing the costs.''
</TEXT>
