<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Kitty-Homeless     07-21 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Kitty-Homeless,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nominee's Wife Lunches With Homeless On Day Of Convention Climax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis ate lunch with homeless people
Thursday and promised to do something about their plight as a
``very active first lady'' if her husband's bid for the presidency
succeeds.
   Mrs. Dukakis, who interrupted preparations for Michael Dukakis'
coronation as the Democratic presidential nominee to eat at a
restaurant for the homeless on the fringe of the city's downtown,
also criticized President Reagan's social agenda.
   ``Homeless-ness is a national problem ... a national tragedy,''
Mrs. Dukakis said. ``We will work together, I hope, under the
leadership of President Michael S. Dukakis in January.''
   If Dukakis is elected, ``I would be a very active first lady,
involved in this issue and other issues that I feel are
important,'' she said.
   Inside the 458 Cafe, Mrs. Dukakis ate lunch at a table with two
homeless men. She was joined by Mayor Andrew Young, his wife Jean,
Mrs. Young's mother and a A.B. Short, local minister who helps run
the center.
   She selected lasagna from a menu that also offered roast beef
and tuna casserole.
   For most of the meal, Mrs. Dukakis chatted with Joey Washington,
a homeless Vietnam veteran seated across from her. Washington said
he suffered from post traumatic stress syndrome, which led to
impulsive behavior.
   Leaning across the table, Mrs. Dukakis asked whether Washington
would consider it prying if she asked him to discuss his life since
returning from Vietnam.
   He said he became disenchanted by anti-war protests, and on his
first day back in the United States ``some long-hair spit on my
shoes.''
   Mrs. Dukakis told Washington that ``even if we love our country,
we have to admit that sometimes Americans can be misguided.'' It
was not clear whether she was referring to the protests or to U.S.
policy toward Vietnam.
   About a dozen other homeless men ate in the small cafe as Mrs.
Dukakis chatted with Washington.
   Outside, she told reporters that the Reagan administration's
spending priorities had led to reductions in programs to aid the
homeless.
   ``Leadership at the federal level has to be there and it's
missing today,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
