<DOCNO> AP880721-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     07-21 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aug. 22 Date Set for Trial of Rescue School Commander</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military judge Thursday set trial for
Aug. 22 in the court-martial of Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, officer in
charge of the Navy Rescue Swimmer School when a recruit died during
a training exercise.
   Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis., died in March
when he was forced back into a swimming pool after he panicked,
climbed out and screamed that he was quitting the school at
Pensacola Naval Air Station.
   Torchia, who was on the telephone in his office overlooking the
pool when Mirecki was pushed into the water, is charged with
dereliction of duty.
   The Navy had offered Torchia a chance to accept non-judicial
punishment, but he opted for the court-martial. Though a trial
gives him a chance of being exonerated, he risks up to three months
imprisonment and removal from the Navy if convicted.
   Four instructors agreed to take nonjudicial punishment of loss
of pay and rank after being charged with conspiracy to commit
battery.
   Also facing court-martial, on charges of involuntary
manslaughter, battery and conspiracy to commit battery, is Petty
Officer 2nd Class Michael Combe, one of the instructors.
   The Navy has alleged Combe forced Mirecki's head under water
just before he collapsed and died.
   At a hearing last month, a Navy psychiatrist testified Mirecki
had a phobia about being dragged under water and that fear
triggered heart failure, followed by drowning, when Mirecki was
forced under by instructors. A pathologist was uncertain whether
the recruit died from the heart attack or drowning.
   A flight surgeon had declared Mirecki unfit for the rescue
training or any other aircrew duty about a month before he died
because of his phobia, but the airman was readmitted to the school
through a series of administrative errors, witnesses said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
