<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Bush-Women     07-21 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Bush-Women,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schroeder Says Bush Will Try to Bridge Gender Gap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats shouldn't assume nominee Michael
Dukakis will retain his lead among women voters because certain
opponent George Bush is about to ``become a born-again'' on
feminist issues, Rep. Pat Schroeder of Colorado said Thursday.
   Ms. Schroeder, who briefly pondered a run for president last
summer, told women activists that Bush has scheduled speeches
before women's groups and will begin moving to cut into a gender
gap that has found him trailing badly among women in most polls.
   If he's successful, she said, Dukakis will lose the fall
election.
   ``If George Bush bridges the gender gap, he'll win,'' Ms.
Schroeder said. ``They did it in 1984. Don't let those other folks
steal it, we can't afford it.''
   Throughout the week of the Democratic National Convention, the
women delegates and other activists have been meeting daily to
devise ways to push feminist issues and build on Dukakis' strength
among women.
   Ms. Schroeder issued a blunt warning that the stakes are
enormous and the outcome far from settled.
   ``He (Bush) is going to become a born again day-care advocate,''
Ms. Schroeder said. ``George Bush is going to try to transplant
Mike Dukakis' record onto his resume.''
   In addition, Ms. Schroeder said, Democrats who control Congress
risk losing their support among women unless they win approval for
such feminist priorities as required maternity leaves.
   ``We can't keep talking gender gap and keep voting it down,''
Ms. Scroeder said.
   Beginning with the keynote speech of the convention by Texas
Treasurer Ann Richards, Bush has been under fire from women, and
Ms. Schroeder continued the assault as the gathering neared its
end, insisting Republicans have been insensitive to women's issues.
   ``Their problem is the shortage of nannies in America,'' she
said. ``Somehow, it doesn't translate into having to live on
$10,000 per year.''
</TEXT>
