<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Rain     07-21 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Rain,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Relieves Drought For Some Farmers, Municipal Water Still
Tight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain this week over some drought-stricken areas brought
``instant recovery'' for some hay farmers, but other crops are
still threatened and more rain is needed.
   ``Overall it has eased things a little bit. But the drought is
still in effect,'' said Alan Ringo, a hydrologist with the National
Weather Service in Cleveland. ``Those streams and reservoirs that
were low are still going to be low because for the most part, all
this rain was sucked up into the earth.''
   ``The grass will turn green, and it will help, somewhat, for the
crops. But if they had the rain two or three weeks ago it would
have been much better,'' he said.
   ``Farmers are in a much better mood than three weeks ago,'' said
Morris Bitzer, an extension specialist with the University of
Kentucky in Lexington.
   A bill to give drought-stricken Wisconsin farmers a property tax
cut of up to $1,000 was signed Thursday by Gov. Tommy Thompson.
Farmers said it would not make or break them, but it would help.
   ``It's hard. It's tough for the government to come out and
please everybody,'' said Carl Gorell, 76, who owns a 240-acre farm
at Seymour, Wis. ``They can't make it rain and that would be the
only way to do it.''
   Rainfall amounts varied widely, ranging across Ohio from 0.62
inch at Toledo since Monday morning to 5.28 inches at Cincinnati,
the weather service said. Massachusetts' Quabbin Reservoir, which
supplies 2.5 million people, including Boston, has 4.31 inches so
far this month, above the normal 3.94.
   Eastern Iowa got isolated showers Wednesday, but amounts were
one-tenth of an inch or less, while northern New Jersey got more
than 6 inches.
   Parts of Tennessee got a few inches of rain in the past week,
but as of the end of June the area was 63 inches below normal for
the past four years, which is more than a year's normal rainfall.
   The rain cooled parts of Iowa, but most of the state is still
firmly in the grip of the dfrought, said acting state climatologist
Harry Hillaker.
   ``There are certainly areas which are much better off than they
were two weeks ago, but 80-85 percent of the state is still very
much drier than usual,'' said Hillaker.
   Western Massachusetts farmers said the rain was too late for
some crops.
   ``Right now, you take what you can get,'' Scott Danner, sales
coordinator for the 66-member Pioneer Valley Growers Association,
said Thursday. ``What was lost during the dry spell is gone and
won't come back. The sweet corn had a rough time and so did the
peppers. But this will help save what is left.''
   ``Our problem now is our fields are muddy,'' said Great
Barrington, Mass., vegetable grower Daniel Tawcynski. ``But it's
either feast or famine.''
   Gary Palmer, a tobacco specialist for the University of Kentucky
College of Agriculture, said the rain did ``a tremendous job of
bringing the tobacco out of the problems it had been in.''
   He estimated the burley yield would be reduced as much as 10
percent to 15 percent, or ``maybe 150 million pounds short of the
eight-state quota'' because of the drought.
   The Kentucky-American Water Co., which serves several central
Kentucky counties, said its customers will remain on a water alert
despite increased flow of the Kentucky River.
   ``August is typically dry, and that has some bearing on our
making a decision too soon,'' said Robert Edens, company vice
president and general manager. ``The Kentucky River reacts quickly
to rain. It also reacts quickly when it is dry, and the rainfall is
not to be interpreted as a cure-all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
