<DOCNO> AP880721-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--DisappointedVendors     07-21 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Disappointed Vendors,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vendors Find Few Buyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arnold Ringgold brought 60 fur coats from
Washington, D.C. to sell to delegates at the Democratic National
Convention. He is returning to Washington with 60 fur coats.
   Akilah and Shahrazad Ali, sisters from Philadelphia, paid
$15,000 to lease 10 spaces in a hall set aside for vendors and
brought $25,000 worth of high fashion brass jewelry. They have sold
one ring for $20.
   Diane Spencer of Seattle says she's out $15,000. ``If we had had
the traffic we were promised, we would have done business,'' she
said.
   All of them are thinking about suing the Democratic National
Committee.
   ``They told us there would be 45,000 people a day,'' said Akilah
Ali. ``People spent $750 to $5,000 a space.'' After sizing up the
situation, she said, she gave up nine of her spaces and sent home
the people she had hired.
   The vendors, in the huge World Congress Center, were all but
hidden from delegates who attended the convention in The Omni arena
next door, which was next door in the same way that Fort Worth is
next door to Dallas. The area is four floors down, marked by a
small sign.
   Many of the 275 vendors have pulled out and Mark Weiner,
marketing director for the Democratic National Convention
Committee, said he refunded $100,000 in booth rental fees. The
vendors have been allowed to set up with half their staffs on
higher floors.
   Katie Young, who sells umbrellas, paid $100 for use of the
official Democrats' logo and $1,500 for a 10-by-10 foot space. She
got $750 back but she says she will seek full restitution.
   ``I thought about going to New Orleans for the Republican
Convention next month but I would not want to go into another deal
like this,'' she said. ``This is a raw deal.''
   Ringgold said he had never tried selling furs at a political
convention, but that he decided to try it because there is little
summer business anyway. He paid $1,500 for his space. On his rack
are coats priced from $675 for a rabbit fur-lined raincoat to
$5,995 for a natural female Black Glama mink, which he says sells
for $14,000 in season.
   ``I'm sorry we came,'' he said, ``but you have to spend money to
make money.''
   Ms. Ali said ``we are considering legal advice. We have
consulted an attorney to see if there is any recovery. It's a
horrible situation for a small business firm.''
   Ms. Spencer has been working conventions for three years. ``If
it's set up right, vendors can make back their expenses and make
money the first day,'' she said. ``I'm out $15,000. I have to pay
for the hotel rooms of employees, their meals, their
transportation.''
   She pointed to the furrier's booth. ``If there were people
coming by, they would have been swamped with inquiries. You'd see
women trying on coats. I haven't seen any one doing it yet.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
