<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Democrats-Drugs     07-21 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Democrats-Drugs,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Seize on Drugs As Issue for Fall Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats, looking ahead to the fall campaign,
called illegal narcotics trafficking ``a new kind of national
security threat,'' and said Thursday that the Reagan administration
was premature in announcing progress in the crusade for a drug-free
America.
   Members of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, meeting
on the final day of their party's national convention, accused the
Republican administration _ and GOP nominee-in-waiting George Bush
by association _ of cutting funds for drug education and
enforcement programs at the same time it announced full-scale war
against dealers.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini of Arizona said the administration is
seeking to cut more than $450 million for state and local drug
enforcement programs and 60 percent of the 3 million that was spent
in 1986 on drug education programs.
   The forum called for coordination between federal, state and
local governments in such areas as education, interdiction and
rehabilitation. And it declared that while Democrats might not have
all the solutions, they had the leadership necessary to ``wage a
successful war on drugs.''
   The anti-drug rhetoric resounded at the session.
   Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts called the widespread use and
trafficking ``a new kind of national security threat financed by
the narco-dollar.''
   ``We have a crime wave sweeping across America that is due to
one factor and one factor only _ illegal drugs,'' added DeConcini,
who presided over the forum.
   DeConcini said that while President Reagan pronounced progress
in the campaign toward a drug-free America, ``the hard fact is this
nation is outmanned, outgunned and outspent by narcotics
traffickers.''
   The participants praised Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis and runner up Jesse Jackson for their leadership on the
drug issue.
   ``Democrats should be particularly grateful to Jesse Jackson on
this issue ... which runs very, very deep for the American
people,'' said consultant John Marttila.
   He said a survey for Americans Talk Security, a group formed to
promote interest in national security affairs, said 41 percent of
the those polled considered illegal drug trafficking as the first
or second most important national security concern.
   The survey polled 6,013 registered voters between October 1987
and May 1988. It had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percent.
</TEXT>
