<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-Agenda     07-21 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Agenda,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Aides Meet to Map Out Reagan's Last Six Months in Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top White House aides met here
Thursday to map out what chief of staff Kenneth Duberstein said
would be an ``energetic, active last six months'' for President
Reagan's administration.
   As Reagan vacationed at his ranch in the Santa Ynez Mountains
north of of Santa Barbara, Duberstein and 14 other White House
officials met for three and a half hours at a Santa Barbara hotel
to discuss a wide range of issues.
   Duberstein said the president had asked him about two weeks ago
to hold the meeting.
   ``He wants a positive, energetic, active last six months of his
presidency,'' the chief of staff said.
   He said Reagan, who returns to Washington on Sunday, plans to
meet with Republican congressional leaders on Tuesday.
   One of the subjects for discussion at that meeting, he said,
will be ways to get ``as much aid as possible'' for the Contra
rebels in Nicaragua.
   Asked whether this would include military supplies of a lethal
nature, he said, ``It is something we are going to discuss with the
congressional leaders next week.''
   Duberstein said the White House also plans to push for drought
relief legislation and other domestic policy measures. He said the
officials also agreed that ``special attention'' needs to be given
to getting Senate action on 26 federal judicial nominations that
Reagan has sent to Capitol Hill.
   On the foreign policy side, he said the administration ``will be
moving forward'' toward a treaty with the Soviet Union on
intercontinental-range nuclear missiles, following up last
December's pact on intermediate- and shorter-range missiles.
   The president's national security adviser, Lt. Gen. Colin
Powell, who attended the meeting, said in Los Angeles on Tuesday
that it is becoming less likely with each passing week that such a
treaty can be achieved during Reagan's administration.
   Duberstein said he telephoned Reagan at the ranch after the
meeting and the president told him he was anxious to ``get going''
on the agenda.
   He said the group also discussed plans for Reagan's
participation in the presidential and congressional election
campaigns.
   White House officials said Secretary of the Treasury James A.
Baker III, who is widely expected to resign to become Vice
President George Bush's presidential campaign manager, was coming
to Santa Barbara on Saturday and would fly back to Washington with
the president aboard Air Force One.
   Duberstein said Reagan has been watching ``bits and pieces'' of
the Democratic National Convention on television.
</TEXT>
