<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-USMIAs     07-21 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US MIAs,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Will Try to Resolve 70 Cases, Welcomes Joint Searches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam said Thursay it will try to
resolve 70 priority cases of missing U.S. servicemen this year and
will carry out more joint excavations at warplane crash sites.
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach made the pledges in an exchange
of letters this month with retired Gen. John W. Vessey, U.S.
presidential envoy on the issue of accounting for 1,761 Americans
still missing 13 years after the Vietnam war ended, according to a
Voice of Vietnam radio report.
   Thach ``affirms Vietnam's efforts to solve before the end of
this year 70 cases of Americans missing in action considered
priority by the U.S. side,'' said the broadcast, monitored in
Bangkok.
   ``He welcomes the U.S. side for joint efforts in seeking out and
excavating the remains of MIAs in August, September and October
this year.''
   A U.S. government statement read to reporters in Washington
said: ``We have long urged Vietnam to agree to joint activities,
such as field investigations, surveys and excavations, to expedite
the resolution of the POW-MIA issue.
   ``The Vietnamese offer is an encouraging development ... and we
look forward to greatly expanded cooperation in the coming months.
The two governments have agreed to hold planning meetings in Hanoi
July 25-28 to discuss technical aspects of implementing this
offer.''
   Vessey and Thach reached an agreement in August 1987 under which
Vietnam would speed the search for remains and the United States
would consider Vietnam's humanitarian concerns.
   Washington has sent medical teams and encouraged private
American agencies to help Vietnamese, including those disabled in
the war.
   Last August, Vessey gave Thach a list of 70 ``discrepancy
cases'' the United States considers most easily resolvable because
the Vietnamese should have information on them. Included are cases
in which there are photographs of airmen taken after they were
captured.
   Vietnam has delivered many purported MIA remains since,
including 27 sets April 6, the largest turnover since the war. Few
discrepancy cases have been resolved, however, and U.S. officials
have complained about the slow pace.
   Despite pledges to do so, Vietnam has not allowed joint
excavations since the first one, a dig in late 1985 at the site of
a B-52 bomber crash near Hanoi. U.S. officials in Bangkok say the
Vietnamese have not given a clear explanation.
   On Thursday, the radio said Thach wrote Vessey a letter July 9
urging the United States to ``seriously carry out all agreements
relating to Vietnam.''
   It said a reply received Monday welcomed the joint excavations.
According to the report, Vessey ``hoped that the cooperation
between the two countries this year will be continued and
expanded'' and said the United States ``will continue trying to
respond to Vietnam's humanitarian concerns.''
   Thach indicated previously Vietnam wants more U.S. government
aid, but Washington refuses to agree until Vietnam ends its
9-year-old occupation of Cambodia.
   The United States and Vietnam have no diplomatic ties, but
relations have improved with the recent agreements.
   Diplomats said one indication was the relative speed with which
Vietnam returned three U.S. Navy aviators it rescued after their
plane made an emergency landing July 12 in the South China Sea.
They arrived at Subic Bay naval base in the Philippines on Tuesday.
   Previously, any foreigners found in Vietnamese territorial
waters were confined for months in difficult conditions.
   The same hard bargaining continued, however. Bill Schauer, a
U.S. Embassy spokesman in Bangkok, said Thursday Vietnam asked the
United States to pay all costs incurred in the rescue,
transportation and lodging of the aviators.
   ``This request is under review,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1754EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArtDispute 1stLd-Writethru a0720 07-21 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Art Dispute, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thais Express Outrage Over Art Institute Proposal For Return Of
Relic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `The 2{-feet...' to provide more information
about lintel, its location. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Following a...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai officials expressed outrage Thursday at a
proposal that they lend sculptures to the Art Institute in exchange
for returning a historic relic the Thai government contends was
illegally removed from the country.
   ``The feeling of the people of Thailand is that it is stolen,''
said Prince Subhadradis Diskul, an expert in Thai art and
archaeology who came to Chicago to negotiate return of a
900-year-old sculpture from a temple.
   ``And they think that if it is stolen, we shouldn't have to send
anything in return,'' he added at a news conference.
   The stone sculpture at issue _ called a lintel, or crosspiece
over a door or window _ is titled ``Birth of Brahma With Reclining
Vishnu On A Makara.''
   The 2{-feet-long by 3-feet-wide lintel depicts the Hindu god
Vishnu reclining on water, and dates to Cambodia's Khmer dynasty
from 805-1250 A.D. It is the only important original piece missing
from the 10-acre Khmer temple of Phnom Rung in the northeastern
Buri Ram province near the Cambodian border.
   Following a morning meeting, Art Institute of Chicago officials
proposed a revolving-loan program that would bring to Chicago, for
at least 10 years, ancient Thai sculptures of a comparable period
and aesthetic importance.
   The prince and a delegation of Thai officials planned to take
the proposal back to their government, but he predicted it would be
rejected.
   The piece was legally purchased by a dealer in Bangkok, who sold
it to a New York dealer, who finally sold it to the Alsdorf
Foundation of Winnetka, Ill., said Art Institute spokeswoman Eileen
Harakal. It was on loan to the Art Institute from 1967 until 1983,
when the foundation made it a gift, she said.
   The Art Institute said is had no legal requirement to return the
lintel under terms of the 1970 UNESCO Agreement or the 1983 U.S.
Cultural Property Act.
   But the Art Institute proposed that three sculptures be loaned
for display over a 10-year period, with the third one returned to
Thailand ``following successful negotiation of a continuing loan
agreement'' between the two parties.
   ``But if negotiations fail at that time,'' the prince said,
``they would keep the third piece. We can agree to everything, but
they want a guarantee these negotiations would be successful. ...
This is not a loan, it is an exchange.''
   ``The agreement was designed to be vague enough so that there
would be something to work with, so that both sides would have
something they want,'' Ms. Harakal said.
   On July 4, about 30 Thai university students staged a peaceful
protest in Bangkok outside the U.S. Embassy, urging the U.S.
government to help return the ancient lintel.
   And members of the Thai Vishnu Lintel Committee have staged
similar protests outside the Art Institute in recent months. The
group scheduled another demonstration Saturday.
   ``In effect they are holding this piece for ransom,'' said
Katherine Bowie, a University of Chicago anthropologist and
committee member. ``It does not seem by any stretch of the
imagination to be right.''
   The prince said he believed his government would reject the Art
Institute proposal and simply drop the matter.
   ``We will probably put a sign at the temple where the lintel
should be so tourists _ including Americans _ will know it was
taken, that we asked to give it back,'' he concluded, ``and that
they would not.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
