<2ND_LINE>AM-Jessica's Nurse,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nurse Who Cared For Jessica McClure Allowed To Remain in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Grenada-born nurse who cared for
2-year-old Jessica McClure after she was rescued from an abandoned
well last year will remain in the United States, the woman's
attorney says.
   Mavis Felix-Walton, 37, was granted permanent resident status by
the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service, attorney Paul
Douglas said.
   Douglas said an appeal of a 1987 deportation order apparently
was granted sometime this year, although he received news of the
decision Tuesday.
   Ms. Felix-Walton had faced deportation because she had stayed
too long in this country.
   ``I appreciate them letting me live here in the country I
love,'' she said.
   The nurse said letters from her doctor, the nursing agency that
employs her and Jessica's parents held little sway during two years
of dealings with the immigration service.
   Ms. Felix-Walton migrated to London 20 years ago to attend
college and moved to the United States in 1984 on a worker's permit.
   After marrying in July 1985, she applied for citizenship.
Following the end of her marriage, her ex-husband withdrew his
support of the application.
   Federal law stipulates that only immediate relatives who are
U.S. citizens can lend support to such applications.
   She said she will return to England by July 30 while her U.S.
paperwork is being processed.
</TEXT>
