<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iraq-Cease-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0697 07-21 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Cease-Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt
^Iraqi President ``Astonished'' by Iran's Rejection of Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to ADD meeting of Iraqi leaders. Pick up
8th pvs, First Deputy.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein said Thursday he
was astonished Iran rejected face-to-face peace talks with Iraq in
favor of indirect U.N.-mediated talks to end the Persian Gulf war.
   Diplomats in Baghdad said Iraq fears U.N. peacemaking efforts
will fail despite Iran's acceptance Monday of a U.N. resolution
calling for a cease-fire in the nearly 8-year-old conflict.
   Iran on Wednesday rejected a call by Iraqi Foreign Minister
Tariq Aziz for direct talks sponsored by U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   The Iraqi news agency said Hussein stressed the U.N. resolution
was not a temporary formula for a cease-fire but part of a
framework for ending the war.
   Hussein said he was astonished Iran rejected direct talks,
adding that anyone who rejected them did not want peace but only
sought tactical gain, the report said.
   Hussein made his comments in a telephone conversation with
Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi, the Iraqi agency said. It did
not provide direct quotes from the conversation.
   Iraq has claimed Iran accepted the cease-fire resolution Monday
only to give its forces time to regroup after a series of losses on
the battlefield.
   Later in the day, Hussein chaired a meeting of the ruling
Revolution Command Council during which top leaders ``stressed the
necessity of a positive Iranian response to the Iraqi proposals,''
the Iraqi agency said.
   Iraqi proposals include direct cease-fire talks leading to
full-fledged peace talks, the clearing of the clogged Shatt-al-Arab
waterway and guarantees of free navigation including a halt to
attacks on shipping in the Persian Gulf.
   First Deputy Foreign Minister Wissam Zahawi told the news agency
Iran's rejection of direct peace talks ``is tantamount to rejection
of (the United Nations cease-fire measure) itself, and of the
principle of a comprehensive and lasting peace.''
   ``If the Iranians don't want to talk to Iraq, then who do they
want to talk to?'' Zahawi asked.
   A Western diplomat in Baghdad who spoke on condition of
anonymity said the Iraqis regard direct talks as ``a token of
serious purpose.''
   Iraqi officials, who accepted the U.N. resolution upon its
adoption last July, have repeatedly insisted the cease-fire must be
part of a broader plan to achieve peace.
   ``If it is clear the secretary-general is only talking about a
cease-fire, they (the Iraqis) will certainly put a stop to it,''
the Western diplomat said.
   Iraqi suspicions have been fueled by Iranian assertions that a
cease-fire would not end the war.
   Diplomats said the Iraqis have been mistrustful of Perez de
Cuellar since September of last year, when he appeared to consider
Iranian-suggested modifications to the cease-fire measure.
   ``They certainly don't trust the Iranians, they really don't
trust the secretary-general and they don't much trust the rest of
the world,'' the Western diplomat said.
   Public reaction to the Iranian announcement has been muted in
Iraq, which has suffered hundreds of thousands of casualties in the
war. Diplomats atttributed the muted reaction to skepticism that
the Iranians truly want peace.
</TEXT>
