<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Embassy Fire,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Fire at U.S. Ambassador's Home Destroys Stored Artworks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small fire in an unused kitchen at the U.S.
ambassador's residence destroyed some American Indian prints and
handicrafts that were in storage for an exhibition planned in the
fall, a spokesman said Thursday.
   U.S. Embassy press attache Richard Gilbert said the fire was
detected at about 4:50 p.m. Wednesday in the kitchen of what was
previously a separate apartment within the residence but is now
used as an art gallery.
   Ambassador Jack Matlock's wife, Rebecca, had received an advance
shipment from a group in Michigan for an exhibit she plans on
American Indian art this fall, Gilbert said. He did not know the
name of the group whose works were involved.
   The prints and handicrafts were being stored in the unused
kitchen, he said.
   ``It appears that the electric stove somehow got turned on,''
Gilbert said.
   He did not know the value of the artworks ruined in the fire,
which was put out by Soviet firefighters shortly after they were
summoned to the residence known as Spaso House.
   There was no damage to the main quarters of the residence,
Gilbert said, and a dinner party Wednesday evening took place as
scheduled.
