<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Rather-Cronkite     07-21 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Rather-Cronkite,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rather and Cronkite, Buddies Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a unity gesture that would make Michael
Dukakis and Jesse Jackson proud, CBS newsmen Dan Rather and Walter
Cronkite posed happily in their anchor booth at the Democratic
National Convention Thursday to show what good friends they are.
   ``The problems of the past are the past. They're gone,'' said
Cronkite, who preceded Rather as the top CBS anchor. Rather called
Cronkite a ``master broadcaster.''
   Things were not so chummy last year when Cronkite suggested
Rather should have been fired for walking off the ``CBS Evening
News'' set in Miami and causing six minutes of air silence. Recent
tell-all books about CBS News recounted how Cronkite steamed as he
stood by in a studio in Washington as Rather ignored him during the
1984 convention.
   Cronkite is renegotiating his contract with CBS after suggesting
he might be free to work for another network under a phase-out that
kicks in this fall.
   So Cronkite was invited back into the anchor booth this year to
provide commentary during the conventions. He and Rather often
chatted amiably during CBS' coverage.
   ``We would be terribly dishonest if we said that we hadn't had
communications problems in the last couple of years. But as far as
I'm concerned, that ended with our association with this event,''
said Cronkite. ``I will also say that I came into it with a certain
amount of trepidation, which perhaps Dan had, since we haven't been
in the close communication we once had in the last few years. I
feel really very warmly that we have re-established that
communication here.''
</TEXT>
