<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     07-21 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Rival's Atlanta Triumph Will Be `Gone With The Wind'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Thursday
that the Democratic Party's show of unity in Atlanta for Michael
Dukakis will soon fade and ``we will remember Gone with the Wind''
about his presidential rival's convention city.
   Bush, on a campaign swing to the Carolinas on the climactic day
of the Democratic gathering, said he watched the roll call for
Dukakis' nomination Wednesday night and was impressed by the
apparent unity it reflected.
   But ``I don't know what's bubbling under the surface,'' Bush
said at a news conference opening a visit to the Carolinas.
``There's a lot of bubbling discontent on their side.''
   ``But that's got nothing to do with me,'' he continued. ``My
business is to take on Michael Dukakis.''
   ``Soon the convention will be over and we will remember `Gone
with the Wind,''' said Bush, in a sly reference to the famed Civil
War movie set in Atlanta.
   The vice president, however, praised Dukakis as a ``very good
man,'' and said he intended to watch his rival's acceptance speech
on television Thursday night.
   ``I'm going to stay plugged in,'' Bush said at the airport news
conference. Earlier, he said he missed the first two days of the
Democratic convention entirely, while he was in the midst of a
four-day fishing excursion with Treasury Secretary James Baker III.
   Bush said he expected Dukakis' acceptance speech ``to be
somewhat positive. It would a nice change of contrast with the rest
of the proceedings, I'm told.''
   The vice president, attending GOP fund-raisers here and in
Greenville, S.C., told reporters ``I'm trying to keep a relatively
low profile.''
   ``I don't think it would be good to make it look like we
frantically jump in and try to make news in the last days of the
Democratic convention,'' he said.
   His visit to the Carolinas was part of a five-day campaign swing
that began on Wednesday.
   He said he wasn't troubled by the prospect of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson campaigning around the country for the Dukakis ticket along
with the Democratic vice presidential candidate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen
of Texas.
   ``Three on two?'' asked Bush. ``Those odds aren't bad.'' Bush
didn't mention that along with his own running mate, he also will
have a powerful third force _ President Reagan _ on his side.
   ``I can't wait for the debates _ Dukakis versus Bentsen. It's
going to be great,'' Bush quipped.
   He made similar remarks in Greenville, S.C., saying: ``you've
got two different stripes and three candidates. There's very
liberal and there's Lloyd Bentsen.''
   ``My responsibility is just to take on the top of the ticket,''
he said at the South Carolina stop.
   On the subject of a running mate, Bush reiterated that he still
intends to delay the announcement of his choice until the
Republican National Convention next month.
   He told reporters on his North Carolina stop that he wanted his
decision to be ``laden with suspense.''
   ``I will try to avoid the perception of game-playing'' or
selecting a candidate ``by the applause meter,'' he said.
   The vice president said on Wednesday that former rival Sen. Bob
Dole, R-Kan., would be ``on any list'' of potential GOP candidates.
   Bush, told that Democrats were ridiculing him at their
convention with questions like ``where was George?'' when key
Reagan administration decisions were made, said he would not
respond to such attacks.
   ``You expect the ploy, the old rhetorical shout at the
convention,'' he said. ``Just let it go.''
   At another point, as reporters pressed him on saying when Baker
would join his campaign, Bush retorted ``lighten up.''
   Administration and campaign sources have said Baker will soon
resign as treasury secretary to become Bush's campaign chairman,
probably in the first week in August.
   Bush said he would have something publicly to say on Baker's
role ``several Thursdays from now,'' reinforcing that timetable.
   Baker flew to California after the fishing trip and will return
to Washington with President Reagan, Bush confirmed.
   On another subject, the vice president said he had not yet read
the report of independent counsel James McKay on Attorney Gen.
Edwin Meese.
   However, Bush said, ``As I've said before, the Justice
Department should be beyond any perception of impropriety.''
   ``The press stories have indicated there is a perception of
impropriety (in the Meese case),'' he continued. ``That standard
would not meet the high standard I've tried to bring to public life
and which I would aspire to have in Cabinet appointees.''
   Bush previously had praised Meese for having done the ``right
thing'' in announcing he would resign.
   McKay said in a report earlier this week that Meese probably
violated tax and conflict-of-interest laws, even though no criminal
prosecution would be pursued.
</TEXT>
