<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0654 07-21 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,0905</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Prepares To Send Teams; Iraq Wary Of Iran Refusal To Talk
Directly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with details of U.N. cease-fire
efforts, second U.N. team to investigate prisoner of war situation,
Iraqi president commenting on Iran's refusal to hold direct talks.
Iraqi report on Thursday's attacks and background on Rafsanjani. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. representatives prepared to
mediate cease-fire talks and investigate prisoners of war in the
Iran-Iraq conflict Thursday, but Iraq said it was wary of Iran's
motive in refusing direct negotiations.
   In Tehran, Iranian Parliament speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani said
Thursday he wept while listening to Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
statement reluctantly accepting a U.N. cease-fire resolution,
official Tehran radio reported.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported one
civilian died and two were injured Thursday by Iraqi shells falling
on the village of Sardasht in northwestern Iran.
   The Iraqi News Agency said Iraqi forces launched a series of
attacks on Iranian troops in northern Iraq, ``purging Iraqi border
peaks of the filth of enemies.''
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said an eight-member team of
military observers assembled in Jerusalem and Vienna will mediate
cease-fire talks and a second group being assembled in Geneva will
look into the prisoner of war situation.
   The second team ``will endeavor to ascertain the facts and
inquire into the concerns expressed by the two governments with a
view to ensuring observance of relevant rules of international
humanitarian law,'' Giuliani said.
   Both teams were expected to begin their trip over the weekend,
going first to Tehran and then Baghdad, he said.
   U.N. officials said most of the military observers being sent to
mediate come from the U.N. Truce Supervision Organization, based in
Jerusalem, and will be led by Norwegian Lt. Gen. Martin Vadset.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar announced
Wednesday that U.N. observers would travel to the warring nations
to help implement the U.N. resolution passed one year ago but not
accepted by Iran until Monday.
   U.N. Resolution 598, aimed at ending the nearly 8-year-old war,
calls for an immediate truce and troop withdrawal and sets out a
peace plan to end the war, including the return of captured
soldiers.
   In Baghdad, Iraqi President Saddam Hussein said he was
astonished Iran rejected face-to-face peace talks, the official
Iraqi News Agency reported.
   The agency quoted Hussein as telling Libyan leader Col. Moammar
Gadhafi in a telephone conversation that anyone who rejected direct
talks did not want peace and sought tactical gain.
   Iraq has claimed Iran accepted the cease-fire call only to give
its forces time to regroup after a series of losses in the war.
   Iran on Wednesday rejected a call by Iraqi Foreign Minister
Tariq Aziz for direct U.N.-sponsored talks on ending the war.
   Rafsanjani, also commander-in-chief of Iran's armed forces, was
quoted as saying Thursday that Iranians should not ask too many
questions about the decision.
   ``We should not ask why and how, not create more problems for
our society,'' Tehran radio quoted him as saying.
   Rafsanjani said Iranians would come to accept Khomeini's change
of heart in accepting the cease-fire resolution, the radio reported.
   Until this week, Khomeini was adamantly opposed to ending the
war with Iraq until Hussein was driven from power. The war, which
has killed and wounded an estimated 1 million people, began in
September 1980 when Iraq invaded Iran after several border
skirmishes.
   In a statement Wednesday, the 87-year-old Khomeini stressed how
difficult it was for him to accept the cease-fire resolution.
   ``I shall say again that the acceptance of this issue is more
deadly to me than poison, but I am happy to submit to God's will
and drank this cup for his satisfaction,'' the revolutionary
patriarch said.
   Khomeini's turnaround appeared to be influenced by Rafsanjani,
who introduced a less bellicose tone to Iran's war policy when he
took over as commander-in-chief last month.
   While fully backing the war effort, Rafsanjani, 53, has
consistently advocated diplomatic efforts to end the conflict and
has pushed for forging links to the West. Analysts believe he is
the man most likely to hold temporal power when Khomeini dies.
   Rafsanjani called Khomeini's decision a ``great sign of Imam
Khomeini's soul and health,'' adding he wept while listening to the
message.
   Also Thursday, four more bodies from the Iran Air jetliner shot
down July 3 by the U.S. Navy were recovered, bringing the total of
recovered bodies to 186, Tehran radio reported. A total of 290 were
killed in the incident.
   The radio said Iran obtained the equipment needed to search for
the ``black box'' flight recorder and ``a serious effort for
finding the box will soon be started in the Persian Gulf.''
   A letter was on its way to the USS Vincennes, the ship that
downed the Iranian plane, bearing nearly 10,000 signatures
expressing support for the officers and crew, U.S. Navy officials
said.
   The letter weighs 50 pounds and is 570 feet long _ four feet
longer than the cruiser itself. It originated in San Diego, Calif.,
home port of the Vincennes.
   The Vincennes ``returned to duty'' overnight, a U.S. Navy
spokesman said. It had been in port for 15 days while a team of
U.S. military experts investigated the July 3 incident.
</TEXT>
