<HEAD>Nominee's Mom Calls Son A Symbol Of America Dream</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Euterpe Dukakis on Thursday called her son
Michael a ``wonderful role model'' for immigrants and their
families and said his acceptance of the Democratic presidential
nomination was a reminder that ``they too can live the American
dream.''
   The 84-year-old immigrant mother of the Massachusetts governor
said his crowning as the party's candidate capped his ``brilliant
career'' and added quietly, ``I hope God continues to shine down on
him so lovingly.''
   Dukakis has made his Greek heritage a central theme and almost
always includes in his speeches a reference to his mother and late
father, both of whom came to the United States from Greece in the
early 1900s.
   ``What a wonderful role model he will be for the children of the
generations of other people who have come to this country,'' Mrs.
Dukakis said in an interview hours before her son accepted the
nomination. ``Michael has shown that they don't have to wait to
become leaders of this country. Michael has shown that they have
the means, that they too can live the American dream.''
   Mrs. Dukakis, who was an active campaigner during the primary
season, said it had been an ``awesome, wonderful experience. I've
had marvelous times meeting so many wonderful people and learning
the geography of our country going from the Atlantic shore to the
Pacific shore.''
   She said that Wednesday night, when the California delegation
cast its votes to put Dukakis over the top for the nomination, he
turned to her and whispered in her ear.
   ``He said, `Well, mother, here it is,' and I said
congratulations,'' she said.
