<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1928EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SatelliteTheft     07-21 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Satellite Theft,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Cracks Down On Satellite TV Pirates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   =
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Federal Communications Commission is
cracking down on television pirates who market illegal descrambling
devices for backyard satellite dishes, the agency's chairman said
Thursday.
   ``We will put them out of business and, if we can, put them in
jail,'' Dennis Patrick told a news conference. ``We're putting the
public on notice that we will no longer look the other way.''
   Patrick said the FCC is sending warning letters to 19 firms that
the FCC believes sell the technology that enables a dish owner to
decode the scrambled signals used by premium program services like
Home Box Office and Showtime.
   Using such illegal devices allows a dish owner to receive the
broadcasts without having to pay the fees charged by the
programmers or the cable firms authorized to retransmit their
signals.
   Patrick said he was unable to say how many illegal descramblers
are in use around the country, but he said their use is increasing
and some estimates put the number at as many as half of all the
units sold.
   The letters pointed out that sale and use of illegal
descramblers is prohibited by both the Federal Communications Act
and the U.S. Criminal Code. They warned of FCC fines and possible
criminal prosecution for any continued illegal activity.
   ``We strongly encourage you to discontinue selling this
technology immediately,'' the letters said.
   Patrick said signal piracy not only hurts programmers but also
the public because it increases the cost of programming,
discourages new programmers from entering the market and could lead
existing cable services to refuse to sell their signals to dish
owners.
   ``This market may dry up in the long run if we cannot stamp out
piracy,'' said Patrick. He declined to predict whether an end to
piracy would lead cable services to lower the prices they charge
dish owners.
   The FCC said it sent letters to Testron, Floral Park, N.Y.; D.B.
Systems, Glencoe, Ontario, Canada; RJL Marketing, Turks and Caicos
Islands, British West Indies; Satellite TV, Muncie, Ind.; V.C.
Bytes, Anthony, Fla.; Sports Scheduling, Fargo, N.D.; and Hinks,
Ann Arbor, Mich.
   Also, Magna Systems, Flushing, N.Y.; E.O.Q. Research, LaCrosse,
Wis.; Advance Logic Inc., Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada;
Walker Technical Services, Catlett, Va.; VC-Tech, Oakville,
Ontario, Canada; Wiz-Tech, Grand Rapids, Mich.; Clear Vision,
Arvada, Colo.; CNH, Townson, Ga.; Downlink Communications, Bixby,
Okla.; B&J Electronics, Marshall, Mich.; Coop's Box, Washington,
Mich.; and Integrated Circuit Technology, Nashville, Tenn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
