<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Boxer     07-21 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Boxer,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Cartoonist And Magazine Editor Mark Boxer, 57</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Mark in 1st graf is correct spelling of Boxer's first name;
Marc in 4th graf is correct spelling of the name under which he
drew.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cartoonist and magazine editor Mark Boxer, whose
barbed depictions of the fads and foibles of middle-class
trend-setters entertained Britain for 20 years, has died, his
family announced Thursday. He was 57.
   Boxer died Wednesday of a brain tumor at his home in London
after a five-month illness.
   From 1968 until this year, Boxer's cartoons appeared in a
variety of newspapers and magazines including The Times of London,
The Guardian, The Observer, The Daily Telegraph, The Listener and
the New Statesman.
   Drawing under the name Marc, he chose as targets people in
television, newspapers, advertising and publishing; real estate
agents; interior designers, and a host of other upwardly mobile
professionals. His cartoons always were the width of a single
newspaper column.
   ``He invented ... the north London world of TV producers,
reviewers and dons (university academics) not averse to publicity
and the beau monde,'' The Daily Telegraph said. ``He had no
affection for the characters he created. His couple Simon and
Joanna Stringalong ... poisoned life.
   ``Joanna was cowardly (and) had no friends. ... Simon went in
for every trendy cause and dropped each when it was no longer
fashionable. All they wanted was to be in with those who mattered
in the media world.''
   The Times wrote: ``Marc drew ... the trendies and the
publishers, the Hampstead (in north London) intellectuals,
lecturers, teachers and politicians, the mini-skirted and student
rebels. ... He was hawk-eyed to spot a trend.''
   In 1975, when wealthy Arabs were buying up expensive London real
estate, Boxer depicted a real estate agent telling his secretary:
``Change the line about `facing south' to `facing east.'''
   Britons like homes facing south, in order to catch the sun, but
Arabs and other Moslems face east to Mecca to pray three times a
day.
   Boxer was born May 19, 1931, and his father was an army colonel.
He went to Cambridge University but was suspended for publishing a
poem considered blasphemous. As a stunt, he left in a hearse
accompanied by friends as mourners.
   He returned at the end of the brief suspension, but student life
bored him and he left without a degree.
   After a short stint with the Sunday Express newspaper, he joined
the Ambassador, a fashion export magazine, and began drawing for
the fashion and society magazine Tatler.
   In 1957, he became art editor at another fashion and society
magazine, Queen, and from 1962-65 edited the magazine section of
the Sunday Times.
   Employing big names like painter David Hockney and photographer
Lord Snowdon, Boxer made the Sunday Times magazine into a major
publishing success.
   He worked for a variety of other magazines over the years and
became editor in chief of Vogue, another top fashion and society
magazine, last year.
   His first marriage, to food writer Lady Arabella Stuart, third
daughter of the 18th Earl of Moray, ended in divorce in 1982. They
had a son and a daughter.
   He then married Anna Ford, one of Britain's leading TV
announcers, who survives him. They had two daughters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeachesClosed     07-21 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beaches Closed,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beaches Closed Again In Monmouth County, But Pollution Source
Identified</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The likely source of pollution that
has plagued four New Jersey seashore communities since last week is
the Asbury Park sewage treatment plant, health officials said
Thursday.
   Beaches in Asbury Park, Ocean Grove, Bradley Beach and
Avon-by-the-Sea were closed again Thursday after tests showed high
levels of coliform, or fecal bacteria, in the ocean.
   The first beach closings occurred June 13, and Monmouth County
health officials initially pointed to polluted Sylvan Lake, which
empties into the ocean. But health officials realized the lake
would not be the source of balls of grease that had washed ashore.
Such pollution is commonly associated with sewerage plants.
   The county received state Department of Environmental Protection
assistance, and investigators checked all local sewerage plants and
pumping stations, chlorinated nearby lakes and looked at local
rivers.
   Meantime, the bacteria slowly dissipated and beaches reopened.
By Wednesday, all but four blocks in Asbury Park were reopened to
swimmers, said Myron LaVake, environmental program administrator
for the Monmouth County Health Department.
   Then on Wednesday night, as part of their investigation, county
and state health officials monitored operations at the sewage
treatment plants in Asbury Park and Neptune.
   The team discovered the Asbury Park plant ``was inefficiently
operating during the night,'' Monmouth County spokesman Paul Ridner
said. ``During the day it seemed to be fine.''
   Apparently, tides washed away most of the pollutants by the time
health officials took tests each morning, prompting beaches to
slowly reopen, said Lester Jargowsky, Monmouth County health
officer.
   The coliform sometimes reached more than eight times the state
standard, which is 200 colonies per 100 milliliters of water, he
said.
   Officials in the four affected seashore communities, meanwhile,
lamented the loss of business since the pollution closings began.
   ``Business has been absolutely brutal in Ocean Grove this past
week,'' said beach manager August G. Stoll.
</TEXT>
