<HEAD>Lynn, Rogers Finalists For Hall of Fame</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 7 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loretta Lynn, ``the coal miner's
daughter,'' and Roy Rogers, ``the king of the cowboys,'' were among
10 finalists named Thursday for the Country Music Hall of Fame.
   Two people will be selected from the finalists and they will be
named Oct. 10 during the Country Music Association's nationally
televised awards show. The inductees will bring the hall of fame
members' total to 48.
   Joining Miss Lynn as finalists in the open category for
induction were singers and humorists Homer and Jethro, singer
Bradley Kincaid, singer Ray Price and singer Hank Thompson.
   Besides Rogers, those chosen in a category to honor those active
30 years ago were Bill Carlisle, the Louvin Brothers, the
Jordanaires and Cindy Walker, all singers.
   A panel of 200 music industry representatives will pick one from
each category.
   Miss Lynn overcame an impoverished childhood in Kentucky to
become a top country music star in the 1960s. Her autobiography was
made into a 1980 movie, ``Coal Miner's Daughter,'' starring Sissy
Spacek, who won an Academy Award for best actress.
   Roger was a member of a country music group, the Sons of the
Pioneers, before becoming a movie and television star. The group
was famous for the songs ``Cool, Cool Water'' and ``Tumbling
Tumbleweeds.''
   The Country Music Association also announced 10 finalists for
its Horizon Award, an honor that goes to a rising performer who
previously hasn't won an association award.
   The 10 are Rodney Crowell, Foster and Lloyd, Nanci Griffith,
Highway 101, David Lynn Jones, Patty Lovelace, Lyle Lovett, K.T.
Oslin, Ricky Van Shelton and Sweethearts of the Rodeo.
   The list will be trimmed to five Aug. 18 when finalists for
other annual association awards are announced. Those categories
include entertainer of the year, male vocalist of the year and
female vocalist of the year.
