<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PipeBombs     07-21 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pipe Bombs,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Investigate Pipe Bombs Found In Two Suburbs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLESLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two unexploded pipe bombs were found
lying in a street here, officials said Thursday, while a bomb scare
in a nearby town has prompted authorities to seal all mailboxes
until further notice.
   The bombs found in Wellesley were similar to four that exploded
in neighboring Needham. No injuries were reported, but authorities
said there was a close call for a jogger as one of the bombs blew
up in a newspaper vending box.
   A resident spotted the first Wellesley bomb lying in the street
Wednesday night. State police told Wellesley officers the bombs in
Needham had been found in pairs, so the area was searched and a
second bomb was found about 30 yards away.
   In Needham, two pipe bombs exploded minutes apart Sunday night,
one on a curb near the police and fire departments' building and
the other in a parking lot nearby.
   A third bomb exploded Tuesday night in a newspaper box outside
the Needham Public Library, said Needham police Lt. Thomas Leary.
   ``The bomb that exploded in front of the public library went off
just 15 seconds after a woman jogger had passed by the newspaper
box,'' said Joseph Sainato, senior explosives technician with the
state police. ``If it had gone off when she was in front of it, it
would have cut her to shreds.''
   About two hours after Tuesday's explosion, a postal employee
found a pipe bomb in a mail deposit box outside a post office.
   The bomb was ``as powerful as a military grenade ... (and) could
send 10 pieces of shrapnel flying off at 6,000 feet a second,''
Sainato said.
   Leary would not comment on whether authorities had received any
threatening messages related to the bombs.
   The four bombs in Needham were made of the same materials,
leading investigators to believe they are connected, said Detective
Trooper Michael Cherven, who is assigned to the state fire
marshal's office.
</TEXT>
