<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--SuperdomeSeating     07-21 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Superdome Seating,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Orleans Has Seats to Spare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican officials noting the seating
shortage at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta say they
are considering opening their bash to the general public.
   They can consider that option because the Republican National
Convention next month will be held in the spacious Louisiana
Superdome, which will have room for an estimated 40,000
conventioneers.
   In Atlanta, Democrats held their convention this week at The
Omni, which _ after construction of an elaborate made-for-TV podium
_ could hold only about 11,000 people. More than 4,000 delegates
and 13,000 reporters attended the four-day convention, which ended
Thursday.
   When the Republicans assemble in New Orleans Aug. 15-18, there
should be some seats left over, said Nadine Wong, a convention
management spokeswoman.
   Wong said she expects about 30,000 people _ delegates, reporters
and guests _ to attend the four-day event.
   Convention officials are looking for a way to parcel out the
empty seats and still maintain security.
   One idea under consideration is offering tickets to the public.
Wong wouldn't speculate on how the tickets might be distributed. A
decision should be made next week, she said.
</TEXT>
