<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN-DorothyBush     07-21 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN-Dorothy Bush,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Pay Tribute to Longtime Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democrats, who have been taking swipes all
week at George Bush, paid tribute Thursday night to a Bush they
love: longtime party secretary Dorothy Bush.
   Mrs. Bush _ no relation to the vice president _ has been calling
the roll of the states at Democratic conventions in her distinctive
Southern lilt since time immemorial (actually 1944).
   The delegates watched a video tribute to her career that showed
scenes from past conventions, and magazine accounts of the striking
young woman who created a stir when she broke into the
male-dominated political world.
   Wiping tears from her eyes, the silver-haired Mrs. Bush said,
``The Democratic Party really has been good to me and it's been
good for me for many, many years.''
   ``Probably the greatest reward of all has been in the vast
number of interesting people that I have met, from precinct workers
to presidents of the United States,'' she said.
   ``You may be sure, each and every one of you Democrats, that I
promise to be a good, hard-working Democrat for the rest of my
life, absolutely!'' she said.
   The 71-year-old party stalwart said afterward she has no plans
to retire. ``I'm going full speed ahead,'' she said.
   Will she still be calling the roll come 1992?
   ``I'll just wait and see what happens.''
</TEXT>
