<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Soviets     07-21 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Soviets,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Dimiss Convention as Visual Spectacle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic National Convention was dismissed
by a Soviet news commentator Thursday as a visual spectacle with
little of the openness or freedom evident at the recent Communist
Party conference in Moscow.
   The Thursday evening news from Moscow, complete with standups in
front of The Omni, was taped and translated by Soviet television
experts at Emory University here.
   The segment, about 20 minutes into a 35-minute newscast, opened
with a yellow map of the United States and shots of The Omni,
Michael and Kitty Dukakis, and John F. Kennedy Jr. with his uncle,
Sen. Edward Kennedy.
   A voiceover described to Soviet viewers the large number of
senators, congressmen and other prominent politicians at the
gathering and said the Democrats have a good chance of returning to
power, according to a translation supplied by political science
professor Ellen Mickiewicz, creator and director of a Soviet media
center at Emory.
   Then Genrikh Borovik, described by Mickiewicz as a well-known
commentator, writer and journalist, was interviewed in front of The
Omni by a colleague, Boris Kalyagin, a European-based Soviet
reporter.
   ``It's good that the convention invited Soviet guests,'' Borovik
said, his credentials flapping on his chest. He then went on to
say, ``after our party conference, this is just boring because it's
all determined in advance. It's a show, it's a spectacle, it's
visual. For seriousness and openness and freedom, our party
conference was better.''
   At this point, Borovik switched to a friendlier assessment of
the festivities. ``Americans have their own ways, their own
customs,'' he said.
   He said the convention sent a friendly message to the Soviet
Union, one compatible with that country's ``new thinking'' _ the
code word for the reforms pressed by Soviet Leader Mikhail
Gorbachev.
   Mickewicz said the convention was featured on the Soviet news on
Monday, Wednesday and Thursday but not on Tuesday. On Thursday it
followed items about a strike at a Soviet factory, troops returning
from Afghanistan and U.S. observers arriving East Germany under
terms of the nuclear reduction treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
