<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--AthenianPledge 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Athenian Pledge, 1st Ld-Writethru,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis To Again Cite Ancient Greek Pledge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with pledge text</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis echoed the words of his ancient
Greek forefathers in accepting the Democratic presidential
nomination Thursday, vowing to ``never bring disgrace to this, our
country, by any act of dishonesty or cowardice.''
   The pledge, which Dukakis spoke when he announced his candidacy
on April 29, 1987, and occasionally repeats in campaign speeches,
praises the virtue of public service and respect for the rule of
law.
   The Massachusetts governor often referred to the pledge when
criticizing the ethical standards of the Reagan administration.
   On Thursday, Dukakis told the Democratic National Convention,
which sealed his nomination a day earlier, that ancient Greeks
celebrated important occasions ``like this one'' by taking a pledge.
   ``That pledge _ that covenant _ is as eloquent and timely today
as it was 2000 years ago,'' he said.
   He recited:
   ``We will never bring disgrace to this, our country, by any act
of dishonesty or cowardice. We will fight for the ideals of this,
our country. We will revere and obey the laws.
   ``We will strive to quicken our sense of civic duty. Thus, in
all ways, we will transmit this country greater, better, stronger,
prouder and more beautiful than it was transmitted to us.
   ``That is my pledge to you, my fellow Democrats,'' he said.
``And that is my pledge to you, the American people.''
</TEXT>
