<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CocaineConviction     07-21 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cocaine Conviction,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colombian Convicted in Smuggling Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian who authorities said was
dealing with the Medellin cocaine cartel has been convicted of
conspiring to smuggle a ton of the drug into the United States.
   Alvaro Echavarria-Olarte, 50, was found guilty by a jury late
Wednesday of two conspiracy charges and six of 11 other related
charges. He is to be sentenced Aug. 3 by U.S. District Judge
Charles Legge and could get a life term.
   Echavarria was one of 16 people arrested last year when federal
and local authorities broke up what they said was a plot to carry a
ton of cocaine, worth an estimated $48 million if divided for
street sales, from Colombia to San Francisco. It was to be
distributed from there by truck throughout California, authorities
said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Stephen Graham said the plot came
to light when one of the conspirators approached a pilot, who was
an undercover Drug Enforcement Administration agent, and asked him
to fly the cocaine in a leased jet.
   Graham said Echavarria was a broker who was dealing directly
with the leaders of the Medellin cartel, considered the world's
largest cocaine ring. He was arrested in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
