<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Glenn     07-21 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Glenn,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Glenn Says Bentsen Won't Be `Out of Touch' When Major Decisions
Are Made</HEAD>
<HEAD>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Glenn of Ohio introduced Lloyd Bentsen
to fellow Democrats on Thursday as a winning vice presidential
candidate who _ unlike George Bush _ won't be ``out of the room,
out of pocket, out of town or out of touch'' when major White House
decisions are made.
   Glenn, himself a serious contender as Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis' running mate until Bentsen was chosen, gave no hint of
personal disappointment as he presented the Texas senator to the
Democratic National Convention.
   Speaking shortly before Bentsen's nomination for the No. 2 spot
on the Democratic ticket, Glenn drew a scathing comparison between
Bentsen _ ``a real Texan'' _ and Vice President Bush.
   ``How many real Texans do you know whose idea of Mexican food is
refried quiche?'' Glenn asked in the prepared text of his speech.
   The Ohio Democrat said Bentsen ``rejects the idea that we should
be hard on needy children and easy on greedy defense contractors,''
and believes ``you can't talk like Rambo and act like Bambi'' in
overcoming America's foreign trade deficit.
   Glenn tied Bush to a Reagan administration that he said had
``consistently taken its cues from right-wing zealots'' on women's
and civil rights issues.
   On the ethics issue, Glenn said Bush talks about being tough on
crime and wanting ``four more years,'' while more than 100 Reagan
administration officials already have been indicted or left office
under a cloud.
   ``At the rate they're going, I think some of them may end up
serving 10 or 20,'' Glenn said.
   The Ohio senator said Dukakis and Bentsen would make no deals
with terrorists or drug-pushing dictators, and that ``when major
decisions are being made, Vice President Bentsen will not be out of
the room, out of pocket, out of town or out of touch.''
</TEXT>
