<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0766 07-21 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0766,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Demands Direct Peace Talks, Delays UN Team</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs UPDATING with Iranian quotes, Security
Council consultations, other developments. PICKS up 9th graf `Perez
de Cuellar'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq renewed its demand for direct peace
negotiations with Iran and said Thursday it has not yet decided
whether to receive a U.N. team assigned to work out details of a
truce in the 8-year-old war.
   ``The request of the secretary-general to dispatch the mission
is under discussion in Baghdad,'' Iraq's ambassador, Ismat T.
Kittani, told a news conference.
   Iran said Monday it would accept a year-old Security Council
cease-fire resolution. It has agreed to receive the eight-man U.N.
military team, due in Tehran on Sunday, but rejected Iraq's demand
that the two governments negotiate directly with each other.
   Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati, the Iranian ambassador, criticized
Iraq's demand for direct talks and its other new proposals as
``extraneous elements which will only complicate the whole thing''
and delay a truce.
   He told reporters: ``Iraq wants to prolong the war, gain some
more territory and leverage and reinforce their aggressive
policies.''
   Members of the 15-nation Security Council began informal
consultations on the situation. They also were discussing problems
with the technical team and the new Iraqi demands.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar later told
reporters that he was ``reflecting very carefully'' on the letter
from Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz who urged immediate and
direct consultations with Iran in New York. The U.N. Chief also
said he was ``considering inviting both foreign ministers'' to U.N.
headquarters in New York, but had not made a decision.
   Ali-Akbar Velayati, the Iranian foreign minister, sent a letter
to Perez de Cuellar on Thursday saying his government ``is fully
prepared to receive and cooperate'' with the technical mission on
details of a cease-fire.
   His letter, which diplomats made available to The Associated
Press, said Iran also is prepared to show military restraint.
   Iraq said soon after the council passed Resolution 598 on July
20, 1987, that it would accept the plan if Iran did, but the
Iranians said no truce could take effect until Iraq was branded the
aggressor in the war.
   Now Iran favors an immediate cease-fire and Iraq is hesitant.
   President Saddam Hussein's government says it suspects Iran of
playing for time to rebuild its war machine.
   Perez de Cuellar is assembling a second U.N. team to visit the
region this weekend and determine the situation of prisoners of war.
   The Security Council's Resolution 598 calls for a cease-fire to
be followed by withdrawal of military forces to recognized borders,
prisoner exchange, peace negotiations and an investigation of which
side started the war. Iraq invaded Iran in September 1980 after
several border skirmishes.
   Kittani, the Iraqi ambassador, said after his fourth meeting in
two days with Perez de Cuellar: ``We think the first step should be
face-to-face discussions (with Iran) under the auspices of the
secretary-general.''
   In response to questions, Perez de Cuellar told reporters he was
not yet disappointed with progress in implementing a truce and did
not blame either side.
   Asked whether Iraq's insistence on direct talks might block or
delay the technical mission, Perez de Cuella said: ``No. They (the
Iraqis) only want clarifications, which I will give to them.''
   The military team of officers from the U.N. Truce Supervisory
Organization is to leave Friday or Saturday from Vienna or
Jerusalem.
   Iraq has said it was suspicious of Iran's abrupt acceptance of
the Security Council plan after rejecting it for a year.
   Kittani said Thursday that the Iranian ambassador's comments
``added to our legitimate suspiciouns, as Mr. Mahallati dismissed
our proposals as irrelevant.
   ``He wants an immediate cease-fire but there is no commitement
from himself or his government to even talk to Iraq.''
   The Iraqi envoy also emphasized the importance of dredging the
Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms the southern border between the
two countries and is Iraq's only outlet to the sea.
   Rival claims to the Shatt-al-Arab were a major cause of the war.
   Kittani said Thursday the issue should be discussed in direct
talks and that Iraqi access to the waterway is essential to peace
in the region. He declined to answer questions about whether
acceptance of the cease-fire team was linked to Iraq's demand for
direct negotiations.
   Middle East diplomats said privately that Iraq was annoyed by
Perez de Cuellar's handling of his announcement of the technical
team's mission. They said he consulted Mahallati but did not wait
for official Iraqi acceptance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-USGarbage 1stLd-Writethru a0687 07-21 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-US Garbage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0687,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britons Dump Plan To Dump American Trash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs `Nick Baig ...' and 6th pvs `In an
interview...' with one graf each to include that Baig and company
are British.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to dump American household garbage in
Britain has been, well, dumped.
   Nick Baig, the British businessman who devised the scheme, said
Thursday that an application for permission to import refuse from
the eastern United States to northwest England has been withdrawn
because of ``impossible conditions'' set by the government.
   Critics of the idea say the American garbage could have brought
new diseases into the country and taken up dumping space needed by
Britain. So when Parliament was told Wednesday night that the deal
was off, there was general relief.
   ``It is unacceptable that the northwest should be made the
world's dust bin,'' said Winston Churchill, grandson of the wartime
leader and lawmaker for the area.
   Baig, however, accuses the British of getting too emotional
about what he believes was a beautifully simple idea to extract
gold from them thar trash cans.
   In an interview, he explained that his British company, Power,
Water and Waste, was negotiating with American municipalities for
ships to pick up garbage in New York, Boston and Philadelphia, and
take it across the Atlantic to be dumped on a 390-acre landfill
site in Merseyside, greater Liverpool.
   The Americans, he said, would pay him $50 for each ton of
garbage removed, and he would pay the British authorities $12 per
ton dumped at this end.
   Baig said he would have relieved the Americans of 1.2 million
tons a year over five years.
   But things could never be that simple.
   When Baig eyed abandoned tin mines in Cornwall, the southwest
peninsula of England, as potential garbage sites, the opposition
was so fierce that he had to shift his sights northward. The
Manchester Ship Canal Co. was interested and applied for a license
to have the imported garbage dumped at its Merseyside landfill.
   But faced with an influx of sticky beer cans, non-biodegradable
cereal boxes and half-eaten hamburgers, the government proved less
than enthusiastic.
   ``Our opinion was that it was a large volume of waste which
could have serious implications for plant and animal health,
because it could carry viruses from outside the country,'' said
Brendan Clark, an Environment Department spokesman.
   The Ministry of Agriculture told the importers they would need a
sanitation license.
   ``That is an impossibility because how can anybody inspect half
a million dust bins?'' said Baig. ``The law was designed for the
import of fresh meat and products. In our plan, none of the rubbish
would enter the food chain of beast, bird, plant or man.''
   Cheshire County Councilor Derek Bateman was quoted as telling
The Daily Telegraph newspaper the garbage would include waste from
New York hospitals, animal fat and rotting vegetation.
   ``The rubbish will not be covered, so we will have the prospect
of it blowing all over Cheshire and exposing people to a potential
health risk,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Baig called such responses ``ignorance'' and a sign of ``the
insularity of the situation here.'' He said he never expected
``emotions to be aroused.''
   But David Norbury, a Cheshire council spokesman, said Britain
has garbage problems, too. He said in an interview that his
district is relying on the dumping site to accommodate local
garbage for 25 more years, and if Baig's scheme was approved, the
site would be full in five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
