<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-21 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Not Over, But Some Spots Have Heavy Rainfall, Others
Record Lows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperature records fell Thursday in the southern and central
Plains, but they were record lows, not highs; and heavy rain was
reported in parts of the South and mid-Atlantic states.
   Though it wasn't enough to erase the problems caused by a
weeks-long drought, storms that formed along a cold front extending
from the Tennessee and Ohio valleys through New England brought
locally heavy rainfall to some areas.
   Some basements were flooded in parts of Steuben County, N.Y.,
where rainfall totaled almost 2{ inches in some areas. In Catlin,
N.Y., nearly three-quarters of an inch fell in one hour.
   Heavy rainfall also occurred in parts of West Virginia,
Tennessee and Pennsylvania.
   In Maryland, storms earlier in the week prompted Gov. William
Donald Schaefer to lift a 2-week-old, statewide ban on outdoor
burning Thursday. In Rhode Island, the week's rainfall brought the
month's total to above normal.
   Early Thursday afternoon, showers and thunderstorms were
scattered from southern Texas through the Gulf Coast states, the
Appalachians, and the Atlantic Coast states; and in Wisconsin,
northeastern Illinois, and Lower Michigan.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. CDT
included 1.63 inches at Elkins, W.Va.; 1.51 inches at Chattanooga,
Tenn.; 1.50 inches at Syracuse, N.Y.; 1.14 inches at Bradford, Pa.;
1.05 inch at Elmira, N.Y.; 0.90 inch at Huntsville, Ala.; 0.79 inch
at Del Rio, Texas; 0.76 inch at Glen Falls, N.Y.; and 0.75 inch at
Muscle Shoals, Ala.
   Though areas in the Ohio, Tennessee and lower Mississippi
valleys have received substantial temporary relief the past 10
days, the drought conditions continue there and in the Missouri
Valley and Great Lakes states, with no significant relief seen in
the near future, the National Weather Service said.
   The record lows Thursday included 46 degrees In Valentine, Neb.,
4 degrees colder than the record set in 1956; 56 at Kansas City,
Mo.'s international airport, compared with 62 in 1979; 55 in
Amarillo, Texas, compared with 57 in 1897; 57 in Lubbock, Texas,
compared with 59 in 1915; and 62 in San Angelo, Texas, compared
with 64 in 1970. Denver's low of 51 tied a 7-year-old record.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 105 degrees at Luke Air Force
Base at Glendale, Ariz. Thursday's morning low was 37 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo., and West Yellowstone, Mont.
   The national forecast for Friday called for scattered showers
and thunderstorms throughout the Atlantic Coast states, Florida,
Alabama and the eastern Gulf Coast region. The storms will be most
numerous ahead of a stationary front extending from central North
Carolina across eastern Pennsylvania, southeastern New York state,
Massachusetts to southeastern Maine.
   Highs in the 70s and 80s were forecast in the middle and upper
Atlantic Coast states, the Appalachians, the Great Lakes, the Ohio
Valley, the middle and upper Mississippi Valley, the eastern half
of the central and northern Plains, and the Pacific Coast; between
100 and 105 in eastern Montana; between 100 and 115 in the desert
Southwest and parts of Nevada and Idaho; and in the 90s in most of
the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
