<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Protests, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0742,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gays Restage Kiss-In Following Agreement with City</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 3rd graf about rain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay rights activists whose ``kiss-in'' was
thwarted by police earlier in the week restaged it Thursday a
half-block from the Democratic National Convention site after
receiving an apology from the mayor.
   A half-dozen members of the AIDS Coalition To Unleash Power, or
ACT UP, kissed in front of the Omni Hotel, largely ignored by
passers-by. Uniformed riot police kept their backs to the
demonstrators and watched the designated convention protest zone
instead.
   Later, after a week of temperatures over 90 degrees that sent
270 protesters and bystanders to a Red Cross tent for treatment for
blisters and heat exhaustion, rain fell. Folk singer Richie Havens
was entertaining a crowd of about 1,000 in the parking lot that
serves as the protest site when the downpour started, and most
bystanders scattered.
   On Monday, when ACT UP first tried to stage the ``kiss-in,''
about 80 helmeted police officers carrying shields forced the
activists 1{ blocks to the protest site, where they were taunted
and spat on by some youths.
   A bystander later identified as a Dukakis campaign aide was hit
in the head by a rock, and a man was subsequently charged with
aggravated assault.
   ACT UP filed a complaint with the city, and on Wednesday, Mayor
Andrew Young apologized, saying the officers might have been
short-tempered because of the heat and some might have trouble
dealing with homosexuality. The city negotiated with ACT UP and
agreed to the 15-minute sidewalk demonstration.
   Frank Smithson of New York, a spokesman for ACT UP, said, ``We
were very excited about the mayor. He's an incredible man with real
concern about the lesbian and gay community.''
   As the convention wound down, so did the level of interest in
the activities in the hot blacktop parking lot where the city has
provided a stage and sound equipment to various groups.
   A morning demonstration by a mental health group drew few
spectators; one reporter read a newspaper in a patch of shade.
Later, bystanders appeared far more interested in the shift-change
by riot-uniformed policemen, and some officers posed for pictures
along Marietta Street.
   By far the most arrests of the week came Tuesday morning, when
135 anti-abortion activists tried to blockade a clinic where
abortions are performed. All were granted bond, but some 120
remained jailed Thursday for refusing to give their names.
   Also in the protest zone Thursday, a coalition of groups from
the home state of Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
complained about his environmental record, saying he has been
insensitive to such issues as governor of Massachusetts.
   ``If he's going to be a really great leader, then we need to
educate him and educate him now,'' said Noreen Brodeur-Routhier.
</TEXT>
