<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen-War 1stLd-Writethru a0801 07-21 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-War, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0801,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Had Exaggerated Number of WWII Missions; Error Corrected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs detail on how error detected from press
secretary after 8th graf pvs bgng ``The reason''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campaign literature issued by Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen during his previous Senate races exaggerated the number of
missions he flew in World War II, but the error was corrected a few
years ago, a spokesman said Thursday.
   Bentsen is campaigning for a fourth term in the Senate at the
same time he is running for vice president on the Democratic ticket
with Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   All versions of Bentsen's biography agree that as a B-24 bomber
pilot based in Italy he was decorated for distinguished service and
discharged at the end of the war as a colonel in the reserves.
   Air Force records, consistent with Bentsen's biographies, show
that he received the Air Medal with three oak leaf clusters and the
Distinguished Flying Cross and Europe-Africa-Mideast Theater Ribbon
for serving in Italy.
   But official biographies put out during earlier campaigns by the
senator say that ``Bentsen flew 50 bomber missions over Europe
during the war.''
   Air Force records show that he flew 35 combat missions, and
logged 129 combat hours, according to an Air Force spokesman, Maj.
Lou Figeroa.
   Bentsen spokesman Chris Peacock, contacted at the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta, said that ``the biography issued by
the senator's office now lists no number of combat missions.''
   ``The reason for that is that several years ago, there were
biographies that had a number. We discovered that the number was in
error, so the number was dropped.''
   Jack Devore, Bentsen's press secretary, said he is not sure how
the incorrect number worked its way into the official biographies.
   ``A few years ago I sent his bio routinely in for Senator
Bentsen and Senator Bentsen said, `Jack, I don't think that's
right,''' Devore said. He said Bentsen could not remember whether
he had flown 34 or 35 missions, so the number was omitted
altogether in subsequent literature.
   According to the Air Force, Bentsen enlisted in the Army Air
Corps, the precursor to the Air Force, on April 11, 1942, and
became a commissioned officer on Oct. 28 of that year.
   He served as an assistant intelligence officer until June 1943,
then was a student pilot from June 1943 to January 1944.
   From March 1945, Bentsen was stationed in Italy as a B-24 pilot,
rising to squadron commander, Air Force records show.
   According to biographies put out by Bentsen, he was promoted
from major to a colonel in the reserves at the time of his
discharge, on July 20, 1945.
   A brochure bearing Bentsen's logo and dated Jan. 2, 1970 _ the
year he was first elected toOOe Senate _ said: ``He flew 50
missions over Europe.''
   Another biography from the 1970 campaign said: ``In World War
II, he entered the Army Air Corps as a private, became a pilot, and
flew more than 50 combat missions, earning the distinguished flying
cross and three air medals _ ending his career in the service as a
colonel.''
   An eight-page advertising supplement in the Fort Worth Star
Telegram from Sunday, April 5, 1970, said: ``During World War II,
he flew more than 50 combat missions as a bomber pilot, part of
them as a squadron commander.''
   A biography bearing the logo, ``Bentsen '76 Senate Campaign,''
said: ``He served in the Army Air Corps as commander of a B-24
squadron, flew 50 missions over Europe, and rose to the rank of
major.''
   A biography on the ``1984 Democratic National Convention Fact
Sheet,'' said that ``Bentsen flew 50 bomber missions over Europe
during the war.''
   Bentsen's current biography says that ``he rose to major and
B-24 squadron commander during World War II'' and ``was a colonel
in the Air Force reserves'' when he left active duty.
   ``During one bombing mission over Europe he made a forced
landing on the Island of Viz in the Adriatic,'' the current
biography says.
   ``Years later, in 1972, as a senator visiting Yugoslavia, he had
a chance to personally thank Marshal (Jozef Broz) Tito, whose
partisans kept the Viz airstrip open and made it possible for
Allied forces to send in a plane and bring Bentsen and crew to
safety,'' the official biography says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
