<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-Lyng 1stLd_Writethru a0671 07-21 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Lyng, 1st Ld _ Writethru, a0671,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agriculture Secretary Visits Drought-Stricken Farm</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs, `Farmers in ...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with Lyng's visit to Michigan, quote, Schuette's comment. Picks up
5th graf pvs, `While Lyng ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL C. BUELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIPPEWA FALLS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wisconsin's corn crop looks a little
greener than that of other drought-stricken states, but that does
not diminish the help needed by Wisconsin farmers, Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng said Thursday.
   Lyng, wearing a ``Think Rain'' button, inspected the 285-acre
farm of Ken and Mary Ellen Falch as part of a 10-state tour through
the parched corn belt.
   ``We've seen corn that's terribly disappointing,'' Lyng told a
crowd of about 250 gathered at the farm. ``I don't think there's
anyplace where we haven't seen corn that's totally unusable.''
   In Breckenridge, Mich., a rumbling sky announced the approach of
rain later on Thursday while Lyng viewed the drought's effects. It
was the last leg of the agriculture secretary's tour.
   ``Seeing it firsthand has a lot more impact than hearing
reports. It's the same all over _ it's hard,'' Lyng told several
dozen farmers. ``I am impressed with the challenge agriculture is
facing and the way farmers are responding. I, for one, will try to
help.''
   U.S. Rep. Bill Schuette, Michigan's only representative on the
House Agriculture Committee working on a drought relief bill, said
he expects the bill to go to a floor vote July 28.
   While Lyng was in Chippewa Falls, Republican Gov. Tommy Thompson
was at the farm to sign a bill to provide farmers with a 10 percent
property tax credit, up to a maximum of $1,000, on this year's
bills.
   ``Right now, we're going through the psychology of the
drought,'' Thompson said, standing beside Lyng. ``In a few months,
we'll be going through the economy of the drought.''
   Falch told Lyng that his yield would be cut from 165 bushels per
acre last year to about 50 bushels per acre this year.
   Lyng told the crowd that the trip to Wisconsin and other drought
states has given him ``a better appreciation of the need for
forage.'' Lyng said he hoped federal farm legislation to address
the problem would emphasize direct payments to farmers to buy feed
and to help them pay for other day-to-day needs.
   Lyng said he will report to President Reagan on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
