<DOCNO> AP880721-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--BradleyText 3Takes   07-21 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Bradley Text, 3 Takes,370-up</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the speech delivered by
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley to the Democratic National Convention
Thursday night.
   Thank you very much. Thank you very much.
   Mr. Chairman and delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, this is a real first for me tonight. This is the first
time I have spoken to a national convention and this is the first
time I will have performed in The Omni wearing long pants.
   I've been asked to speak about the role of the presidency in
American life. Let me begin by asking a few questions.
   Does it make a difference who's president of the United States?
Did Lincoln make a difference? Did Woodrow Wilson? Ask any child
who stares in wonder at the Grand Canyon if Teddy Roosevelt made a
difference. Ask anyone who lived through the Depression, out of
work and out of luck, if Franklin Roosevelt made a difference. Ask
any European who loves democracy if Harry Truman made a difference.
Ask anyone who cares about human rights if Jimmy Carter made a
difference.
   Do presidents make a difference? Teapot Dome, Iran-Contra,
Watergate, the Depression. Do presidents make a difference? You bet
they do. And Democratic presidents have made the most positive
difference.
   The strength of a president comes from his character. A good
president knows that public office is one of democracy's marvelous
abstractions _ that you exercise power but you must never claim it.
   When you go into the voting booth and pull that lever down for
president, you make the most important decision a voter makes.
Before making that decision, I'd ask myself a few questions: whom
do I trust with my life, whom do I trust with my job, and who
shares my hopes for my town, my family and my country.
   A president must engender trust because a president leads by
trust. Trust is a bond earned by honest words and honest actions.
   A good president doesn't define honesty as simply staying out of
jail.
   The words of a president can show how the past is a part of the
present, and how both can lead to a better future. He can give
reassurance and understanding to those who have never been
reassured or understood; he can give guidance in a world that
technology changes every day. The words of a president, like
nature's returning seasons, can provide continuity in the midst of
change.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--DukakisText-Excerpts 2Takes   07-21 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dukakis Text-Excerpts, 2 Takes,570-1,140</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from the prepared text of the
speech by Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis to the Democratic
National Convention on Thursday night as he accepted the party's
presidential nomination.
   We're going to win because we are the party that believes in the
American dream. ...
   A dream that brought my father to this country 76 years ago;
that brought my mother and her family here one year later _ poor,
unable to speak English, but with a burning desire to succeed in
their new land of opportunity.
   And tonight, in the presence of that marvelous woman who is my
mother and who came here 75 years ago; with the memory in my heart
of the young man, who arrived at Ellis Island with only $25 in his
pocket, but with a deep and abiding faith in the promise of
America; tonight, as a son of immigrants with a wonderful wife and
four terrific children; as a proud public servant who has cherished
every minute of the last 16 months on the campaign trail, I accept
your nomination for the presidency of the United States. ...
   It's time to rekindle the American spirit of invention and
daring; to exchange voodoo economics for can-do economics; to build
the best America by bringing out the best in every American.
   It's time to wake up to the new challenges that face the
American family.
   Time to see that young families in this country are never again
forced to choose between the jobs they need and the children they
love; time to be sure that parents are never again told no matter
how long they work or how hard their child tries, a college
education is a right they can't afford.
   It's time to ask why it is that we have run up more debt in this
country in the last eight years than we did in the previous 200;
and to make sure it never happens again.
   It's time to understand that the greatest threat to our national
security in this hemisphere is not the Sandinistas _ it's the
avalanche of drugs that is pouring into this country and poisoning
our children. ...
   Because this election isn't about ideology. It's about
competence. ...
   We're going to take America's genius out of cold storage and
challenge our youngsters; we're going to make our schools and
universities and laboratories the finest in the world; and we're
going to make teaching a valued and honored profession once again.
   We're going to light fires of innovation and enterprise from
coast to coast ...
   Now, I have a reputation for being a frugal man. In nine years,
I've balanced nine more budgets than this administration has and
I've just balanced a tenth. And I've worked with the citizens of my
state _ worked hard to create hundreds of thousands of new jobs _
and I mean good jobs, jobs you can raise a family on, jobs you can
build a future on, jobs you can count on. ...
   And what we have done reflects a simple but very profound idea _
an idea as powerful as any in human history.
   It is the idea of community.
   It is the idea that we are in this together ... It is an idea
that was planted in the new world by the first governor of
Massachusetts.
   ``We must,'' said John Winthrop, ``love one another with a pure
heart fervently. We must delight in each other, make each other's
condition our own, rejoice together, mourn together, and suffer
together ... We must be knit together as one.'' ...
   When a young mother named Dawn Lawson leaves seven years of
welfare to become a personnel specialist in a Fortune 500 company
in Worcester, Mass. _ we are all enriched and ennobled.
   When a Catholic priest named Bill Kraus helps homeless families
in Denver not just by giving them shelter, but by helping them to
find the jobs they need to get back on their feet, we are all
enriched and ennobled.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--DukakisText-Excerpts 1stAdd   07-21 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dukakis Text-Excerpts, 1st Add,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: and enobled.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   When a high school principal named George McKenna and his
dedicated staff of teachers and counselors create a real
environment for learning at the George Washington Preparatory High
School in Los Angeles, a high school that is 90 percent black and
10 percent Hispanic and has 80 percent of its graduates admitted to
college, we are all enriched and ennobled.
   When a dedicated new management team and a fine union in
Milwaukee work together to turn Harley-Davidson around and help it
come back to life, we are all enriched and ennobled.
   And when a man named Willie Velasquez can register tens of
thousands of his fellow citizens as voters, and bring new energy
and new ideas and new people into court houses and city halls and
state capitals all across the southwest _ we are all enriched and
ennobled.
   (Y cuando un Willie Velasquez puede inscribir decena de miles de
sus conciudadanos para votar, brindando asi nuevas energias, nuevas
ideas, nuevas personas a los gobiernos municipales y estatales del
suroeste todos nos enriquecemos y enoblecemos.) ...
   We must be _ we are _ and we will be _ militarily strong.
   But we must back that military strength with economic strength;
we must give the men and women of our armed forces weapons that
work; we must have a secretary of defense who will manage _ and not
be managed by _ the Pentagon; and we must have a foreign policy
that reflects the decency and the principles and the values of the
American people.
   President Reagan has set the stage for deep cuts in nuclear arms
_ and I salute him for that.
   He has said that we should judge the Soviet Union not by what it
says, but by what it does _ and I agree with that.
   But we can do a lot more to stop the spread of nuclear and
chemical arms; we can do a lot more to bring peace to Central
America and to the Middle East; and we can and we will do a lot
more to end apartheid in South Africa. ...
   We're going to have a Justice Department that isn't the
laughingstock of the nation ...
   We're going to have nominees to the federal bench who are men
and women of integrity and intelligence and who understand the
Constitution of the United States.
   We're going to have an Environmental Protection Agency that's
more interested in stopping pollution than in protecting the
polluters.
   We're going to have a real war _ not a phony war _ against
drugs; and we won't be doing business with drug-running Panamanian
dictators.
   We're going to have a vice president who won't sit silently by
when somebody at the National Security Council comes up with the
cockamamie idea that we should trade arms to the ayatollah for
hostages; we're going to have a vice president named Lloyd Bentsen
who will walk into the Oval Office and say, ``Mr. President, this
is nuts.'' ...
   And as I accept your nomination tonight, I can't help recalling
that the first marathon was run in ancient Greece, and that on
important occasions like this one, the citizens of Athens would
complete their ceremonies by taking a pledge.
   That pledge _ that covenant _ is as eloquent and timely today as
it was 2,000 years ago.
   ``We will never bring disgrace to this, our country, by any act
of dishonesty or cowardice. We will fight for the ideals of this,
our country. We will revere and obey the laws. We will strive to
quicken our sense of civic duty. Thus, in all these ways, we will
transmit this country greater, better, stronger, prouder and more
beautiful than it was transmitted to us.''
   That is my pledge to you, my fellow Democrats.
   And that is my pledge to you, the American people.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>END DUKAKIS EXCERPTS _ 2 Takes</HEAD>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--BradleyText 1stAdd   07-21 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Bradley Text, 1st Add,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: of change.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Harry Truman would say that the words of the next president must
be plain talk to the American people _ about what needs to be done
_ and why.
   We've made government very complex when it's really very simple.
   Do we want young couples to be able to own a home?
   Do we want our children to live in safe neighborhoods with good
schools?
   Do we believe child care for working parents is a necessity?
   Do we want our grandparents to get decent health care?
   Do we want to clean up the environment?
   These are very simple questions _ made difficult by people who
don't care about the answers. Do we care? Do we care enough to
elect a president who cares?
   A president who cares will never shy away from confronting those
who sit in judgement of the poor from the vantage point of the
veranda.
   The founding fathers didn't write a constitution and create a
government only for the 1790's. They created a political system,
enduringly alive, and flexible enough to allow each generation of
Americans to remake its world.
   Our motto, as Rev. Jackson recalled the other night, ``Out of
Many, One,'' recognizes both our individualism and our common
purpose. But achieving unity is no easy task.
   Part of us always strives for difference: for individual
liberty, individual progress, individual achievement. We've put our
faith in free men and women and open markets. We've achieved
material progress on a scale never before known on earth. And we
have never feared to speak our mind.
   Surely, no serious person would risk that individual freedom.
   But individualism without some limits imposes heavy costs.
Personal initiative can become destructive greed. The company that
employed thousands can leave town without notice. The business that
gave life to a community may have poisoned it with toxic wastes.
   And beyond individualism, our life depend on virtues _ simple
virtues: courage, honor, truth. These are the essential virtues of
a republic. The essential elements of political character. And none
of them can be bought. Rather, they're gifts we give to each other;
and we can repay each other only in kind.
   FDR said, ``The presidency is preeminently a role of moral
leadership.''
   A good president knows that our lives are not separate from
other lives around us. He knows too that the ultimate challenge
posed to a citizen in a democracy is to ask yourself what you owe
another human being. And by that I don't mean what you owe
yourself, or your family or your friends, but what you owe a
stranger simply because he or she is a human being. Do you owe more
than a contribution to charity or taxes to the government? Do you
owe a commitment of some part of your life? Or, do you believe you
owe them nothing at all? How we answer these questions will
determine the kind of society we become.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
