<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--BradleyText 2ndAdd   07-21 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Bradley Text, 2nd Add,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: we become.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In this century, it's been Democrats who've committed our
political capital to the belief that long-term prosperity derives
from a caring national community. We not only believe it _ we lived
it; we made it work. It's been Democrats who've understood that our
future is stagnant unless our economy expands to include all those
who've been left out. Yet, we also believe that the promise of
America is not comfort but freedom, not a numbing
self-preoccupation but an opportunity for everyone to compete on
reasonably equal footing.
   As John Kennedy said, ``Courage, not complacency, is what we
need today'' _ the new frontier arrived and departed long ago, but
the need for courage remains. We live in a time when thousands die
each year from a disease that was unknown a decade ago; when the
Soviet Union's arsenals remain full even as Gorbachev moves toward
reform; when environmental plunder threatens the building blocks of
nature; when drugs and violence create no-parent families and
homeless ten-year-olds.
   The next president must be a person who is awake and will stay
awake _ because he can't rest while kids kill kids in our cities
and families sleep on the streets.
   The next president must be a person with enough wisdom to know
that despite the bitterness and bloodshed in the modern world,
mankind has never been able to do more for itself than it can today.
   The next president must not merely preside, but must work and
lead.
   The most mysterious bond in American politics is the bond
between the people and the president. It goes beyond words to
symbols, memories and a sense of place.
   Remember Franklin Roosevelt, in his wheelchair _ his words over
the radio, clear and simple, aimed first at Depression and then
war, but always at fear.
   Remember John Kennedy _ his Peace Corps that urged young people
to go to every corner of the world, and young people who went
because they sensed in him a commitment to truth and the absence of
cant that honored their own intelligence and judgement.
   Remember Lyndon Johnson, a Southerner, a Texan who affirmed in
law our conviction, both black and white, that we shall overcome.
   Remember the feeling the first time you visited the Jefferson
and Lincoln memorials? I do.
   Remember last night _ seeing Jesse Jackson, his name placed in
nomination for president of the United States. Rev. Jackson, thank
you for helping us understand.
   The president is, in Emerson's phrase, our ``representative
man.'' He embodies America and gives our lives meaning. He doesn't
express some higher truth from above or lead a legislative
majority. He's simply himself...but, with the right person at the
right time, by being himself, he becomes a part of us all.
   Maybe that's why most of us remember where we were, and what we
were doing, and how we felt the day we heard that FDR died or the
day John Kennedy was shot.
   Tonight, after two years of party contest and on the eve of a
tough general election, we give our candidate to the country --
Michael Dukakis, the son of immigrants, who personifies the promise
of America and the traditions of New England; a person committed to
excellence, who is calm under pressure, and has the capacity to
know what's important. A Democrat excited to take the reins of
government _ and make it work once again. A leader committed to
govern all of the people and proud of this land.
   Thank you.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>END TEXT</HEAD>
</DOC>
