<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--SealedConvention 4thLd-Writethru a0853 07-21 0917</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Sealed Convention, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0853,910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Hall Closed for Third Night</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 4th graf pvs bgng, `Among those,' to INCLUDE Willard
Scott locked out; INSERTS 4 grafs crowd comments after 6th graf pvs
bgng, `Party officials,' to UPDATE with others locked out,
comments, crowd scene; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs bgng, `There was;'
DELETES final graf to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The overcrowded arena holding the Democratic
National Convention was sealed Thursday night for the third night
in a row as the party turned out for the convention's final night
acceptance speech by presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   The Omni was sealed for safety reasons by order of the fire
marshal at 7:35 p.m. EDT, about a half-hour before the evening
session began. Democratic National Committee officials said they
agreed with the decision.
   About 200 people _ many of them delegates _ crowded around two
entrances to the arena, some of them cursing and shouting, ``I'm a
delegate,'' and demanding admission to the hall.
   Among those locked out were Rep. Mary Rose Oakar of Ohio,
Theodore Sorensen, a guest of the New York delegation and a White
House aide to former President Kennedy, and Willard Scott, the
ubiquitous weatherman from NBC's ``Today'' show.
   In addition to Dukakis' speech, the party Thursday night was
selecting Lloyd Bentsen as the vice presidential nominee and
hearing an acceptance speech from him.
   Party officials earlier had braced for another round of
complaints from delegates locked out of The Omni and said a system
had been set up to get super delegates and ``essential personnel''
into the hall even after it is closed. But the new system would not
accommodate regular delegates, they said.
   Outside the hall, Mayor Johnny Ford of Tuskegee, Ala., a Jackson
delegate, said he was disappointed but not angry: ``There was a
time when we would be raising Cain, but as you can see, we're very
calm. There's more important things to worry about, like winning in
November.''
   The crowd was sedate until Polly Miller, a Gore delegate from
Asheville, N.C., suddenly started shouting at the top of her lungs
into a television camera under a klieg light. ``We were elected in
our states! Who's in our seats?'' she demanded. ``We paid to get
here! Who's voting in there?''
   ``We want in!'' the delegates started chanting, many of them
bitterly denouncing the Democrats' choice of Atlanta for the
convention site. But the outrage died quickly when they spotted
Willard Scott, and many scrambled to get his autograph.
   ``I can see locking me out, but how can they lock out the
delegates?'' Scott said. ``I can't believe it.''
   There was little sympathy from convention organizers, who said
delegates should know better than to show up late for the nightly
sessions.
   ``Everybody knew we were going to have this problem,'' said
party finance director Donald R. Sweitzer. ``If you don't have
foresight enough to get in to meet your obligations as a delegate,
I don't have a lot of sympathy.''
   The arena had been sealed in mid-session on Tuesday and
Wednesday nights when Atlanta's fire marshal determined that
crowding inside had reached its maximum safe level.
   But dozens of delegates, including members of the House and
Senate, were steamed when they were locked out and missed votes or
what they saw as historic speeches.
   ``This is an injustice ... it's outrageous,'' said Michael
Stein, a delegate from Chicago who was left out in the heat
Wednesday night.
   Among members of Congress fenced out were Sens. Edward Kennedy
of Massachusetts, Alan Cranston of California, Bob Graham of
Florida and J. Bennett Johnston of Louisiana. Texas Treasurer Ann
Richards, who delivered the convention keynote speech, also was
barred from entering Wednesday night.
   ``Thank God, we've got another chance to go somewhere else in
four years where there will be some room,'' retiring Rep. Ed Jones
told his Tennessee delegation Thursday.
   By contrast, Republican officials said they expect to have so
many extra seats available for their convention in New Orleans next
month that they may offer tickets to the public. The spacious
Louisiana Superdome will have room for an estimated 40,000
conventioneers.
   Nadine Wong, a convention management spokeswoman, said Thursday
she expects about 30,000 people _ delegates, reporters and guests _
to attend each day of the four-day event. She said officials are
looking for a way to parcel out the empty seats and still maintain
security.
   Adding to the confusion and overcrowding at the Democratic
convention were an estimated 1,700 people who received passes to
get into The Omni arena because of their status as big-ticket
contributors to the party.
   Members of the party's National Finance Council, whose members
give at least $5,000 each, its Business Council, who give $10,000
or more apiece, and its Victory Fund, who commit to give or raise
$100,000, all receive passes to the convention hall, Sweitzer said.
   He estimated that during convention sessions, about 1,000 of
those with contributor passes were actually in the hall, which
seats 12,500 to 13,000 people in its configuration for the
quadrennial event. Thousands of seats were sacrificed to build a
huge podium full of technical gear and press seating, and skyboxes
for television crews.
   But Sweitzer said contributors do not compete for the 4,212
delegate seats. Their passes do not permit them on the convention
floor, but give access only to guest seating high in the arena, he
said. They share that space with 1,170 alternates and other guests,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 2210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--DaschleText 1stLd-Writethru a0762 07-21 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Daschle Text, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0762,610</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Provides as-delivered transcript; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the speech by Sen. Thomas
Daschle of South Dakota seconding the nomination of Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas for vice president at the Democratic National
Convention on Thursday night.
   My name is Tom Daschle and I'm here to tell you that the last
thing we need on the prairie is another dried up old Bush.
   We need a change. We need Michael Dukakis.
   And we need Lloyd Bentsen.
   South Dakotans pay no greater respect to anyone than to those
pioneers who found partnership with the land. Our glory comes from
those who carved dreams from that land, under a sky so vast that
only greatness could unfold.
   The Bentsen family is a story of the American dream, of taking
chances, of beating the odds; a story of a family's life in South
Dakota and the rigors of survival in the American West, a rugged
beginning from which our roots take hold, roots of American life
that sprout qualities from which our nation draws its greatness,
roots of American soul that lend strength to our nation's values.
   Roots from which descendants of Greek and Danish immigrants will
soon become the president and vice president of the greatest
country in the world.
   And it is from these roots that values are born.
   Roots are not force-fed; they are passed on.
   Values are not worn on the sleeve but come from the soul and
emanate through the words and deeds of those who live them.
   Lloyd Bentsen's values _ born in the West, nurtured in the South
_ are now evident across this land.
   Like those of Michael Dukakis, they are values of genuine
American leadership:
   _ A deep respect of human dignity.
   _ A rare courage to stand up for one's beliefs.
   _ And a profound belief that he owes the nation much more than
this nation owes him.
   As this man lives out these beliefs, this nation has been paid
back in multitude, and we are the beneficiaries.
   So, now as he faces the American people, let us confirm what we
know: that Bentsen leadership is American leadership of the most
valuable kind, leadership marked not by what one says, but by what
one does.
   And for those of us who call rural America home, we also call
Lloyd Bentsen ``friend;'' someone who fights with us, not against
us for the family farm; and someone who believes, as we believe,
that Reagan and Bush are to agriculture what the drought is to
wheat and corn; someone who fights with us, not against us because
Americans can win in any marketplace if the competition is fair;
and who believes, as we believe, that someone deathly sick in the
countryside ought to have the same chance opportunity as someone in
country club square.
   To rural Americans tonight who listen from their family farms;
who may be watching from the town cafe; who may occupy a bed in a
rural hospital, or a desk in a small classroom, or a counter in the
town hardware store; let me say to each one of you and to all
Americans: This man stands with us, on accomplishments not
promises, on values not vagaries, with roots that are our roots. He
is the son of our heritage. He is our friend.
   So it is with humility and great pride tonight that I second the
nomination of the next vice president of the United States, Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Daschle Text _ 1 Take</HEAD>
