<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Rostenkowski     07-21 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Rostenkowski,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Nominates Bentsen, Calls Workers Back To Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., nominated Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen for vice president Thursday, saying the Texas
millionaire understands the problems of Americans who ``live from
paycheck to paycheck.''
   ``Lloyd Bentsen is one of a few people in public life who is at
home with those who are trying to make it in America and those who
already have,'' the Rostenkowski told the Democratic National
Convention.
   ``He fights for those who seek a better life because he knows
they deserve it,'' said Rostenkowski, chairman of the tax-writing
House Ways and Means Committee. ``That's what our Democratic Party
is all about, and that's what Lloyd Bentsen stands for.''
   He referred to Bentsen as a legislative partner because the
Texan is chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, the counterpart
to Rostenkowski's panel. The two have often worked together on tax,
trade and health insurance legislation.
   Rostenkowski said his district on the Northwest Side of Chicago
houses people who ``run our stores, work in our factories, teach
our children, drive our buses and protect our neighborhoods.''
   Many such traditionally Democratic voters switched and supported
Reagan in 1984, contributing to a Republican presidential landslide.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen knows these people and has fought for these
people,'' he said, calling on them to return to the Democratic
fold. ``Come on home where you belong.''
   Rostenkowski called Bentsen straightforward, smart and tough.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen has everything it takes to be one of America's
greatest vice presidents,'' he said.
   He said Bentsen ``believes that no one should get free ride, but
no one should be left behind either.''
   ``Isn't this what we all believe?'' he said.
</TEXT>
