<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Bolivia-Cocaine 3rdLd-Writethru a0874 07-21 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Cocaine, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0874,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Trek Through Jungle To Nab Cocaine Kingpin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One graf SUBS for 9th graf pvs, The 15-year ... clarifying
that defendant tried in absentia. Picks up 10th graf pvs, Bolivia,
a ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LPZ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized Bolivia's cocaine kingpin,
Roberto Suarez Gomez, after trekking through jungles all night to
catch him by surprise, asleep at his ranch, the minister of the
interior reported Thursday.
   In Miami, Chief Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Gregorie, said
on hearing the news, ``He's the biggest cocaine producer in the
world. He has enormous acreage in coca plants.''
   Suarez Gomez was flown to La Paz from Trinidad city, where he
was taken after 10 anti-drug police captured him Wednesday morning
at his El Sujo ranch, 25 miles away, Interior Minister Juan Carlos
Duran said.
   El Sujo is one of Suarez Gomez's five ranches in the heart of
the tropical northeastern Beni region.
   Duran said Suarez Gomez was asleep when 10 anti-drug police took
over the ranch, confiscating 20 automatic weapons and arresting two
bodyguards.
   Suarez Gomez, 56, is wanted in Miami on drug trafficking charges
and has been called by authorities the ``godfather'' of Bolivia's
illegal cocaine trade and a major supplier of drugs to the
Medellin, Colombia, drug cartel.
   However, Duran told a news conference that Bolivia will not
extradite Suarez Gomez to the United States, since he already has
been sentenced to 15 years in prison here.
   He said Suarez Gomez had heart problems and would be examined
medically before being presented to the press.
   The 15-year sentence was handed down by a judge earlier this
year. The former rancher-turned-drug baron never showed up for his
trial and was tried, convicted and sentenced in his absence on drug
trafficking charges.
   Bolivia, a nation of 6.7 million people in the center of South
America, produces a third of the cocaine that reaches U.S. and
European markets.
   Until now, Suarez Gomez has used his money and influence to buy
his freedom in Bolivia. He publicly spoke of paying off political
figures and policemen.
   Duran told reporters, ``President Victor Paz Estenssoro says he
is very pleased with Suarez Gomez's arrest and that the fight
against drugs is the top priority of the government.''
   In 1980, the Bolivan Human Rights Association says, Suarez Gomez
helped finance the military coup that overthrew the civilian
government of Lidia Gueiler Tejada, the interim president, and
installed a government that hired Italian, German and Argentine
mercenaries to undertake a campaign of terror.
   Under that right-wing government, headed by Gen. Luis Garcia
Meza, drug traffickers operated with impunity and left-wing
political figures and labor leaders were killed, tortured or
exiled. The mercenaries went after opposition figures and provided
protection to traffickers. Suarez Gomez was considered the main
player on behalf of cocaine traffickers.
   According to the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration, during
and after the 1980 military coup Suarez Gomez became a close
associate of Interior Minister Luis Arce Gomez, who offered him
protection from prosecution in return for large sums of money.
   ``I think that Suarez Gomez's arrest shows that Bolivian police
are serious about going after major cocaine traffickers,'' Frank
Macolini, the DEA country attache for Bolivia, said in a telephone
interview.
   The anti-drug police, trained and equipped by the U.S.
government, have consficated over eight tons of cocaine paste in
one year, Duran said.
   Bolivian police assisted by the DEA destroyed two large
cocaine-processing laboratories in the Beni region Wednesday, but
officials did not say whether the labs belonged to Suarez Gomez or
another trafficker.
   DEA spokesman Jack Hook said in Miami that Suarez Gomez was
indicted there in 1980 for conspiracy to peddle 854 pounds of
cocaine, but that Suarez Gomez commonly deals in tons of cocaine.
   ``He's really the same as the upper levels of the Medellin
cartel,'' said Hook. ``He could be considered one of the pioneers
involved in growing, manufacturing and trafficking cocaine to the
United States.''
   Hook noted that Medellin cartel leader Carlos Lehder Rivas was
sentenced in Jacksonville, Fla., on Wednesday to life in prison
without parole.
   Last month, the lower house of Bolivia's Congress accused
cocaine kingpins of trying to take over the government and called
for a united front to preserve democracy.
   The government in June closed a radio station and a television
station that broadcast a talk show with Suarez Gomez. On the show,
Suarez Gomez described the U.S. State Department as ``the king of
cocaine, the vice royalty is the government of Bolivia and the
president is a boss at the service of the U.S. government.''
   Bolivia's conservative government said the program slandered Paz
Estenssoro and the government and that it was closing the stations
for a year.
   In 1986, Newsweek magazine, citing sources in Washington, said
Suarez Gomez had a network of connections stretching from the
Amazon basin to Guadalajara, Mexico; Miami and Europe.
</TEXT>
