<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NightStalker 1stLd-Writethru a0834 07-21 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Night Stalker, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0834,0698</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Serial Murder Trial Under Way</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 6th graf `Tynan began' to UPDATE with
questioning ending for day, number of potential jurors excused.
Picks up 7th graf pvs `The trial...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years after the summer of his arrest,
Richard Ramirez went on trial Thursday and the long search began
for jurors to judge him on charges he committed 13 grisly murders
and 30 related felonies.
   ``Perhaps you have heard about this case,'' Superior Court Judge
Michael Tynan told 50 prospective jurors at the beginning of an
expected eight-month jury selection process. ``This is the
so-called Night Stalker case.''
   Tynan pointed out Ramirez, a pale, shaggy-haired drifter dressed
in a loose-fitting, doublebreasted, dark blue suit wih a blue
hankerchief in his pocket to match his tie. Ramirez did not
acknowledge the jury prospects and continued to sit with his back
to them at the counsel table.
   Tynan told the group he is looking for ``committed people,
willing to devote from one to two years to the case.
   ``This is a very serious business, a very serious trial,'' he
declared.
   Tynan then began listening to reasons jurors said they were
unable to serve including the inability to get time off from work.
   At least six panelists were dismissed when they declared their
belief in the defendant's guilt. Thirty-two were excused because
their employers would not pay for two years of jury service. After
a half-day of questioning, jury selection recessed until Monday.
   The trial, which had been delayed many times, got under way
after a last defense motion in which Ramirez' lawyers sought to
exclude the press and public from the jury selection.
   An attorney for the Los Angeles Times opposed the motion but the
judge said he had already decided to deny it.
   The State Supreme Court also rejected a defense motion Thursday
to block the trial. Defense lawyers contended jury selection
procedures would keep young people and Hispanics off the panel in
disproportionate numbers.
   ``I am ecstatic about finally going to trial in this case,''
said Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin. ``And I hope we can
move the trial along a little more efficiently than we've attended
to the pretrial affairs.''
   Ramirez, 28, a native of El Paso, Tex., could be sentenced to
die in the gas chamber at San Quentin if he is convicted of the
spree of murders, rapes and assaults.
   Defense attorneys, anticipating extensive questioning of jury
prospects, said it is unlikely a jury will be seated until spring.
   Then, the jurors will settle in to hear from some 1,000
witnesses.
   Attorneys Daniel Hernandez and Arturo Hernandez, who are not
related, say their client is eager to have his case resolved.
   ``He's been ready to go to trial all along. Eager is a good
word,'' said Daniel Hernandez.
   Ramirez was captured and beaten by east Los Angeles residents
during the hot Labor Day weekend of 1985 after his picture appeared
in newspapers as the prime suspect in murders and attacks that had
terrorized Southern Californians.
   Residents locked their windows and bolted their doors against
the random killer, who typically entered homes through unlocked
doors, raped women, killed both men and women and stole jewelry and
other valuables.
   At a preliminary hearing for Ramirez in 1986, anguished
witnesses including several women who had been raped told of
horrific confrontations with the Night Stalker who invaded their
homes, killed their husbands and demanded they ``swear to Satan.''
   Some murders were ghoulish, including one in which the victim's
eyes were gouged out.
   The killer often left behind drawings of pentagrams, inverted
five-point stars often associated with devil worship.
   Ramirez' bizarre courtroom behavior at early hearings fueled
speculation that he was a devil worshiper. He once shouted, ``Hail
Satan!'' and flashed a pentagram drawn on his palm. During the most
grisly testimony at his preliminary hearing, he appeared to giggle.
   But in recent months, he has been content to slump in his
courtroom chair scribbling notes or reading legal papers.
</TEXT>
