<HEAD>ATLANTA: dissipate lightly.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen is concerned about health care for the elderly and
the aged and the children and the widows. Lloyd Bentsen cares about
the constituency of the Democratic Party. And he sees to it that
whenever he gets a chance as a member of the United States Senate,
he will vote for those programs that will aid and advance the
health and well-being of those people who are our most vulnerable
citizens.
   Lloyd Bentsen is a proponent of those programs to help those
frail people.
   But I'll tell you something else about Lloyd: he has not been a
spectator in the United States Senate. He has been a doer. An
action man. And he sees to it that action takes place on behalf of
those people who need it the most, and that's why he ought to be _
he must be _ the Democratic nominee for vice president of the
United States.
   Lloyd Bentsen knows that welfare programs don't work. That the
people who need the money don't seem to be there to get it. But he
is there working on welfare reform as a part of his mandate for
action on behalf of the people in the United States Senate.
   I wish _ I wish you knew Lloyd Bentsen as I know Lloyd Bentsen.
If you knew him as I do, you would join me on this podium tonight,
and each of you would urge the nomination of this man for vice
president.
   Lloyd Bentsen recognized that civil rights and human rights
needed the attention of people in the United States Senate. He knew
that civil rights and human rights need the attention of the
governors of America long before a Civil Rights Bill of 1964. He
opened the doors of his public accommodations facilities to
minorities long before there was a public accommodations section to
the 1964 Civil Rights Act.
   And, do you remember down South, we used to have a poll tax, a
poll tax to keep minority people from being able to vote? Lloyd
Bentsen voted against the poll tax long before anybody thought
about removing it from the government ...
   It is a mistake for you to label Lloyd Bentsen. The media and
others have already tried to label him. They call him a ``Tory
Democrat.'' A conservative. A businessman. They call him a man who
is at odds with the liberal faction of the Democratic Party. But I
would simply say to you tonight, don't try to label Lloyd Bentsen.
   Lloyd Bentsen is a good American. And he believes _ and he
believes in the principles of the Democratic Party just like you do.
   Lloyd Bentsen believes in public service. He believes in the
public service ethic. And he does not believe that you go into
public service to get rich. You go into public service to serve
people.
   I believe that Lloyd Bentsen will be a good vice president
because he believes in this country, and he wants to do what is
right, and he has an instinct for doing what's right.
   Lloyd Bentsen believes with one of the ancient Greek
philosophers, Aristotle. Aristotle said in The Politics, ``If
liberty and equality as it is thought be some is chiefly found in
democracies, they will be best attained when all persons alike
share in the government to the utmost.'' Lloyd Bentsen believes
that.
   Lloyd Bentsen would say, with Adlai Stevenson, ``Democracy
cannot be saved by supermen, but only by the unswerving devotion
and goodness of millions of middlemen.'' Lloyd Bentsen believes
that.
   He is a sensible, reasonable, rational, common sense, good
choice for vice president of the United States. And I believe that
he is the best choice you could come up with to give us a strong
and winning ticket this November.
   I am pleased and I am proud to second the nomination of Lloyd
Bentsen.
   Thank you very much.
</TEXT>
