<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SavedByTheCow     07-21 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saved By The Cow,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bossy's Body Block Saves Plane That Crashed into Field</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: June 4 is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot who crashed into a farm field and
blacked out as the plane hurtled toward a steep ravine says an
800-pound Hereford gave its life saving him and his three
passengers.
   ``The cow saved our lives, no doubt,'' said pilot John Lozano.
``We would have smashed up real bad.''
   The cow was hit by the plane, limped away and later died. Lozano
reimbursed farmer Sam Jahnke $1,500 for the animal.
   ``That's the best $1,500 I ever spent,'' Lozano said, estimating
that otherwise the plane would have headed into the ravine at about
60 mph.
   Lozano was on a pleasure flight from Cass County, Mo., to
Junction City, Kan., June 4 when he determined the runway at
Junction City was not long enough for his Beechcraft Bonanza.
   The engine stalled as Lozano decided to fly to Manhattan, about
10 miles away. Between hills on his left and right, Lozano spotted
a flat area in Jahnke's field and put the plane down.
   The last thing Lozano remembers seeing is the ravine coming up
and a group of cows standing around a tree. ``I thought, `Oh ...'
and I blacked out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
