<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Strikes 2ndLd-Writethru a0791 07-21 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Strikes, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0791,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikes Cripple Mining, Other Industrial Activity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with police blockage around
union local lifted as strike winds down. PICKS up graf 5 pvs
`Police said...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National strikes, accompanied by guerrilla
violence, have crippled the vital mining industry and seriously
affected other industrial activity.
   A two-day general strike to protest soaring inflation was
declared illegal. Police used tear gas and water cannons Wednesday
to disperse strikers who piled rocks and burning mounds of garbage
to block highways around Lima.
   Labor Minister Orestes Rodriguez declared the general strike a
failure and said less than 30 percent of Peru's 7 million workers
participated. He said strikers would be docked three days' pay.
   Late Wednesday police lifted their blockade of the headquarters
of the General Confederation of Peruvian Workers, which had called
the strike. Traffic and police presence around Lima returned to
normal as the strike wound down.
   The General Confederation said riot police shot and wounded 23
strikers and arrested 740 since the action began Tuesday. Most
wounds were from buckshot and minor, but three people were hit by
bullets, the federation said.
   Police said 30 people were arrested in Lima but reported no
serious injuries.
   Fish, chicken and vegetables were in short supply in Lima
markets and stores Wednesday because of the strike.
   Guerrillas of the Shining Path, a Maoist group that began
fighting eight years ago, killed seven policemen, wounded five and
assassinated a judge in attacks across the country Monday and
Tuesday.
   Police said it was not clear whether the Shining Path was acting
in conjunction with the strike, but said leftist guerrillas
supporting the work stoppage had bombed buildings in several cities
and planted a car bomb in Lima that wounded three passersby.
   A strike by the National Federation of Mine, Metal and
Steelworkers was in its third day Wednesday, forcing silver prices
up on world markets. No violence has been reported at the mines.
   The union said 85 percent of mining operations were shut down,
but industry spokesmen put the figure at 50 percent to 60 percent.
   Officials said Cerro de Pasco and Buenaventure, which together
produce about 8 million ounces of silver a year, were paralyzed but
operations continued at Peru's largest silver mines, Orcata and
Orcopampa, and several smaller producers.
   Peru is second in world silver production and a major source of
copper, lead and zinc. Mining output traditionally accounts for
more than half the nation's income.
   Union spokesmen said copper production had ceased at Cajone and
Toquepala, two principal mines of the U.S.-owned South Peru Copper
Corp.
   Industry spokesmen said operations at state-run Centromin,
Peru's largest mining company were partially affected and the La
Oroya smelter, the nation's most important, continued working.
   Minero Peru, a state company that operates copper mines and zinc
and copper refineries, said operations were normal.
   The mine union, which claims 75 percent of the nation's
estimated 100,000 mine workers as members, said the strike is
intended to force mine companies to negotiate all contracts at the
same time. The government has refused.
   Alberto Ramirez, spokesman for the general union federation,
said the 48-hour strike closed 80 percent of the factories, stores
and businesses in Lima and a slightly smaller percentage elsewhere.
   It was the third general strike against the 3-year-old
government of President Alan Garcia, head of the governing
center-left Aprista party.
   It was called to protest austerity measures imposed this month,
which include increases in food prices ranging from 20 percent to
100 percent. Inflation is expected to reach 400 percent this year.
   The federation says it represents 90 percent of the 1.6 million
unionized workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
