<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-JapanTrade     07-21 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Trade,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Ends Trade Dispute Over Processed Food Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators have resolved a long-standing
trade dispute over Japanese import quotas on 11 categories of
American processed food products, U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter announced Wednesday.
   ``I am pleased that we were able to finally reach an ...
agreement to implement the GATT (General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade) report which ruled that Japan's quotas were illegal under
international trading rules,'' Yeutter said in a statement issued
by his office.
   Yeutter said the agreement ``sets a precedent for other pending
cases we have before the GATT in which the United States is denied
access to foreign agricultural markets.''
   ``It is a further example that with persistence and
perserverence the United States can open markets abroad for our
products,'' he said, noting that some products had been severely
restricted or prohibited in Japan for more than two decades.
   Under the three-year settlement, Japan will eliminate import
quotas on products including ice cream, frozen yogurt and processed
cheese; sugar syrups; fruit puree and paste; fruit pulp; non-citrus
fruit juices; tomato juice and ketchup.
</TEXT>
