<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Anglican-Women     07-21 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anglican-Women,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglicans' No. 2 Leader Proposes Compromise on Women Bishops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop of York John Habgood, the
Church of England's second-ranking prelate, said Wednesday that
Anglicans agonizing over the issue of women bishops should
compromise by allowing them to ordain priests _ but only with a
male bishop present.
   Habgood spoke amid warnings that the worldwide Anglican
Communion of faithful in 164 countries could break up if U.S.
Episcopalians consecrate their first woman bishop.
   ``I have a very simple suggestion, and that is whenever a woman
bishop ordains (a priest), a male bishop should ordain with her,''
Habgood said in a British Broadcasting Corp. television interview.
   ``I would say that women bishops would then be acceptable within
the Council of the church and recognized as having a place in the
next Lambeth Conference and so forth. I think that is a possible
compromise.''
   Other church leaders made no immediate response to Habgood's
proposal.
   The current Lambeth Conference of 525 bishops representing the
world's 70 million Anglicans has been overshadowed by the
controversy over admission of women priests by some Anglican
churches.
   The conference, held once every 10 years, was due to debate the
issue of women priests on Friday. The three-week conference opened
in this cathedral city in southeastern England on Sunday.
   The Church of England has so far refused to ordain women as
priests, but it is deeply divided on the question.
   The issue involving 2.5 million U.S. Episcopalians centers on
whether the church would accept a priest ordained by a woman
bishop. Some Church of England leaders say they would, others say
they could not.
   Habgood ranks second in the Church of England hierarchy behind
the state church's spiritual leader, Archbishop of Canterbury
Robert Runcie.
   Runcie, who leads the world's Anglicans without the kind of
formal authority the pope exercises over Roman Catholics, warned
Monday that the Anglican church worldwide was endangered by an
``unholy conflict'' over women priests and bishops.
   ``We need to recognize that our unity is threatened over the
ordination of women to the priesthood and episcopate in whatever we
ultimately decide to do,'' he told the conference in a keynote
speech.
   A minority of the 27 self-governing Anglican churches in the
world, including U.S. Episcopalians and Canada, have admitted women
to the priesthood since 1977. But they have so far stopped short of
permitting women bishops.
</TEXT>
