<HEAD>Police Shoot Man In Running Gun Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officers responding to a disturbance call
Wednesday shot and killed a man who police say opened fire and
engaged in a running gun battle with the lawmen.
   The man, whose name was not immediately released, was pronounced
dead at Baylor University Medical Center late Wednesday afternoon,
said hospital administrator Katherine Wright. The man suffered
gunshot wounds to the upper chest, neck and leg, she said.
   No officers were wounded, said Sgt. A.J. Crawford.
   The officers responding to the call encountered two men who were
firing guns and fled from police, said Lt. J. Calame. Three
officers chased the suspects through an alley for several blocks,
exchanging gunfire during the chase, he said.
   The second man was taken into custody, police said.
   Police cordoned off several blocks of a heavily traveled road
that remained closed through much of the night.
   Dallas police have drawn criticism from minority group leaders
for being too quick to shoot at suspects. Last summer, a
congressional subcommittee conducted a hearing into the
department's use of deadly force, prompted by white officers' 1986
slayings of two elderly blacks in unrelated cases.
   Three Dallas police officers were shot this year, sparking a
backlash of support for police. Then-Police Chief Billy Prince
fueled controversy when he said criticism of the department by
members of the City Council had fostered an atmosphere of hostility
to police.
