<2ND_LINE>AM-Olympic Tickets,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Darts Used To Distribute Tickets For Olympic Ceremonies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers are distributing tickets
for the opening and closing ceremonies of the 1988 Olympics with
the aid of computers and darts.
   The Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee said a lottery using the
so-called Multiplicative Congruent Method was held for almost 14
hours at the Korea Exchange Bank Wednesday to draw winning numbers
of Koreans who applied for tickets.
   Organizers said that in the lottery, they first picked three
numerals by having people shoot darts into a wooden wheel with
numbers on. The three figures were fed into a computer to come up
with winning numbers.
   The lottery was used to decide who gets about 40,000 tickets for
the two ceremonies. About 967,000 people requested opening ceremony
tickets _ or 48.3 people for every ticket.
   Another 20,000 tickets for each event went on sale overseas last
October, with prices ranging from $40 to $200.
   The Olympics are scheduled for Sept. 17-Oct. 2 in Seoul.
</TEXT>
