<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday July 31 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This publishable note is for use with
BC-Victims-Palestinians, b0519, and BC-Victims-Israelis, b0520</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians throw stones and sometimes
firebombs at Israelis in the uprising on the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Israeli soldiers sometimes strike back with live ammunition,
but more often with rubber bullets, tear gas, and clubbings. The
rubber bullets, which are not intended to kill, are taking a toll,
nevertheless, and Palestinian children have been caught by them in
the crossfire. Some have lost their eyes, leaving them in a state
of trauma and with little understanding of what happened to them.
At the same time, the stones and firebombs are leaving Israelis
seriously injured, some maimed for life. Following are two stories
by Associated Press correspondents on how the disorders have
tragically afflicted individuals on both sides of the conflict.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday July 31</NOTE>
