<2ND_LINE>BC-Victims-Palestinians, Adv 31,0678</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday July 31 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dozens of Palestinians Lose Eyes in Clashes During Uprising</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A companion story is Victims-Israelis, b0520; a separate
editor's note for both stories is BC-Victims-Note, b0518</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three-year-old Rasha
Hoshiyeh stabs out the eyes of her dolls and stuffed animals.
   She is trying to understand, her mother says, what happened when
a rubber bullet fired by an Israeli soldier put out her left eye.
   ``She's not the same Rasha,'' said the mother, Majdouleen
Hoshiyeh. ``At night she looks at herself in the mirror without her
eye and sometimes she starts to cry.''
   Rasha Hoshiyeh was playing at the door of her family's home in
the West Bank town of Ramallah in March when the rubber bullet,
fired by one of the soldiers chasing Palestinian protesters,
smashed through the glass and hit her in the left eye.
   ``The force of the bullet knocked Rasha over. The eyeball was
hanging outside the socket, there was blood flowing everywhere,''
Mrs. Hoshiyeh, 24, recalled in an interview.
   Rasha has since undergone two operations. Today, the dark-haired
child with curly pigtails and long black lashes wears an immobile
glass eye several shades darker than her chestnut-colored right eye.
   Since losing her eye, Rasha is more nervous, her mother said.
Evidence of that is a blond-haired doll and teddy bear that sit
eyeless on a shelf in her bedroom.
   Eye loss is among the most dramatic of the injuries suffered by
36,000 Palestinians hurt by gunfire, tear gas, beatings or rubber
bullets during the seven-month-old Palestinian uprising on the West
Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   Of the total, about 6,000 have suffered lasting injuries,
according to figures compiled from hospital and field reports by
the Arab-run Human Rights Information Center.
   One Palestinian, Yussef Abu Eid, 32, was killed in March by a
rubber bullet fired at point blank range into his right eye. Two
soldiers were charged with manslaughter.
   One of the youngest Palestinians to lose an eye is 9-month-old
Fidah Sharafi of the Jabaliya refugee camp in the Gaza Strip. On
June 6, troops chasing demonstrators fired rubber bullets into the
marketplace where, her mother said, they had gone to buy milk.
   ``When my daughter is old enough to understand,'' said Safia
Sharafi, 22. ``I will tell her: `The Jewish soldiers came here and
opened fire, and that's how you lost your eye.'''
   Another infant victim was Hoda Masoub.
   On June 1, Hoda's mother grabbed her daughter and ran into the
narrow alleyway after troops hurled a tear gas cannister into her
home while pursuing stone-throwing youths. Hoda was hit by seven
rubber bullets.
   ``My daughter is disfigured for life and she did nothing,'' said
Mrs. Masoub, 29, as her daughter sat sucking a lollipop, her face
half-concealed by a bandage and her right arm in a cast.
   Dr. Ziad Jaouni, an ophthalmologist at St. John's Eye Hospital
in Jerusalem, said 81 Palestinians had been treated at the facility
for eye injuries received in clashes with troops. Of that group, 42
lost their eyes _ about half of them innocent bystanders.
   ``We have treated many small children and elderly people who
were not demonstrating. They were hit while standing in windows,
doorways or on balconies,'' he said.
   Doctors say dozens of others with serious eye damage or loss
have been hospitalized elsewhere.
   Eye injuries have been caused primarily by the cork-shaped
rubber bullets, which are embedded with a hard metal core.
   An Israeli army spokesman, Col. Ranaan Gissin, said rubber
bullets do not have a straight trajectory and aiming is difficult
when soldiers are chasing rioters.
   ``We don't fire rubber bullets at children and their mothers,''
Gissin said. ``It is one of the non-lethal means we use to disperse
a mob and is not intended to cause bodily harm.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday July 31</NOTE>
