<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Victims-Israelis Adv31   07-21 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Victims-Israelis, Adv 31,0665</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday July 31 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Injured in Uprising Show Anger and Restraint</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A companion story is BC-Victims-Palestinians, b0519; a
separate editor's note for both stories is BC-Victims-Note, b0518</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Cohen, a 20-year-old soldier, was struck in
the head by a 65-pound block thrown from a rooftop while he
patroled the occupied West Bank city of Nablus in March.
   The injury left him paralyzed from the chest down and confined
to a wheelchair.
   ``I'm very angry,'' said Cohen, who is expected to remain in the
hospital here at least until September. ``If I found him (the
assailant), I would hang him from a high tree.''
   But Moshe Nussbaum, who was badly burned on the hands in a
firebomb attack while on reserve duty in the West Bank, said he had
no intention of seeking revenge.
   ``They weren't after Moshe Nussbaum. They were after Israeli
soldiers, and they found me. Those are the rules of this war. I can
understand it. I can't say I hate those kids.''
   Cohen and Nussbaum are among 428 Israeli soldiers injured since
the Dec. 8 start of the Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip. In addition, 272 Israeli civilians have been hurt.
   Army officials said they could not provide a breakdown of
injuries, but according to media reports most soldiers have been
injured by stones and a smaller number burned in firebomb attacks.
   During the same period, about 36,000 Palestinians were hurt by
army gunfire, tear gas, rubber bullets and beatings, according to
the Palestinian-run Human Rights Information Center. It estimated
6,000 suffered lasting injuries.
   Israelis involved in the confrontations with Palestinians say
homemade weapons used by Palestinian youths are far more lethal
than people realize.
   ``Firebombs are dangerous weapons,'' said Nussbaum, 35, a police
reporter for Israel radio when he wasn't on military reserve duty.
``I used to say on the radio, `Two people were hurt by a firebomb.'
Now I understand the real meaning of the word.''
   Nussbaum and two other soldiers were on patrol in the West Bank
village of Janiyeh on June 9 when a firebomb was hurled into their
open jeep.
   ``It exploded between my friend and me,'' Nussbaum said. ``I
started to burn, so I jumped out and rolled on the ground to
extinguish the flames.''
   Nussbaum was burned severely on his hands and back and was given
skin transplants. He has been unable to return to work because he
has not regained the full use of his hands.
   In retaliation for the attack, the army blew up two homes
belonging to three suspects and sealed the house of a fourth. The
army also has begun to issue fire-retardant overalls to soldiers.
   Cohen was on patrol in the narrow alleyways of Nablus' old city
when the block was dropped on his head March 19. The assailant has
not been found.
   ``We were afraid because we did not know from where they would
throw the next stone at us. ... It was like a war,'' Cohen said in
an interview.
   But he added that the Israelis were at a disadvantage despite
their superior weapons and firepower.
   ``The Arabs knew our orders on opening fire. They knew we
weren't allowed to shoot at stone-throwers and that as soldiers we
could not run away from the stones. So what was left was to be hit
by stones and shut up.''
   Cohen, who says he hopes to study commercial photography after
his release from the hospital, complained that injuries to soldiers
were largely ignored while the media focused on the Palestinians.
   ``When a soldier gets hurt nothing is written about it,'' he
said. ``I would like it to be known that not only the Arabs are
suffering.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, July 31</NOTE>
