<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-AIDS-MinorityOutreach Adv31-2Takes   07-21 0930</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AIDS-Minority Outreach, Adv 31-2 Takes,0957</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Educators Plot Strategy to Quell the Epidemic</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a corner in Harlem, amid the men selling
baseball caps, wind-up toys and perfume, Sharon Williams tries to
save a life or two by killing off a popular myth.
   She is a black woman trying to convince other blacks that the
face of AIDS isn't always white.
   ``I tell them, `What you don't know can kill you,''' said
Williams, who has spent 18 months passing out truth and condoms as
a city Health Department outreach worker. She believes information
means salvation, but on the street, denial runs deep.
   If people cared to hear statistics, they would learn the virus
doesn't discriminate:
   _ Blacks represent 12 percent of the population but account for
26 percent of all U.S. AIDS cases, a figure constant since the
government began tracking cases in 1981. Hispanics make up 7
percent of the population and 14 percent of the AIDS cases.
   _ Blacks make up 73 percent of all heterosexual transmission
cases, compared with 13 percent each for whites and Hispanics. The
risk of contracting AIDS is at least 15 times greater for black and
Hispanic heterosexuals than for white heterosexuals.
   _ More than half of all women with AIDS are black; 19 percent
are Hispanic.
   _ More than half the children with AIDS are black; 25 percent
are Hispanic.
   The numbers only hint at the worst part of the story: when
educators talk about AIDS in minority communities, they're talking
about the death of entire families.
   ``What you have now is grandparents who are burying their kids
who are burying their grandkids,'' said Ravinia Hayes-Cozier,
director of the Office for Community Development for the New York
City health department. ``There's a possibility for two generations
to be destroyed if we don't take it seriously.''
   ``This is going to wipe our community out,'' said Henri Norris,
director of the Multi-Cultural Alliance for the Prevention of AIDS
in San Francisco. ``In the 21st century, black Americans are going
to be in very short supply.''
   AIDS is the fatal insult to an already injured community, said
Hayes-Cozier, who likens the black community to an immune system
long ravaged by societal ills such as poverty, homelessness,
unemployment, drugs and crime.
   ``It's not by accident this same community should be the perfect
host for AIDS,'' she said.
   Ultimately, the spread of AIDS among minorities has nothing
specifically to do with race and everything to do with behavior.
Studies show that people of color engage more frequently than
whites in activities known to spread the fatal disease, such as
needle-sharing and casual sex among intravenous drug users. Of
cases contracted through intravenous drug use, 80 percent are black
or Hispanic.
   But as researchers and educators prepare for the second annual
Minority AIDS Conference, scheduled for Aug. 15-17 in Washington,
D.C., they say the message filtering down to minority communities,
particularly blacks, has been too confusing, too inaccurate or too
demeaning to evoke widespread concern and action.
   Instead, the most common response has been fear and denial, a
denial reinforced by AIDS media campaigns aimed at gay white men,
who make up the bulk of total AIDS cases.
   ``The message was, if you're not gay, you're not white, you're
not sleeping with anyone who's gay or white, you're not at risk for
the disease,'' said Ernest Andrews, an AIDS educator in the poor,
predominantly black Bayview-Hunter's Point area of San Francisco.
   ``The community became very comfortable with the idea it was not
at risk. We've had to fight that kind of denial, which really has
blanketed the black community.''
   In a recent survey of black adults in South Carolina, 95 percent
either did not know or did not believe that more than half the
children and women with AIDS in the United States are black.
One-fourth characterized AIDS as a gay disease.
   A 1987 Los Angeles Times survey of 2,100 people found anxiety
about AIDS highest among blacks, and an Illinois Department of
Public Health poll showed blacks and Hispanics to be among the
least knowledgeable and most fearful of AIDS.
   In big cities, educators must address the fear that AIDS is a
government conspiracy to eliminate society's ``undesirables,''
namely minorities, drug addicts and homosexuals. They must overcome
cultural and religious barriers that prevent people from halting
behavior that puts them at risk or from using condoms to protect
themselves from infection.
   And they must constantly seek funding in a struggle that pits
minority outreach efforts against better-organized gay groups with
significant resources and political clout.
   In San Francisco, a city that spends more per capita for AIDS
education, treatment and research than any other in the nation,
only $100,000 of the $20 million spent in 1985 and 1986 was
earmarked for minority communities. Last year, a coalition of
minority education groups bypassed the city and asked the state for
$150,000 to target high-risk behaviors in their communities.
   This year's $177 million federal AIDS information-education
budget, up from last year's $104 million, includes $7 million for
state and local minority activities, the same as 1987. An
additional $3 million was included for national minority efforts.
Federal treatment of perinatal AIDS, aimed largely at black and
Hispanic women in New York and New Jersey, receives about $6
million.
   ``They divide the two populations, gay vs. minorities,''
Hayes-Cozier said. ``It almost sets up the scenario that it's a
battle that can't be won.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
