<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-AIDS-MinorityOutreach Adv31-1stAdd   07-21 0921</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AIDS-Minority Outreach, Adv 31-1st Add,0939</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: be won.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In the trenches, they are disheartened but still fighting.
Williams and 14 other outreach workers must cover a dozen
neighborhoods with the highest HIV infection rate in New York,
which has 15,000 AIDS cases, more than any other U.S. city. The
statistics, and the job, can be overwhelming.
   ``Sometimes you get really, really busy, and it gets depressing.
You can feel helpless,'' said Williams, 26. ``How can one person
ideally educate 300,000 people? Across five zip codes? It's
impossible.''
   She does what she can, and she walks away from presentations at
places like the Harlem men's shelter knowing she has told them what
they need to know to avoid the virus. She also knows that AIDS is
like a festering wound: open it, and a hundred other poisons bubble
to the surface.
   ``The biggest problem we have is that there are so many other
problems,'' she said. ``How can you teach someone about AIDS when
they can't pay their rent, they're facing eviction, their husband
abuses them, they're homeless?''
   ``You can't worry about something five years down the line when
you're worried about feeding yourself today,'' said Sunny Rumsey,
who coordinates AIDS outreach for the New York City health
department. ``These communities are just overstressed. I think AIDS
is the straw that's breaking the camel's back.''
   A man in Alabama told Venus Medina, an associate for minority
affairs at the National AIDS Network, that he couldn't discuss AIDS
education with her. ``I have no food in my refrigerator. I have no
food stamps, no work. How can I talk about AIDS when I have nothing
to eat?'' he said.
   ``Some of these people say, `I should get AIDS and get out of
this awful world,''' Medina said. ``They say, `Don't talk to me
about what's going to happen next week or next month; talk to me
about how to keep my stomach full and keep a roof over my head.'
How do we talk about AIDS to a person who's already given up?''
   ``We talk their language. We put it in terms they can
understand,'' San Francisco's Andrews said. ``We also address the
fears they might have.''
   One of the most pervasive is the conspiracy theory, the belief
that AIDS is a plot by authorities _ the U.S. government in the
most popular version, the Soviets in another _ to wipe out
minorities. The concept of genocide ranges from benign neglect to
an outright campaign of annihilation, and there is enough evidence
of the former to give credence to the latter, educators say.
   ``Does the government really want to save its citizens? The
minority community will tell you `No,''' Rumsey said. ``(The
community will say) `They want us to get infected. They want us not
to know what's going on.'''
   Blacks have been disproportionately affected since the beginning
of the epidemic, but minority educators note that while the
government initially listed Haitians as a risk group, it failed to
warn blacks in general.
   ``Why weren't TV messages made to say that black people are
being affected?'' said the Rev. Carl Bean, founder of the Los
Angeles Minority AIDS Project. ``Everytime they saw anything on the
news, it was always a white gay male. It gave people an opportunity
to say, `That's not me.'''
   Outreach workers say their job has been made more difficult
because the epidemic was well along before they were alerted. Bean
started the Los Angeles Project in his home in late 1984 after
hearing the statistics in an AIDS support training program.
   ``It just blew me away,'' he said. ``I couldn't understand why I
was sitting in training class with only three people of color out
of 50. I thought, `I must go back home to my people.'''
   At the time, there were no culturally sensitive brochures or
posters. ``In my community, there was nothing that put a face on it
that said `black,''' Bean said. He created his own, in simple
language and the red, black and green of the black liberation
movement.
   Lack of money elsewhere has meant that little effective
literature has been produced. Outreach worker Williams carries a
bagful of brochures that she knows many people won't bother to
read. In South Carolina, the founder of the state's AIDS Education
Network uses tips from her beautician's job to buy AIDS information
materials and develop her own.
   Getting the message out is one challenge; getting people to
listen is another. Techniques used in the middle-class white gay
community don't work in poor black and Hispanic neighborhoods, with
their basic distrust of governmental agencies.
   In San Francisco, Andrews mounted a production of an original
play, ``Community At Risk.'' Reformed drug addicts-turned-educators
in San Francisco, Chicago, New York and Atlanta go into shooting
galleries, where addicts inject drugs, to talk one-on-one about the
dangers of sharing needles.
   Frustration over reaching so few people breeds creative
solutions: AIDS rap contests, free ``Blow the Whistle on AIDS''
concerts, raffles and AIDS information parties paid for by outreach
groups. Meanwhile, the country still lacks a national media
campaign that shows the many faces of AIDS in a hard-hitting,
non-judgmental way.
   ``The community needs to see and hear real live people saying,
`I've got AIDS, my baby's got AIDS, my mother has AIDS.' That has
not happened,'' Andrews said. ``And until that happens, it's going
to be like chipping away at granite with a small chisel.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 31</NOTE>
