<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-AIDS-MinorityBehaviors Adv31   07-21 1095</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AIDS-Minority Behaviors, Adv 31,1127</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>At Risk: Cultural Beliefs Hinder AIDS Education Among Minorities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AIDS-Minority Outreach</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note frank tone of information in story.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someday soon, Dr. Mireille Tribie, a family
practitioner, hopes to enlist the help of a voodoo priest.
   She thinks he may help convince Haitian women infected with AIDS
that the virus might ultimately kill any children they bear.
   ``They don't believe what I tell them,'' said Tribie, director
of the minority AIDS program for the Haitian-American Community
Association of Dade County.
   ``They think the disease is mystical, something evil, that
someone put a voodoo hex on them. (They think) it's impossible for
them to be sick because they don't feel sick.''
   In Miami's Little Haiti, where some of the city's 80,000
Haitians seek out voodoo priests for spiritual advice, mysticism
and medicine clash with deadly results.
   And in minority communities across the nation, religious and
cultural practices from disapproval of condoms to bisexuality
frustrate health officials desperately trying to change risky
behavior.
   ``There are some tremendous cultural barriers I don't think
we'll ever be able to surpass,'' said Jeanne Easton, director of
the Dade County AIDS Program Office in Miami. ``What's more
entrenched in a culture than sexuality?''
   Tribie has contacted an anthropologist to seek a meeting with
the area's chief voodoo priest, hoping he can preach to
AIDS-infected women on the dangers of getting pregnant. Childbirth
is so important in Haitian and other cultures that the 50-50 chance
of delivering a healthy child is considered worth the risk.
   Haitians were originally identified as a high-risk group for
AIDS until it was shown their behavior, not their nationality, made
them susceptible. In Florida, which has the third-highest number of
AIDS cases behind New York and California, 33 percent of blacks
with AIDS were born in Haiti.
   Many minorities have yet to learn that what they do, rather than
race, puts them at risk for the disease. Much of the complacency
and denial stems from the fact AIDS was first identified in white
homosexuals.
   Hispanic men who have anal sex with males, however, don't regard
themselves as homosexuals and therefore may not recognize the risks
_ to their wives as well as themselves.
   ``It starts off in Third World poverty. Men have sex with other
men for money,'' said Dr. Laureano Vega, director of the South
Florida AIDS Project. ``They did not consider themselves gay
because it was not something they did for pleasure. They're into
heavy denial.
   ``If they are the penetrator, they're not the ones receiving
infected semen,'' he said. ``They tend to think there's a lower
risk for contracting the disease. That's not the case.''
   AIDS brochures are being translated into Spanish, but there are
subtle dialect differences among Cubans, Puerto Ricans, Mexicans
and South Americans. Some sexual acts have no translation in
Spanish, such as fisting, a variation of anal intercourse. That
weakens the warning.
   In addition, ``everything has to be less explicit,'' Vega said.
``You have to sterilize the message. We cannot approach these
issues as openly as we can in the Anglo community.''
   Religious conservatism in the black community and its associated
homophobia have forced many gay black men to hide their sexual
identity, making it difficult to reach them, educators say.
   ``There is a percentage that identify as black first, gay
second,'' said San Francisco AIDS educator Ernest Andrews. ``They
don't go to gay bars and they don't read gay newspapers. Their
sexuality is very private.''
   Religious beliefs have proved a profound obstacle to AIDS
education in very basic ways. With the Roman Catholic Church
opposing condom use, it is difficult to persuade Hispanics to use
them.
   ``We're asking them to almost walk away from their culture,''
said Sunny Rumsey, AIDS educator for the New York City Health
Department. ``How do they stay religious and still protect
themselves from the virus?''
   The church's position has made that impossible, minority social
workers say.
   ``We have to cut out this moral judgment. It's not a moral
issue. It's not a religious issue. It's a health issue,'' said Ruth
Rodriquez of the Hispanic AIDS Forum in New York. ``The shame of it
is, people are infected and die in the meantime.''
   Even when religion is not a factor, economics may be. Cutting
off sexual activity, for instance, might mean cutting off a source
of income.
   ``For poor women, sex may function as a source of employment, a
method for establishing ownership or proprietary rights in a
relationship, or a means of acquiring much needed tangible
support,'' Dr. Vickie Mays, a UCLA psychology professor, said in a
presentation at the American Psychological Association in New York
last year.
   ``When people are perpetually poor, they're not going to spend a
dollar for a condom when they can buy food,'' said Dr. Emo Akpaeti
of Miami.
   In addition, many men refuse to use condoms, and minority women
have little power to persuade them.
   ``We ask them to `negotiate' safer sex ... when many of them
don't know what the word `negotiate' means,'' Mays said. ``Despite
risk-reduction advice to `talk to their prospective partners,' a
rather middle-class notion, many women don't bother to ask men
about previous sexual or drug use behaviors because they know the
men will lie or discount the risk.''
   To complicate matters, in the Haitian community, some women
believe condoms damage their bodies.
   ``They feel the vagina is a sacred part. You have sex and babies
with it. Nothing else can go in there, like a condom, because it
would spoil her sexual organs,'' Tribie said.
   Childbearing is such a strong cultural imperative that even
knowing they are HIV-positive doesn't stop minority women from
getting pregnant.
   ``These people don't equate the virus or infection with having
sex or having a baby,'' Easton said of the Haitian community.
``They're used to having their children die. It's no big deal. It's
an extension of the poverty they came from.''
   In poor communities where the infant mortality rate already is
staggering, the 50-50 chance of producing an infected child often
seems acceptable odds, particularly to women who know childbearing
will bolster their relationship or enhance their community standing.
   ``It's a very basic instinct,'' said New York's Rodriquez.
``There's something very lifegiving about your worth and having
been alive at all in leaving a child. Some people say, `I believe
in God, and God would not do this do me or my baby.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 31</NOTE>
