<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-AIDS-ParlorEducation Adv31   07-21 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AIDS-Parlor Education, Adv 31,0764</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Beautician Uses Parlor to Teach AIDS Education</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AIDS-Minority Outreach</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: DiAna DiAna in lede cq.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another hot afternoon at the beauty
parlor. DiAna DiAna rolls Emma Jacobs' hair into tight curls,
applies her own brand of oil conditioner and talks about men and
women, sex and death.
   No idle gossip here. At DiAna's Hair Ego, Emma Jacobs gets the
full treatment: a perm and an education.
   For 18 months, DiAna has been telling her corner of the world
about a disease that seems too remote to be real. Only 300 cases of
AIDS have been reported in South Carolina's largely rural
population of 4 million. An additional 1,600 people are
HIV-positive. About 65 new cases are reported each month. More than
half the cases so far are among blacks.
   DiAna and partner Bambi Sumpter, who met at a state health
department AIDS training program and formed the South Carolina AIDS
Education Network, understand that information has to spread faster
than the disease to change the future.
   So they teach, anyone, anywhere, anyway they can. They do it on
their own time, mostly with their own money. So far 4,000 people
have gotten the message, among them children, parents, beauticians,
lawyers, prison officials. And of course, the ladies and gentlemen
who come to DiAna's Hair Ego.
   ``People been coming in here six, eight years, and I never know
much more than that their kid's gone from first grade to high
school,'' said DiAna, who has spent 25 of her 40 years making other
people beautiful. ``And then they come in and all of a sudden
because of this AIDS stuff, they have these very, very personal
conversations that are unbelievable.''
   They have had graphic discussions about sexual preferences, what
to do about sexually active pre-teens and how to get men to use
condoms.
   ``You can talk to your beautician, you know, about things you
wouldn't normally say to other people,'' Jacobs said. ``It's a
little like talking to a therapist.''
   It began when DiAna decided she needed to know about AIDS. Were
any beauty services risky? What precautions should she take? The
more she learned, the more convinced she was that everyone needed
to know what she knew, the sooner the better.
   Now a dose of reality awaits everyone who comes through the
door. Women under hairdryers watch AIDS education tapes. A table
holds neat stacks of AIDS pamphlets, donated or purchased with
customers' tips. The centerpiece is a glass bowl filled with
gift-wrapped condoms. Ladies once too embarrassed to pick one up
now take handfuls for themselves and their teen-agers.
   AIDS posters hang on the walls amid blow-ups of impeccably
coifed models _ ``Last to Know, Maybe First to Go'' reads one
hand-lettered sign _ and next to DiAna's mirror is a copy of her
most recent AIDS column from a weekly black newspaper, featuring
real questions and no-nonsense answers.
   ``Why do y'all make it sound like a black problem _ don't more
white folks have AIDS than blacks?''
   ``Can you get AIDS if you sit where an AIDS kid sat?''
   ``If this AIDS problem is so bad, why doesn't somebody do
something?''
   Somebody is. DiAna and partner Sumpter, a doctoral candidate in
public health education, have created educational materials for
illiterate people and a program that trains children to teach their
peers about AIDS. DiAna's new support group, ``Mothers Against
AIDS,'' helps parents communicate with youngsters, using the
language they use.
   ``The children are especially important,'' DiAna said, ``because
they're the next generation who are going to have to take over and
clean up the mess this generation is letting happen.''
   She talks quickly, skillfully smearing relaxer on Norma Hipp's
hair while another beautician crimps Hipp's young daughter, Kidada.
   ``I learn something new every time I come here, and I'm teaching
her about it,'' Hipp said of her 9-year-old. ``The way the world is
now, I don't think any kid is too young to learn about AIDS.''
   Because of DiAna, she knows how to keep Kidada from becoming
another sad statistic.
   ``Everybody used to ask me ... why was I doing this?'' DiAna
said. ``I'm just doing it because I think it's important, and I
think everybody's worst science fiction movie is getting ready to
come true.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 31</NOTE>
