<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growth in personal income slowed in all but
three states during the first three months of 1988, barely keeping
ahead of inflation, the government said.
   The Commerce Department reported Wednesday that growth in income
in the 50 states and the District of Columbia slowed to 0.8 percent
in the January-March period, compared with growth of 2.8 percent in
the final quarter of 1987.
   Despite the slowdown, incomes managed to stay slightly ahead of
the increase in prices, which was 0.6 percent in the first quarter
for personal consumption spending.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nephew of the late Walt Disney
announced a bid to take over Polaroid Corp. that values the company
at $2.84 billion, challenging management's plan to revitalize the
instant camera company.
   Roy E. Disney, an investor with an estimated personal wealth of
$560 million, already owns 6.9 percent of Polaroid through his
family's Shamrock Holdings Inc.
   Polaroid said it was reviewing Wednesday's $40-a-share cash
offer, but suggested management would look unfavorably on the offer.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials said the recent rainfall in the Midwest
hasn't signaled the end of the drought or the end of the crisis for
cornfields.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng said Wednesday he expects
Congress to pass drought-assistance legislation by mid-August, but
that farmers shouldn't expect any help until at least October.
   The welcome rain in the Farm Belt sent soybean futures prices
plunging the permissible limit again on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EAST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pratt & Whitney Aircraft said it is
eliminating more than 1,000 white-collar jobs in a move that will
eventually save $100 million a year and enhance its competitive
position in the jet engine market.
   The company said Wednesday that 283 employees, ranging from
engineers and purchasing agents to vice presidents, would be laid
off over the next 18 months, including 158 who were let go
immediately.
   The rest of the jobs will be eliminated through attrition and
not renewing 181 personnel contracts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food maker Beatrice Co. says it has taken down
its ``For Sale'' sign following a breakdown in negotiations with an
unidentified prospective buyer.
   The move, revealed Wednesday in the company's quarterly
Securities and Exchange Commission filing, prompted speculation
that Beatrice Chairman Donald P. Kelly would launch an effort to
build a new conglomerate, using one or more of Beatrice's
businesses as a vehicle for acquisitions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While a grand jury met to hear more
evidence in the Pentagon bribery case, a federal judge refused a
newspaper's request that he unseal information filed by
investigators to obtain search warrants against their prospective
targets.
   U.S. District Judge Claude A. Hilton said Wednesday that public
release of the affidavits would ``harm the process' of the
investigation.
   Meanwhile, the grand jury met for a second day to hear from the
Justice Department team which has coordinated the 2-year-old
investigation.
