<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ailing Eastern Airlines is considering laying off
as many as 4,000 employees and making drastic service reductions
affecting 15 to 20 cities, a newspaper reported.
   The layoffs would affect nonunion airport and reservations
employees and Eastern's service primarily in the West, especially
in the airline's Kansas City hub, The Miami Herald said Wednesday,
quoting unnamed sources.
   ``The fall schedule and manpower requirements are still being
developed,'' Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak responded.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The historic U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement ran
into trouble when Canada's opposition Liberal Party vowed to block
ratification until Conservative Prime Minister Brian Mulroney calls
a general election.
   But Mulroney, in a heated House of Commons exchange Wednesday,
rejected demands for an immediate election to settle the free-trade
issue _ a debate that has divided Canadians for a century.
   The agreement, signed on Jan. 2, would eliminate all tariffs in
the $150 billion-a-year trading partnership and dismantle
non-tariff barriers in investment, energy and other sectors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission moved a
step closer toward allowing telephone companies to provide cable
television services.
   An 18-year-old FCC rule and a 4-year-old law bar telephone
companies from running cable systems in their own service areas,
but the FCC indicated by a series of actions Wednesday it favors
lifting those prohibitions.
   The commission called the prohibitions a draconian form of
regulation that no longer is needed because the cable industry has
become large and strong enough to compete with the telephone
companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unpublished memo written by the head of the
Food and Drug Administration shows the agency wants to reject
proposals for broader limitations on sulfite food preservatives,
despite estimates that the chemicals can be extremely dangerous to
a million or more Americans.
   A consumer health group said Wednesday the FDA's failure to act
endangers many asthmatics and others who have a severe reaction to
sulfites.
   Sulfites, which have been used for decades to prevent
discoloration in food, have been banned since 1986 for use on fresh
fruits and vegetables.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Canada ordered 34 European-built Airbus A320
passenger jets at a total cost of $1.5 billion for the aircraft and
parts.
   The government-owned airline also said Wednesday it has taken an
option to buy 20 additional A320s, the world's first fully
computerized civilian aircraft and the fastest-selling plane in
aviation history.
   Air Canada also said it will ban smoking on all North American
flights effective Sept. 3.
</TEXT>
