<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     07-21 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Eases, Silver Trading Hectic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in earlier European trading
today. Gold prices fell and the London silver market was busy.
   Foreign currency dealers said the dollar was supported by
underlying bullish sentiment, but capped by the fear of central
bank intervention. They predicted the currency would remain locked
in a narrow range for the immediate future.
   ``There's good two-way trading, but the market is very
nervous,'' said one senior trader with a large Italian bank in Rome.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar built upon overnight gains in New York, rising 0.45 yen
to a closing 133.50. Later, in London, it was quoted at 133.27 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 1.8607 West German marks, up from 1.8520; 1.5350
Swiss francs, down from 1.5360; 6.2420 French francs, down from
6.2455; 2.0919 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0910; 1,372.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,371.50; and 1.1960 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1959.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7190, more expensive for
buyers than late Wednesday's $1.7085.
   Gold eased in quiet London trading. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$443.20 a troy ounce, down from late Wednesday's $444.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $443.60, down from $445 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.42 to close at a bid $444.43.
   Silver dropped as low as $7.63 a troy ounce on profit-taking
this morning, then climbed back on speculative buying from
Switzerland and the Middle East, bullion dealers said.
   The metal was quoted at midday at a bid $7.73, little changed
from late Wednesday's $7.75.
   Dealers said the continuing silver miners' strike in Peru is
still influencing trading, but that information about the strike is
sketchy, contributing to silver's volatility.
   One dealer said the market is full of contradictory reports
about when and if the strike will end, as well as about how much of
the country's silver output is affected.
</TEXT>
