<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-21 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Fluctuate, Dollar Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fluctuated wildly today on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange in heavy but cautious trading, while the dollar gained
against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 404.95-point
winner Wednesday, added 122.16 points, or 0.44 percent, to close at
27,676.14.
   The Nikkei, the exchange's most widely followed barometer,
opened slightly above its close Wednesday. It dipped in early
morning trade from heavy profit-taking by investors taking
advantage of the previous day's sharp leap.
   The index fell 228 points in the late morning to 27,416.24, but
gradually recovered the rest of the day. Today's volume on the
first section of the exchange was 1.5 billion shares.
   ``The bottom flow of the market was bullish all day,'' said a
broker at a major securities firm in Tokyo, speaking on condition
of anonymity. ``It was able to absorb heavy profit-taking and ended
with a plus.''
   He said investors appeared uncertain about where to put their
money in the market after two consecutive days of extremely
volatile trading.
   Steel shares were higher today. On Wednesday, most of steel
shares plunged, with Nippon Steel a 60-point loser and Nippon Kokan
a 55-point loser.
   In contrast, electronics and automobile shares, which had been
seen as replacing steel stocks as the market leaders, failed to
make expected gains because of heavy profit-taking.
   Meanwhile, the dollar closed at 133.50 yen in Tokyo, up 0.45 yen
from Wednesday's finish.
   The dollar, which gained 0.65 yen in New York overnight, opened
at 133.65 yen, up 0.60 yen from Wednesday's close. It traded in a
narrow range of 133.50-134.00 yen.
   Currency dealers said the dollar opened near the New York
closing level of 133.85 yen, and seemed likely to remain in that
range.
   ``Insurance companies and trading houses snapped up and bought
the dollar everytime it retreated to the lower 133's, and that kept
the dollar high all day,'' said an exchange dealer for a major
investment bank in Tokyo, also speaking on condition of ananymity.
</TEXT>
