<DOCNO> AP880721-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0831EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock Bjt   07-21 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock, Bjt,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roy Disney Firm Makes $2.64 Billion Bid for Instant-Film Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. hinted it would reject a
proposed friendly takeover by Roy E. Disney _ nephew of the late
Walt Disney _ who announced a bid that values the instant-film
company at $2.84 billion.
   Disney, an investor with an estimated personal wealth of $560
million, announced the offer Wednesday and disclosed he already
owns 6.9 percent of Cambridge, Mass.,-based Polaroid through his
family's Shamrock Holdings Inc.
   Polaroid said it was reviewing the $40-a-share cash offer with
the help of outside advisers, but suggested management would look
unfavorably on a buyout.
   Referring to a retrenchment plan involving layoffs and
cost-cutting that was announced last week, Polaroid said in a news
release: ``We firmly believe that this is, without doubt, the right
course for Polaroid and for all of its shareholders, employees,
customers and communities.''
   Polaroid's stock shot up $6 to $40 a share Wednesday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Polaroid's retrenchment plan, announced July 12, was widely seen
as an anti-takeover measure, and analysts said Wednesday the timing
of the Shamrock offer suggested it was the trigger for the Polaroid
changes.
   ``It would be very hard to say they're unassociated,'' William
Relyea, who follows Polaroid for Eberstadt Fleming Inc. in New
York, said of the offer and the changes announced at Polaroid.
   Polaroid said it would cut up to 8 percent of its U.S. workforce
and save $50 million a year by reducing overhead and research and
development costs. The company also announced it would repurchase
$300 million of its own shares and create an employee stock
ownership program that owns 14 percent of the company's stock.
   Polaroid also said it would enter the $7 billion-a-year world
market for conventional film, challenging Eastman Kodak Co. and
Fuji Photo Film Co. Ltd.
   Disney described Polaroid's planned foray into the conventional
film business as a misguided attempt to regain momentum in the face
of a stagnating market for instant cameras and film.
   ``The announcement of the company's entry into the conventional
consumer film business appears to be a pedestrian attempt to give
the company new direction,'' Stanley P. Gold, Shamrock president
and chief executive officer, said in a news release.
   ``It betrays Polaroid's heritage of invention and creativity in
the development of new products and markets,'' he said.
   Gold also denounced Polaroid's stock repurchase and employee
stock ownership plans as a ``management entrenchment scheme.''
   In a letter delivered Wednesday to I. MacAllister Booth,
Polaroid president and chief executive officer, Shamrock proposed
that Polaroid management cooperate with the takeover offer.
   Including a recent issue of 10 million shares that created the
employee stock ownership program, Polaroid has 71 million shares
outstanding. The $40-a-share offer thus places a value of $2.84
billion on the company.
   Shamrock already holds 4.93 million shares, or 6.9 percent. To
buy the rest at $40 a share would cost Shamrock $2.64 billion.
   Shamrock offered as an alternative, if approved by the Polaroid
board, to pay a smaller amount of cash and agree to share the
after-tax proceeds of any money Polaroid might win in the damage
trial of its $5.7 billion patent infringement suit against Kodak.
   Kodak and Polaroid are scheduled to appear in U.S. District
Court in Boston on Jan. 9 to begin the damage award trial in the
suit, in which Polaroid claims Kodak violated Polaroid patents on
instant film and cameras from 1976 to 1986. Kodak calls the claim
unreasonably inflated.
   Disney is the son of the late Roy O. Disney, brother of
Disneyland creator Walt and the organizer of the business side of
the Disney empire. Forbes magazine last year listed Disney as being
worth $560 million.
   Shamrock, an investment vehicle for Disney's family, has
holdings in Walt Disney Co., as well as three television and 14
radio stations, 22 percent of Enterra, an energy services company,
real estate and a diverse investment portfolio. Shamrock's most
recent acquisition was Music Plus, a 56-outlet Los Angeles record
store chain.
   In announcing its revitalization plan July 12, Polaroid said it
planned to lay off between 500 and 800 workers in a cost-cutting
move. The Polaroid workforce has dropped from about 20,000 to
13,000 since 1978.
   In announcing the buyout offer, Shamrock also said it had filed
suit in Delaware Chancery Court challenging the employee stock
ownership plan as being overly dependent on borrowing and seeking
damages over cancellation of a meeting between Disney and Booth.
   Shamrock said it had filed suit in federal court in
Massachusetts seeking to overturn the state's anti-takeover law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
