<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Beatrice     07-21 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beatrice,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beatrice Co. Sheds `For Sale' Sign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food maker Beatrice Co. has taken down its ``For
Sale'' sign, prompting speculation that Chairman Donald P. Kelly is
about to begin another lucrative exercise in conglomerate-building.
   Chicago-based Beatrice revealed in its quarterly filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission it has stopped looking for a
buyer following a breakdown in negotiations with an unidentified
company.
   Some food-industry analysts said Wednesday they expected Kelly
to launch a new effort to build a conglomerate, using one or more
of Beatrice's businesses as a vehicle for acquisitions.
   ``Kelly needs a vehicle to do what he does best and I think
he'll be looking for that vehicle,'' said Ronald Morrow, an analyst
in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Kelly, 66, employed such a strategy as chairman of E-II Holdings
Inc., an acquisition vehicle he built from some Beatrice units
after Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. took Beatrice private in 1986
and installed him as chairman.
   E-II was bought by American Brands Inc. for $2.7 billion earlier
this year after E-II made a bid to acquire that company.
   Morrow said Kelly could create a suitable acquisition vehicle by
buying or spinning off as an independent company one or more of
Beatrice's profitable subsidiaries, which consist of Hunt-Wesson
Inc., Swift-Ekrich Inc. and Beatrice Cheese Inc.
   Beatrice, once a $13 billion conglomerate, has sold all of its
other assets since going private. It had hoped to find a single
buyer for the remainder of the company.
   But following the termination of talks with the unidentified
potential buyer, ``Beatrice has no current plans to engage in
further discussions relating to the acquisition of Beatrice by a
third party or the disposition of its major operating companies,''
the company said in the SEC filing.
   Analysts said industry rumors held that Beatrice had been
negotiating a buyout with Netherlands-based foods giant Unilever
NV, but Beatrice spokesman Charles Long would not comment on that.
   Long said Kelly might announce plans for himself and Beatrice in
September.
   Despite the intense speculation that has followed Kelly since
the E-II buyout, Roger Spencer, a Chicago-based analyst with
PaineWebber Inc., said he doubted Beatrice's announcement masked
secret designs.
   ``I think they evidently weren't able to attract a price in line
with their valuation for the property and the owners have decided
to run it as an operating company,'' Spencer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
