<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Allied-Signal     07-21 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Allied-Signal,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allied-Signal Reports Lower Quarterly Net</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied-Signal Inc. reported a 16
percent decline in its second-quarter earnings over a year ago when
it took a one-time gain on the sale of discontinued operations.
   The company said Wednesday that net income for the three months
ended June 30 fell to $128 million, or 85 cents a share, from $148
milion, or 85 cents a share, in 1987.
   Sales rose to $3.12 billion from $2.84 billion.
   Without the $37 million sale of several operations in 1987 _
among them, Linotype Group and Ampex Corp. _ Allied-Signal would
have realized a jump in profits from last year. The company said
earnings from continuing operations in the 1987 second quarter were
$111 million, or 64 cents a share.
   For the first six months of the year, Allied-Signal said net
income on continuing operations totaled $240 million, or $1.60 a
share, compared with earnings of $213 million, or $1.22 a share, in
1987. Sales rose 11 percent, to $6.1 billion from $5.5 billion.
   Chairman Edward L. Hennessy Jr. said the best performers during
the second quarter included Allied-Signal's engineered materials
business and its interest in Union Texas Petroleum.
   Earnings from its automotive and aerospace units declined during
the period, he said.
   Still, Hennessey said in a statement, ``We expect our overall
operating results to remain good for the remainder of the year, and
we anticipate substantial one-time gains in 1988 from our pending
transactions with Siemens AG in automotive electronics and with
Union Carbide in catalysts.''
</TEXT>
