<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AT&T-HiringFreeze     07-21 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AT&T-Hiring Freeze,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Announces Virtual Hiring Freeze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. has
announced a virtual hiring freeze in all divisions and will begin
reassigning employees to marketing and sales jobs to strengthen
itself against computer and long-distance competitors.
   Chairman Robert Allen announced the indefinite freeze in a
televised message broadcast to employees nationwide from New York
Wednesday. Allen said administrative costs were rising too rapidly
and he wanted to place the company's emphasis on increasing sales.
   Allen said the freeze and redeployment of staff would help
``bring our employees closer to customers and the marketplace.''
   ``We're moving people from field tents to the front line,''
Burke Stinson, a spokesman, said today.
   Stinson said the company was transferring 3,000 people to the
sales and marketing force, a process that began at two divisions in
April and is now expanding companywide.
   AT&T continues to lose money in the computer business and has
been increasingly hard-pressed by competitors in long-distance
telelphone service, its bread-and-butter business.
   On Wednesday the company announced its profit slipped 0.3
percent in the second quarter as revenue rose 4.3 percent.
   The company is recruiting volunteers for the sales jobs from
among its 95,000 entry-level and second-level managers, although
all managers are eligible, Stinson said.
   The only hiring to continue will be college recruiting and
``strategic hiring of people who can help our marketing,'' he said.
   AT&T has about 315,000 employees, a total that has shrunk
steadily through layoffs and other steps since the 1984 breakup of
the Bell System.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
