<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-ITT     07-21 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-ITT,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ITT Earnings Fell 12 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ITT Corp.'s second-quarter profit fell 12
percent from the level of a year earlier, when results were boosted
by a one-time $28 million gain from the sale of Virgin Islands
Telephone Co., the company said Thursday.
   Earnings were helped by stronger results at the Hartford
insurance company; Sheraton hotels' European and Latin American
operations; defense technology; industrial and forest products; and
the 37 percent owned Alcatel NV, a European-based
telecommunications company, ITT said.
   ITT said it earned $228 million, or $1.59 per common share or
common equivalent, down from a restated $259 million, or $1.70 per
common share or common equivalent, in the same quarter of 1987.
   Net income for the 1988 quarter included $11 million in tax
benefits at the Hartford, down from $23 million in benefits a year
earlier. Excluding the phone company sale and the tax benefits,
earnings per share would have risen 10 percent.
   Revenue for the quarter rose 7 percent to $5.3 billion from $4.9
billion a year earlier. The totals include insurance and finance
revenues of $2.8 billion, up from $2.7 billion.
   Through repurchases, the company reduced its number of common
equivalent shares by about 6 percent in comparison to a year
earlier. Common equivalents include preferred shares and debentures
that are convertible into common stock.
   For the first half of 1988, net income totaled $407 million, or
$2.84 a share, up from $352 million, or $2.30 per share. Revenue
rose 9 percent to $10.3 billion from $9.5 billion. Revenue from
insurance and finance rose to $5.8 billion from $5.4 billion.
</TEXT>
