<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-21 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade following forecasts for a
return to hot, dry weather in the Midwest.
   The storm system that brought badly needed rain to the
drought-stricken region over the past several days has moved east.
The weather was expected to remain mild and dry into the weekend,
and the National Weather Service's latest 6-to-10-day forecast
predicts a return to warmer- and drier-than-normal conditions by
the middle of next week.
   Corn and wheat futures posted solid gains in early trading. Oats
and soybeans were mixed but mostly higher after a sharp, three-day
decline triggered by the rain.
   ``They're kind of raising their heads a little bit off the floor
after being pounded into the basement,'' said Jerry Gidel, grain
analyst with G.H. Miller & Co. in Chicago.
   But Gidel said he expected the markets to trade cautiously today.
   ``Maybe there's light at the end of the tunnel or maybe there's
another train,'' he said. ``Who knows?''
   In early trading, wheat was 5\ cents to 6 cents higher with
September at $3.86{ a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 7 cents higher
with September at $3.18{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to 5
cents higher with September at $2.78{ a bushel; soybeans were 1{
cents lower to 21 cents higher with August at $8.55 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while most pork futures were sharply
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .50 cent to .87 cent higher with August at
65.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with August at 75.50 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower
to 1.15 cents higher with August at 44.05 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.58 cent to the limit 2 cents higher with July
at 37.75 cents a pound.
   Most livestock and meat futures settled lower on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
