<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Oil     07-21 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Oil,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schlumberger Reports Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Schlumberger Ltd., a New York-based oil services concern, on
Thursday reported its second-quarter earnings increased nearly
five-fold, due in part to firmer prices for the company's services,
market gains and the sale of a business unit.
   Net income for the quarter ended June 30 totaled $144 million,
or 53 cents a share, up from $30.2 million, or 11 cents a share in
the year-ago period. Revenue rose 22 percent to $1.35 billion from
$1.11 billion in the second quarter of 1987.
   The figures include a $35 million gain from the sale of the
company's electricity control and transformers division.
   Schlumberger Chairman Euan Baird said in a statement the
company's worldwide oilfield services operations grew 20 percent,
boosted by firmer prices and market gains.
   He said that so far the price of oil and gas has ``had little
effect on oil company activity,'' but cautioned that if ``present
price levels continue to erode, the strength of the normal second
half surge in rig activity in North America will be adversely
affected.''
   For the year to date, Schlumberger reported net income of $245
million, or 90 cents a share, compared to $35 million, or 13 cents
a share in the first six months of 1987. Revenue totaled $2.65
billion, up from $2.21 billion in the year-ago period.
   Schlumberger performs specialized service to oil drillers and
producers in addition to making equipment and machinery.
</TEXT>
