<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Computer     07-21 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Computer,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Data General Returns To Profitability; Apollo Reports Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Data General Corp. posted a profit in its latest quarter, while
Apollo Computer Inc. had a loss, the computer makers announced
Thursday.
   Data General, the minicomputer company based in Westboro, Mass.,
said it earned $1.9 million, or 6 cents a share, in its third
fiscal quarter in contrast to a loss of $65.1 million a year
earlier that included a one-time charge of $53.8 million for
restructuring and cost-reduction. Second-quarter revenue rose 5.5
percent to $330.7 million from $313.6 million.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Data General said
it earned $31.5 million, or $1.06 a share, compared to a loss a
year earlier of $104.4 million. Revenue rose 8.6 percent to $1.02
billion from $942 million a year earlier.
   ``While we remain profitable, we are disappointed with the level
of revenues generated in the current quarter,'' Edson D. de Castro,
the president, said in a written statement. He said profits had
been hurt by increased hiring in research and development and
sales, which will eventually help results.
   Apollo Computer, a maker of computer workstations based in
Chelmsford, Mass., had warned investors earlier this month that it
expected a loss of $5 million to $8 million in the quarter. It
reported it lost $7.9 million in contrast to a profit of $7.6
million, or 21 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue rose 9 percent to $143.5 million from $132.2 million.
   For the first six months, Apollo earned $2.5 million, or 7 cents
a share, down from a profit of $14.0 million, or 39 cents a share,
a year earlier. Revenue rose 22 percent to $312.4 million from
$255.6 million.
   Apollo has blamed the sales shortfall primarily on customers'
holding off while waiting for new products, and the failure of its
West German subsidiary to meet its plan. Analysts have said Apollo
is facing intense competition from Sun Microsystems Inc., its chief
rival in the workstation market. Workstations are similar to
personal computers, except more powerful.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
