<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Earns-GM 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-GM, 1st Ld-Writethru,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Posts Earnings Gain for 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 15th graf, Hughes' earnings ... in 1987., to fix
1987 net to $140.8 million sted $410.8 million.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said today its net profit
rose 53 percent in the second quarter from a year ago, but the
increase would have been 28 percent if an accounting change had
been made retroactive.
   The company attributed the strong gain to record-breaking
overseas results and improved performance in North America.
   The world's largest automaker said it had an after-tax profit of
$1.5 billion, or $4.52 a common share, in the April-June period,
compared with earnings of $980.3 million, or $2.80 a common share,
in the same quarter a year earlier.
   The company said, however, that if an accounting change made in
the third quarter of 1987 had been applied to the second-quarter
results for 1987, its profit for the year-ago period would have
been $1.17 billion, or $3.39 a share.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 12 percent to a record $29.9 billion
from $26.7 billion.
   In the first six months of 1988, GM earnings rose 36.8 percent
to $2.6 billion, or $7.63 a common share, from $1.90 billion, or
$5.42 a common share, a year earlier.
   The company said that if the accounting change had been
retroactive to the entire first half of 1987, the year-ago profit
would have amounted to $2.29 billion, or $6.65 per common share.
   Six-month revenue rose 6.6 percent to $56.3 billion from $52.8
billion.
   GM changed the way it depreciates plants, tools and equipment in
the third quarter of 1987.
   In a statement, GM said the results reflect ``its increasing
competitive North American automotive operations _ both in terms of
strengthening market position and improving operating efficiency.
Further, overseas earnings in 1988 are exceeding the record levels
achieved in 1987.''
   In 1987, GM barely broke even building and selling cars and
trucks in North America. Much of its $3.56 billion in 1987 earnings
came from accounting changes, tax benefits and record contributions
from its streamlined overseas businesses and its subsidiaries.
   On Wednesday, GM reported earnings by its three subsidiaries _
General Motors Acceptance Corp., Electronic Data Systems Corp. and
GM Hughes Electronics Corp.
   GM blamed higher interest expenses and a drop in auto financings
for an 18.9 percent drop in GMAC earnings to $333.9 million from
$411.8 million a year ago.
   Earnings by EDS, a computer services company, rose a third to
$95.7 million, or 78 cents per GM Class E share, on revenue of
$1.20 billion. That compared with earnings of $72 million, or 59
cents per Class E share, on revenue of $1.08 billion a year ago.
   Hughes' earnings rose 16.4 percent to $163.9 million, or 50
percents per GM Class H share, on revenue of $2.87 billion. That
compared with earnings of $140.8 million, or 44 cents per Class H
share, on revenue of $2.62 billion in 1987.
   Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said they will report
second-quarter earnings next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
