<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-MCA     07-21 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-MCA,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MCA Profits Fall 79 Percent on Toy Write-Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainment conglomerate MCA
Inc. said Thursday its second-quarter profit dropped 79 percent
because of losses on an unpopular toy and an investment in the
struggling toymaker Coleco Industries Inc.
   The movie, music and toy company, which previously announced it
would take a $35 million charge against its second-quarter earnings
on the toy company problems, said Thursday it earned $8.1 million,
or 11 cents a share in the quarter. That was down from $39.3
million, or 52 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   Without the charge, second quarter earnings before taxes would
have increased 12 percent over the previous year, the company said.
   Sales for the quarter ended June 30 were $643.6 million, up from
$611.4 million a year earlier.
   The $35 million charge resulted from reducing the value of
Gotcha paint guns in inventory at the company's LJN Toys
subsidiary, and cutting the value of the company's investment in
Coleco, which has filed for protection from its creditors under
federal bankruptcy law.
   Many of the $30 Gotcha guns were returned by unsatisfied
customers and LJN has stopped making them.
   Operating income in MCA's film division was boosted by ``The New
Leave it to Beaver'' TV series becoming available for reruns and by
pay TV availability of the movies ``The Secret of My Success'' and
``Dragnet.'' Operating income rose in the music and book publishing
divisions and decreased in retail, mail order and toy operations.
   In the first half of 1988, MCA reported a profit of $34.9
million, or 48 cents per share, on sales of $1.25 billion. That was
down 49 percent from the profit of $68.1 million, or 90 cents per
share, on sales of $1.14 billion in the first half of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
