<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Amex     07-21 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Amex,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Express Reports Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. reported a second-quarter
profit Thursday following a loss a year ago, when the financial
services company joined major banks in raising its loan-loss
provision during the Third World debt crisis.
   The company's Travel Related Services division, which runs its
credit card business, had the biggest growth in income during the
period. But earnings declined for Shearson-Lehman Hutton Holdings
Inc. due to lagging expenses from last year's E.F. Hutton
acquisition.
   American Express said it earned $280.8 million, or 66 cents a
share, in the three months ended June 30, compared with a revised
$600,000 loss in 1987. Revenue totaled $5.58 billion, up 21 percent
from $4.59 billion last year.
   Last year's second quarter included a $520 million after-tax
charge stemming from American Express Bank's loan-loss reserve
addition to cover shaky loans of less developed countries.
   American Express Bank reported second quarter net income of $32
million, vs. a $456 million loss a year ago.
   Many other big banks also suffered losses after taking similar
action as a result of Brazil's decision to suspend interest
payments on most of its foreign bank debt and the rise of
concessionary debt repayment plans negotiated by several Third
World countries.
   The 1987 quarterly results were restated to include $73 million
of tax-deferred benefits due to accounting changes.
   For the first half of the year, American Express netted $546.5
million, or $1.28 a share, on revenue of $10.95 billion. That
compared with last year's earnings of $313.3 million, or 70 cents a
share, and $8.74 billion in revenue.
   ``It was an outstanding quarter that demonstrated the soundness
of the strategies each of our business units has been
implementing,'' Chairman James D. Robinson said of the latest
results.
   At Travel Related Services, quarterly earnings climbed 18
percent to a record $196 million from $167 million. Revenue totaled
$1.8 billion, up 20 percent from last year.
   The company said its credit-card charge volume reached an
all-time high of $22.1 billion, up 20 percent from 1987 and
enhanced by its purchase protection plan and the popularity of its
Optima card overseas. Travelers checks sales also rose.
   IDS Financial Services had a 21 percent jump in earnings to a
record $36 million from $30 million, American Express said. The
company said sales of annuity and investment certificates led the
increase, but sales of mutual funds, limited partnership and life
insurance fell.
   Shearson Lehman Brothers Holdings reported net income of $51
million, compared with $64 million last year. Revenue totaled $2.5
billion, vs. $1.7 billion. The results included a $69 million
pre-tax charge for expenses associated with the Hutton acquisition.
   American Express currently owns 70.6 percent of all Shearson
Lehman's oustanding common shares, and its share of the earnings
was $32 million, compared with $47 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
