<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     07-21 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0322</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground in quiet trading
today, reversing Wednesday's rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 13.34 points on
Wednesday, fell 11.03 to 2,099.57 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
448 up, 954 down and 495 unchanged.
   The dollar declined against leading foreign currencies today,
and interest rates rose in the credit markets.
   Prices of long-term government bonds fell nearly $5 for each
$1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 9.25-9.30 percent
range.
   Analysts said traders were showing little interest in chasing
after stocks in advance of the government's monthly report Friday
on the consumer price index.
   Technology stocks were notably weak amid disappointment over the
trend in second-quarter earnings reports issued by several
high-tech companies of late.
   ``In the technology sector there seems to be a disaster or two a
day,'' said Newton Zinder at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Tandem Computers was the most active NYSE issue, down 2~ at 14{.
The company said its earnings for the fiscal quarter ended June 30
came to 18 cents a share, down from 26 cents in the like period a
year earlier.
   Data General, which posted a $1.8 million quarterly operating
profit that fell short of expectations on Wall Street, dropped 1~
to 20{.
   Among other computer and technology stocks, Motorola dropped 1]
to 47|; Hewlett-Packard 1{ to 51[, and Microsoft 2} to 61\ in the
over-the-counter market.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.91 to 151.65. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 1.34 at 307.84.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 107.04 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
