<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-InlandSteel     07-21 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Inland Steel,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports 2nd-Qtr Profit Up Fourfold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inland Steel Industries Inc. said Thursday its
second-quarter profit soared more than fourfold due to strong
demand for U.S.-made steel, higher prices and lower production
costs.
   Inland Steel reported record net income of $79.9 million, or
$2.27 per share, for the three months ending June 30, compared with
$17.5 million, or 44 cents per share, for the same period a year
ago.
   The previous record quarterly earnings of $63.6 million were
reported for the first three months of 1988, the company said.
   Inland's second-quarter sales increased 24 percent to $1.05
billion from $845 million, while steel mill shipments during the
period totaled 1.3 million tons, a 12 percent gain from the
year-ago period.
   For the first half of 1988, Inland had net income of $143.5
million, or $4.06 per share, up 80 percent from $79.9 million,
$2.43 per share, for the first six months of 1987.
   First half sales rose to 19 percent to $2.01 billion from $1.69
billion in 1987.
   A sharp rise in industrial expansion and plant modernization led
to increased demand for structural steel while the dollar's
dramatic fall in value last year against the Japanese yen and West
German mark raised the price of imported steel above that of
domestically produced steel, said Inland spokesman Sam Saran.
   Chairman Frank W. Luerssen said shipments of domestic steel
likely will reach 80 million tons this year compared with 76
million tons last year, and Inland's shipments probably will exceed
the company's earlier estimate of 5 million tons.
</TEXT>
