<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     07-21 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls In Europe, Precious Metals Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mostly lower in moderate
European trading Thursday, although dealers said central banks did
not intervene against the American currency.
   Gold and silver prices rose.
   Currency dealers in Europe attributed the dollar's decline to
several factors, including unconfirmed rumors that U.S. Treasury
Secretary James Baker might resign soon, fears of central-bank
intervention and expectations of higher West German interest rates.
   Traders in Frankfurt said the dollar is likely to stabilize and
will probably test its upside potential again early next week.
   ``Somewhere around here it'll find its bottom for the time
being, and then there'll be a reaction upwards again,'' said a
trader at a large Frankfurt bank.
   Dealers in London and Frankfurt said there was no evidence of
central-bank intervention in dollar trading for the first time in
several weeks, although there were reports that the Bank of England
sold sterling for other European currencies to stem the pound's
recent rise.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7265 dollars, more
expensive for buyers than late Wednesday's $1.7085.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.8375 West German marks, down from 1.8520; 1.5275 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5360; 6.2000 French francs, down from 6.2455;
2.0765 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0910; 1,363.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,371.50; and 1.1968 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1959.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.45 yen to a closing 133.50. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 132.25 yen.
   In the precious metals markets, speculative buying from
Switzerland and the Middle East and rumors regarding a miners'
strike in Peru forced the price of silver upwards, although
profit-taking slowed its rise.
   Dealers in Zurich said that gold's near-term performance also
will depend on silver, which has towed gold along.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of 4$45.80 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $444.50. In Zurich, the bid price
was $445.50, up from dollars late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.42 to close at a bid $444.43.
   Silver, which hit a high of $7.90 in Europe, finished at a late
bid price of $7.81 a troy ounce in London, compared with
Wednesday's $7.75.
</TEXT>
