<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Brokers     07-21 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Brokers,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PaineWebber Earnings Skid on Low Market Activity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PaineWebber Group Inc. reported Thursday its
earnings plummeted in the second quarter as lackluster market
conditions took a heavy toll on the brokerage's revenue.
   PaineWebber said it earned $159,000 in the three months ended
June 30, down 99 percent from $17.6 million, or 53 cents per share
of common stock, in the same period a year earlier. There were no
earnings per common share in the latest quarter after dividends
were paid to preferred shareholders.
   Revenue for the quarter fell to $565.7 million from $637.6
million in the same period a year earlier.
   PaineWebber said its commission revenue fell 32 percent during
the quarter, while revenue from transactions for the company's own
account fell 13 percent. The company reported a 5 percent increase
in its investment banking revenue and a 25 percent jump in asset
management revenue.
   ``PaineWebber's results were adversely affected by lethargic
market conditions,'' company chairman Donald B. Marron said in a
statement.
   ``In particular, our retail business suffered from relatively
low volume as individual investors remained on the sidelines.''
   Other brokerage firms have reported sharply lower second-quarter
profits as market activity remained depressed in the aftermath of
the October stock market crash.
   For the first half, PaineWebber said it earned $20.9 million, or
27 cents per share, down 58 percent from $50.2 million, or $1.58
per share, in the first six months of 1987.
   Revenue for the period declined to $1.17 billion from $1.27
billion.
</TEXT>
