<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-McDonald's     07-21 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-McDonald's,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McDonald's Profit Up 19 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's Corp. said its profit
increased 19 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier,
helped by improving profitability in its foreign operations and
several sales promotions in the United States.
   The fast-food giant reported Thursday that its second-quarter
earnings rose to $177.2 million, or 94 cents a share, from $148.7
million, or 78 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   Second-quarter revenue _ including sales at company-operated
restaurants and fees from franchises _ rose 14 percent, to $1.43
billion from $1.24 billion. More than 75 percent of the McDonald's
restaurants in the United States are franchised.
   Forty percent of the more than 500 new restaurants to be added
each year will be located outside the United States, Chairman Fred
L. Turner said in a press statement.
   ``Maximizing sales at existing restaurants is accomplished
through attention to operations, reinvestment, product development
and refinement, and effective marketing programs,'' Turner said. He
noted that the company's foreign operations are achieving economies
of scale, bringing an improvement in profitability.
   The company is continuing to monitor the effects of the drought
in the Farm Belt on its food commodity costs, said President and
Chief Executive Officer Michael R. Quinlan.
   He noted that McDonald's food costs as a percent of its sales
have declined in both the first and second quarters of this year
compared with 1987. In addition, more than 30 percent of the
company-operated restaurants are located outside of the United
States, and are not necessarily affected by the drought.
   In the first half of the year, McDonald's earnings rose 19
percent _ to $303 million, or $1.61 a share, from $255.7 million,
or $1.34 a share, in the first six months of 1987.
   First-half revenue was up 15 percent, to $2.65 billion from
$2.31 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
