<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Textron,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Sharp Drop In Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Inc. reported a 24.3 percent
decline in its second-quarter earnings Thursday that it attributed
in part to a seven-week strike at a Connecticut subsidiary.
   The company, which has interests in aerospace technology,
commercial products and financial services, reported net income of
$68.9 million, or 78 cents a share, for the three months ending
July 2, compared to $91 million, or $1.06 a share, for the same
period a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenues were $1.81 billion, down from $1.82
billion a year earlier.
   For the first six months of the fiscal year, net income was
$107.3 million, or $1.21 a share, compared to $151.2 million, or
$1.79 a share, a year earlier. Revenues for the first half of 1988
slipped to $3.63 billion from $3.66 billion a year earlier.
   The 1988 results included a first-quarter extraordinary loss of
$29.7 million after taxes.
   Textron Chairman B.F. Dolan said in a news release that the
strike at Textron Lycoming's Stratford, Conn., plant, hurt the
company's performance. About 2,200 United Auto Workers members
struck the plant, which makes gas turbines for military tanks and
helicopters and civilian aircraft, after the company demanded
give-backs on benefits.
   ``With the recent seven-week strike at the Lycoming division now
settled, we are optimistic that Textron will maintain its
first-half momentum and achieve another year of improved earnings
from continuing operations,'' Dolan said.
</TEXT>
