<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Banks     07-21 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Banks,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BankAmerica Posts Second Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp., the nation's
third-largest banking company, on Thursday reported a profit for
the second quarter after a hefty loss a year ago, when it joined
other banks in raising its loan-loss provision to cover shaky Third
World debt.
   Meanwhile, H.F. Ahmanson & Co., parent company of Home Savings
of America in Irwindale, Calif., the nation's largest savings and
loan, said it netted $48.83 million, or 50 cents a share in the
second quarter. That compared with earnings of $34.36 million, or
35 cents a share, in 1987.
   Gains from loan sales were partly responsible for the increase,
the company said.
   BankAmerica said its net income for the three months ended June
30 totaled $162 million, or 85 cents a share, compared with loss of
$1.13 billion in 1987.
   During last year's quarter it added $1.1 billion to its reserves
for possible losses on loans to less developed countries. Many
other big banks had taken similar action, and consequently, lost
money or saw their earnings decline.
   Several special items affected BankAmerica's second-quarter
results, raising net income by $8 million.
   A $46 million legal settlement received by Seafirst Corp.
increased net income on an after-tax basis by $43 million. An $11
million net charge was included in non-interest expense because of
a customer promotional program, but was partially offset by other
gains.
   For the first half of this year, BankAmerica netted $271
million, or $1.41 per share. That compared with a $1.07 billion
loss a year ago.
   Chairman A.W. Clausen said the second-quarter earnings _ the
fourth straight quarter of operating profitability _ demonstrated
the strength of the bank's recovery.
   ``Higher interest revenues in the quarter were due to growth in
loan volume of $1.7 billion, an increase in the net interest
margin, and lower nonaccrual assets,'' he said. ``Net credit losses
also continued to decline. In addition, our increasing
profitability contributed to growth in our capital base.''
   The quarterly results exceeded some analysts' expectations.
   ``The numbers look quite good, better than we expected,'' said
Donald K. Crowley, of Keefe, Bruyette & Woods Inc. in San
Francisco. ``The margins look strong. This recovery appears to be
sustainable for the future. I can't find anything I consider
negative.''
   ``There's no question they're making progress,'' added Dan
Williams, of Sutro & Co. Inc. in San Francisco. ``They had a very
low level of net loan losses and most of the numbers appear to be
moving in the right direction.''
   The industry's highest estimate for BankAmerica earnings for the
second quarter had been about 75 cents per share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
