<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed mixed while corn and wheat
finished sharply higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade in
volatile trading that reflected an uncertain weekend weather
picture and weakening technical factors.
   Private forecasts for a mostly dry weekend in the Midwest and a
return to 100-degree temperatures as early as Monday supported the
soybean market through midday, analysts said. Conflicting
predictions for a wetter weekend kept prices from rising sharply.
   But the failure of the August soybean contract to rally above
$8.58 a bushel convinced several large investment firms it was time
to sell. Others joined in and the August soybean price plunged
nearly 40 cents before rebounding to close above $8.40 a bushel.
   ``There was definitely some disappointment that we couldn't get
much of a rally going, and they sunk her into the hold there for a
while,'' said Jerry Gidel, grains analyst with G.H. Miller & Co., a
Chicago-based trading firm.
   Corn and and wheat gained on expectations for new export
business, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 6{ cents higher with
September at $3.87 a bushel; corn was 5\ cents to 10 cents higher
with September at $3.17 a bushel; oats were 12 cents lower to 8
cents higher with September at $2.67{ a bushel; soybeans were 12{
cents lower to 15 cents higher with August at $8.44 a bushel.
</TEXT>
