<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Phone 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Phone, 1st Ld-Writethru,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bell Atlantic Up 5.5 Percent; U S West Up 25 Percent; Contel Up
121 Percent; Nynex Up .03 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to include Nynex earnings; picks up 4th
graf pvs, U S West ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Second-quarter profits were up 5.5 percent at Bell Atlantic
Corp. and flat at Nynex Corp., while stock offerings contributed to
earnings gains of 25 percent at U S West Inc. and 121 percent at
Contel Corp., the phone companies said Thursday.
   Bell Atlantic, the Philadelphia-based regional Bell holding
company, said its earnings rose to $344.1 million, or $1.74 a
share, from $326.1 million, or $1.64 a share, a year earlier.
Revenue fell 2.3 percent to $2.58 billion from $2.64 billion.
   For the six-month period, Bell Atlantic said its earnings rose
to $673.2 million, or $3.40 a share, from $633.6 million, or $3.18
a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $5.08 billion from $5.11
billion.
   Nynex, the New York-based regional Bell company for New York and
New England, said its profit edged up to $322.8 million from $322.7
million a year earlier. Earnings per share rose to $1.64 from $1.58
because of a stock buyback. Revenue rose 5.3 percent to $3.17
billion from $3.01 billion.
   For the first six months of the year, Nynex said its profit rose
to $633.9 million, or $3.18 a share, from $621.9 million, or $3.05
a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $6.24 billion from $5.90
billion.
   U S West, the regional Bell company based in Denver, said it
earned $336.3 million, or $1.83 a share, up from $268.8 million, or
$1.42 a share, a year earlier. The results were helped by an
after-tax gain of $88.7 million from the sale of stock in its
cellular and paging subsidiary. Revenue rose to $2.21 billion from
$2.11 billion.
   For the first six months, U S West said its earnings rose to
$576.8 million, or $3.13 a share, from $473 million, or $2.49 a
share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 5.3 percent to $4.37 billion
from $4.15 billion.
   Contel, a non-Bell company based in Atlanta that provides local
phone service in 31 states, said its profit rose to $104.5 million,
or $1.32 a share, from $47.4 million, or 61 cents a share, a year
earlier. Those results include an after-tax gain of $43.4 million
from a stock offering in its cellular phone subsidiary.
   Excluding the stock offering and other one-time factors,
earnings per share from recurring operations rose 20 percent,
Contel said.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 12 percent to $788.3 million from
$703.8 million.
   For the first six months of fiscal year, earnings rose to $163.4
million, or $2.07 a share, from $102.4 million, or $1.38 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose to $1.53 billion from $1.39 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880721-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 1611EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-GM Bjt   07-21 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-GM, Bjt,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Reports Strong Improvement for Second Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. reported Thursday that its
profit rose strongly in the second quarter as overseas operations
had a record-breaking performance and sales picked up in North
America.
   Financial analysts said the gains in domestic sales should cheer
the world's largest automaker, which has seen its U.S. market share
eroded in recent years.
   GM had after-tax earnings of $1.5 billion, or $4.52 a share, in
the April-June period, the company's best quarterly profit in four
years. That was up 53 percent from a net of $980.3 million, or
$2.80 a share, in the same quarter of 1987, but GM noted the gain
would have been about 28 percent if an accounting change had been
made retroactive to the first half of last year.
   GM said its profit for the 1987 period would have been $1.17
billion if the change had been in effect.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 12 percent to $29.9 billion from
$26.7 billion, surpassing GM's previous quarterly sales record of
$27.6 billion set in 1986.
   ``General Motors' improved profitability reflects its increasing
competitive North American automotive operations _ both in terms of
strengthening market position and improving operating efficiency,''
GM Chairman Roger Smith and President Robert Stempel said in a
joint statement.
   ``Further, overseas earnings in 1988 are exceeding the record
levels achieved in 1987,'' they said.
   For the first six months of 1988, GM had a profit of $2.6
billion, or $7.63 a share, on revenue of $56.3 billion. That was up
13.3 percent from the $2.29 billion, or $6.65 a share, it would
have earned on revenue of $52.8 billion a year ago, if the
accounting change had been in effect.
   GM slowed the rate of depreciation of plants, tools and
equipment beginning in the third quarter of 1987 to match
depreciation schedules used by its auto industry competition.
   Financial analysts were upbeat over GM's sales gains for the
quarter.
   ``The number of units produced per employee went up almost 17
percent versus second-quarter last year,'' said Ronald Glantz at
Montgomery Securities Inc. in San Francisco. ``That's phenomenally
good, showing the kind of earnings General Motors can have if sales
pick up.''
   In its announcement, GM said: ``Our main challenge is to
continue to build profitability in our North American automotive
business and to profitably raise our market share. We are committed
to managing our cost levels so that they are consistent with market
share.''
   The analysts agreed.
   ``Last year, (sales) volume was so low that most of their gains
came from accounting changes,'' said Kathleen Heaney with Nikko
Securities International in New York. ``This year, it seems based
on volume. Sales were strong in the first half, particularly in the
second quarter.''
   GM said that as of June 30, it had implemented $2.7 billion of
the $4 billion in cost cuts it plans to make during 1988.
   GM said it sold 2.25 million cars and trucks worldwide during
the quarter, which was up 9.3 percent from the previous year.
   The company said it held 35.1 percent of the U.S. market for
cars and light trucks built in North America. That was up slightly
from 33.8 percent at the end of June 1987.
   Last year, GM barely broke even building and selling cars and
trucks in North America. Much of its $3.56 billion in 1987 earnings
came from accounting changes, tax benefits and record contributions
from its streamlined overseas businesses and its subsidiaries.
   But in the second quarter of 1988, operating income rose 64
percent, to $1.8 billion from $1.1 billion a year ago. It rose 16
percent in the first six months, to $2.4 billion from $2.1 billion.
   GM reported Wednesday that earnings for the quarter rose 33
percent at its Electronic Data Systems subsidiary and 16.4 percent
at GM Hughes Electronics. Earnings were down 18.9 percent at
General Motors Acceptance Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
