<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Drugs     07-21 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Drugs,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Companies Report Earnings Rises in Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Three major pharmaceutical producers, Pfizer Inc.,
Schering-Plough Corp. and Squibb Corp., reported higher earnings
for the second quarter Thursday.
   Pfizer, based in New York, said its net income in the quarter
rose 21 percent on a worldwide sales gain of 9 percent. Net income
was $213.1 million, or $1.26 per share, vs. $175.8 million, or
$1.03 per share in the same period a year ago. Sales rose to $1.34
billion from $1.23 billion.
   For the first six months of 1988, net income was up 18 percent
to $432.9 million, or $2.57 per share, from $367.8 million, or
$2.16 per share. Revenue was up 12 percent to $2.63 billion from
$2.35 billion.
   The company said it had gains in all five of its business
segments: health care, agriculture, consumer products, materials
science and specialty chemicals. The health care sales gain
included significant growth in both pharmaceuticals and hospital
products, Pfizer said.
   Schering-Plough, of Madison, N.J., said its second-quarter
earnings jumped 22.4 percent on a sales gain of 9.8 percent.
   Net income was $101.0 million, or 90 cents per share, compared
with $82.5 million, or 71 cents per share. Sales totaled $752.6
million, vs. $685.3 million a year ago.
   For the six months, income was up 21 percent to $202.5 million,
or $1.81 per share, from $167.4 million, or $1.43 per share. Sales
rose 10 percent to $1.51 billion from $1.37 billion.
   The company attributed the earnings growth to strong gains in
its international pharmaceutical business and domestic consumer
operations. In addition to its drug sales, the company said sales
of contact lenses and Maybelline cosmetics also advanced.
   Squibb, of Princeton, N.J., said net income rose 20 percent on a
21 percent increase in sales. Earnings totaled $114.1 million, or
$1.16 per share, compared with $95.2 million, or 91 cents. Sales
were $644.6 million, up from $532.2 million.
   For the six months, income rose 25 percent to $205.0 million, or
$2.05 per share, from $164.6 million, or $1.57 per share. Sales
gained 24 percent, to $1.24 billion from just over $1 billion.
   Along with strong drug sales, the company said favorable
exchange rates also contributed to its good performance. It noted
that the Food and Drug Adminstration gave permission during the
quarter for Squibb to recommend expanded use of Capoten, its drug
used in treatment of congestive heart failure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
