<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-21 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Precious Metals Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined sharply Thursday against all
major currencies despite the absence of significant central-bank
intervention, while a strong British pound took center stage in
worldwide foreign-exchange trading.
   Gold prices fell after advancing overseas. Republic National
Bank of New York quoted a late bid of $441.50 for a troy ounce of
gold, down $3 from Wednesday.
   Currency traders said the dollar started out lower overseas due
to several factors, including nervousness of possible central-bank
dollar-selling and a report from an unidentified Bank of Japan
official that there was room for the dollar to decline further.
   ``That immediately caused the dollar to sell off in pretty
hectic trading in Europe and that continued here,'' explained James
T. McGroarty, a trader for Discount Corp.
   Dealers said there was no evidence of significant central-bank
intervention in dollar trading for the first time in several weeks,
although there were reports that the Bank of England sold sterling
for other European currencies to stem the pound's recent rise.
   McGroarty said traders are bullish on the pound due to the
strong British economy and the prospect for higher interest rates,
among other things.
   ``People are really taking a non-commital view of the dollar but
they're looking at sterling,'' he said.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7265, more expensive than
late Wednesday's $1.7085. Later, in New York, sterling fetched
$1.7280, up from $1.7054.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.45 yen to a closing 133.50 yen. But it fell in
London to 132.25 yen, and in New York to 131.575 yen from 133.775
yen late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.8375 West German marks, down from
1.8555; 1.5278 Swiss francs, down from 1.5392; 6.1980 French
francs, down from 6.2535; 1.1979 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19835; and 1,360.125 Italian lire, down from 1,373.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
1.8375 West German marks, down from 1.8520; 1.5275 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5360; 6.2000 French francs, down from 6.2455; 2.0765
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0910; 1.1968 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1959; and 1,363.50 Italian lire, down from 1,371.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $441.80 a troy ounce from $444.80 late Wednesday.
   However, gold rose in London to a late bid of $445.80 an ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $444.50. In Zurich, the late bid was
$445.50 an ounce, up from $445 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.42 an ounce to close at
$444.43.
   Silver bullion for current delivery fell on the New York Comex,
to $7.737 a troy ounce from $7.827 late Wednesday.
   Silver, which hit a high of $7.90 an ounce in Europe, finished
at a late bid price of $7.81 a troy ounce in London, compared with
Wednesday's $7.75.
   European dealers said speculative buying from Switzerland and
the Mideast and rumors regarding a miners' strike in Peru forced
the price of silver upwards, although profit-taking slowed its rise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
