<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Soviet-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frustrated Consumers Stash Rubles, Threatening Inflation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to ADD dollar amounts for average annual
U.S. savings, income; PICKS up 6th graf pvs, ``The current
five-year ... Deletes 16-17th grafs for transition bgng, ``Per
capita ... Edits for transition. Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associaed Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savings banks hold deposits equal to $1,700 for
every man, woman and child in the Soviet Union, which reflects how
difficult it is for people to find anything worth spending their
money on.
   The per capita savings figure of 1,000 rubles represents half a
year's salary for most Soviet workers and the hoard could generate
serious inflation when more consumer goods reach the market. The
figures were given Thursday, in a partial report on Soviet economic
performance in the first half of 1988.
   Savings banks hold personal deposits of 280 billion rubles ($451
billion) for the nation's 284 million residents, said Nikolai G.
Belov, deputy chairman of the Soviet State Committee on Statistics.
   That indicates Soviet citizens have far more savings in relation
to income than people in the United States or other Western
industrial countries.
   Last year, the average American saved only 3.7 percent of his
income, or $488, and Japanese workers put aside about 15.6 percent
of their income, according to The Wefa Group in Bala Cynwyd, Pa.
The average U.S. income was about $13,200 last year.
   Per capita savings were not given on an annual basis in the
Soviet economic report. Soviet salaries generally range between 150
and 200 rubles a month ($242 to $323 at the official exchange
rate), or about 1,800 to 2,400 rubles annually.
   What the latest figures say about the Soviet economy is that
desirable goods are scarce and consumers appear to be stashing
their money in fear of high prices when subsidies are removed from
basic items like food and housing.
   The current five-year economic plan crafted by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and his advisers calls for simultaneous increases in
quality and quantity, which Western analysts and some Soviet
economists consider unrealistic.
   Although broad figures Belov gave at a news conference indicated
the Kremlin was seeing the quantity output it has ordered, the
savings figure and a look in any state-run store illustrate the
slow improvement in production of consumer goods and services.
   Only about 10 percent of Soviet families own cars. Laundry is
done by hand in most homes for lack of washing machines and many
adults own just three or four changes of clothing.
   Economist Nikolai Shmelev has said the high savings level
indicates pent-up demand among consumers and is a potential cause
of inflation.
   Savings accounts grew by 42 billion rubles in 1987. Shmelev has
criticized the trend in a series of articles proposing improvements
in economic planning and analysis.
   In a speech to the Communist Party conference last month,
economist Leonid Abalkin echoed Western financial analysts in
saying Soviet leaders get a skewed picture of industrial
performance by measuring quantity but not quality.
   Abel Aganbegyan, another economist, told reporters in late June
the Soviet consumer is no better off now than before the economic
reforms Gorbachev introduced last year.
   ``Unfortunately, the majority of Soviet families are not
witnessing the material benefits of perestroika,'' he said.
Perestroika, which means restructuring, is what Gorbachev calls his
reform program.
   Reform has brought significant changes in personal freedom and
created a more open atmosphere, but little visible improvement in
the marketplace.
   The State Committee on Statistics reported in a dispatch
distributed by the Tass news agency that industrial output from
January through June was 4.7 percent higher than the first half of
1987.
   Soviets face little threat of job loss and are guaranteed state
pensions, theoretically lessening the need to put money away for
hard times or retirement. Housing costs are fixed at 3 percent of
family income.
   Shmelev and other economists favor reforms that would end state
subsidies and make prices of goods and services reflect their
actual cost.
   Soviet officials plan to introduce such changes in the 1990s,
but the growth in disposable cash could generate inflation before
that.
   ``This is a huge potential inflationary pressure,'' a Western
economics attache said. ``We're already seeing this in places like
Izmailovo.''
   Artists gather at Izmailovo Park in northeast Moscow each
weekend to sell their art works and handicrafts for high prices
that shoppers who want unique gifts are willing to pay.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Carol J. Williams is based in Moscow and has
reported on the Soviet Union for The Associated Press since July
1984.
</TEXT>
