<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Polaroid     07-21 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Polaroid,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polaroid Reports 2nd Qtr. Profit Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp., the target a takeover
bid by a California group, announced Thursday its net income fell
by 17.5 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier.
   For the three months ended July 3, Polaroid's net earnings were
$22.5 million, or 36 cents a share, compared with a profit of $27.3
million, or 44 cents per share, in the same period last year.
   Sales during the quarter rose to $483.3 million from $448.2
million.
   A statement by the instant photography company attributed the
profit decline to foreign currency exchange losses and a jump in
the worldwide tax rate from 34 percent to 52 percent, compared with
the second quarter last year.
   For first six months of 1988, net earnings were $35.3 million,
or 57 cents a share, on sales of $893.4 million, compared with net
earnings of $51.9 million, or 84 cents a share, on sales of $829.3
million for the same period last year.
   The latest report does not reflect Polaroid's restructuring
plan, announced last week, highlighted by 500 to 800 layoffs and
its planned global distribution of conventional color film,
directly challenging Eastman Kodak Co. and Fuji Photo Film Co. Ltd.
   The company also called for the issuance of 10 million new
shares under a mandated employee stock purchase plan and launched a
$300 million company stock repurchase program.
   On Wednesday, Shamrock Holding Inc., a Burbank, Calif.-based
investment firm that has major holdings in Walt Disney Co. and
several media properties, announced a $40-a-share cash tender offer
for Polaroid.
   Polaroid directors plan to meet July 26 to discuss the bid.
</TEXT>
