<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing Order,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spanish Airline Orders $105 Million in Boeing Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hispania Lineas Aereas has purchased four
advanced-technology 737-500 aircraft valued at more than $105
million from Boeing Commercial Airplanes, Boeing announced
Wednesday.
   The airline, based in Palma de Mallorca, Spain, will take
delivery of the 130-passenger airplanes between June and August
1991.
   Hispania, created in August 1982 as a cooperative and
incorporated in October 1987, now operates five new 737-300
airliners and two 737-200s under leases, Boeing said.
   Hispania is the first private Spanish airline to purchase planes
directly from a manufacturer, according to Boeing.
   The new plane features more fuel-efficient and quieter engines,
aerodynamic wing improvements, more on-board stowage area and wider
aisles, the company said.
   The Hispania order brings the total order of 737-500s to 127
made by 12 customers.
</TEXT>
