<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GAF     07-21 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-GAF,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAF 2nd Qtr. Profit Down; Year-Earlier Had One-Time Credits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GAF Corp. reported Wednesday that its second
quarter profit was down sharply from the year-earlier period, when
net income was boosted sharply by one-time gains.
   The Wayne, N.J.-based chemicals and building materials company
had net income of $41.5 million, or $1.45 per share, compared with
a profit of $132.4 million, or $3.71 per share, in second quarter
1987.
   Sales during the quarter rose 24.5 percent, to $266.7 million
from $214.2 million.
   Second quarter 1988 results included one-time gains of $6.1
million, stemming from GAF's holdings of Union Carbide Corp. stock.
Year-earlier results included unique gains of $102.7 million,
including $97 million from the sale of GAF's investment in
Borg-Warner Corp.
   Profit rose by 16.5 percent in GAF's chemicals business during
the quarter, partly due to a weaker U.S. dollar, which helped
international sales, and the inclusion of results from Alkaril
Chemicals Ltd., which GAF acquired in fourth quarter 1987.
   Building materials profit declined by 12.5 percent, due to
increased operating expenses and lower selling prices, GAF said.
   For the first six months of 1988, GAF had net income of $64.2
million, or $2.24 per share, down from $174.1 million, or $4.82 per
share, a year earlier. Sales rose to $483.3 million from $405.3
million.
   First half results included one-time gains of $6.9 million this
year, and $123.8 million in the same period last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
